      "Cranial Nerves"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Abducens Nerve (CN VI)</b> is a somatic <i>motor cranial nerve</i> that originates from the pontomedullary junction and <u>exclusively innervates</u> the [[f7b5ee5d|Lateral Rectus muscle]], which is responsible for abduction of the eye (looking laterally).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Motor innervation to the ipsilateral [[f7b5ee5d|lateral rectus muscle]], enabling abduction (lateral eye movement).</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Exits the brainstem at the pontomedullary junction, traverses the subarachnoid space, passes through the [[c260efc8|cavernous sinus]] near the internal carotid artery, and enters the orbit via the superior orbital fissure.</li><li><b>Palsy Presentation:</b> Damage results in an inability to abduct the affected eye, leading to a medially directed strabismus at rest and horizontal [[9914d433|diplopia]] that worsens on attempted lateral gaze toward the side of the lesion.</li><li><b>Vulnerability:</b> Its long intracranial course makes it highly susceptible to downward traction from <mark>increased intracranial pressure</mark> ([[7c4e7c74|idiopathic intracranial hypertension]], tumors, hydrocephalus).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> An isolated CN VI palsy is often a <mark>\"false localizing sign\"</mark> of elevated ICP rather than a direct brainstem lesion. It is the most commonly affected cranial nerve in [[c260efc8|cavernous sinus syndrome]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Abducens Nerve</b> has the longest intracranial course of all cranial nerves, making it uniquely vulnerable to stretching and compression from <u>increased intracranial pressure</u>, often presenting as a nonlocalizing palsy that signals a generalized brain pressure problem rather than a specific brainstem lesion.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph LR; A[PPRF] --> B[CN VI Nucleus]; B --> C[Ipsilateral Lateral Rectus]; B --> D[Contralateral MLF]; D --> E[Contralateral CN III Nucleus]; E --> F[Contralateral Medial Rectus];"
