    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Abnormal motor posturing</b> refers to involuntary flexion or extension of the arms and legs, indicating <i>severe brain injury</i>. It occurs in patients who are comatose and reflects damage to motor pathways between the cerebral cortex and the brainstem.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Decorticate (Flexor) Posturing:</b> Characterized by flexion of the arms, wrists, and fingers with adduction of the upper extremities, alongside extension, internal rotation, and plantar flexion of the lower extremities. Mnemonic: Hands are near the '<b>cor</b>' (heart).</li><li><b>Decorticate Lesion Level:</b> Indicates damage <u>above the red nucleus</u> in the midbrain, such as in the cerebral hemispheres or internal capsule. The rubrospinal tract (flexor tone) is intact and overrides the vestibulospinal tract.</li><li><b>Decerebrate (Extensor) Posturing:</b> Characterized by extension, adduction, and internal rotation of the arms with extension of the legs.</li><li><b>Decerebrate Lesion Level:</b> Indicates damage <u>at or below the red nucleus</u> (e.g., midbrain tegmentum, pons). The loss of the rubrospinal tract leads to unopposed extension tone from the vestibulospinal tract.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Decerebrate posturing generally indicates a more severe brain injury and carries a <u>worse prognosis</u> than decorticate posturing.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The type of abnormal posturing provides a crucial clue to the anatomical level of severe brain injury; <b>decorticate</b> posturing implies a lesion above the red nucleus preserving flexor pathways, whereas <b>decerebrate</b> posturing signifies a more caudal lesion below the red nucleus, leaving only extensor pathways unopposed.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Cerebral Cortex] --> B[Red Nucleus]; B --> C[Rubrospinal Tract Flexion]; A --> D[Vestibular Nuclei]; D --> E[Vestibulospinal Tract Extension]; F(Lesion Above Red Nucleus) --> G{Decorticate}; B --x F; H(Lesion Below Red Nucleus) --> I{Decerebrate}; C --x H;"
    },
