    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Absence seizures</b>, formerly known as <i>petit mal seizures</i>, are a type of generalized seizure characterized by a sudden, brief lapse of consciousness without loss of postural tone, typically lasting for seconds. They are most common in childhood and are often mistaken for daydreaming or inattentiveness.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Sudden cessation of activity with a blank stare, lasting about 10 seconds. May be accompanied by subtle automatisms like eyelid fluttering or lip smacking. There is <u>no postictal confusion</u>; the patient immediately returns to baseline.</li><li><b>EEG Hallmark:</b> The pathognomonic finding is a <mark>generalized 3 Hz spike-and-wave discharge</mark> on EEG.</li><li><b>Provocation:</b> Seizures can often be triggered by <mark>hyperventilation</mark>.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> <u>First-line</u> treatment is [[ethosuximide]]. [[valproic_acid|Valproic acid]] is also effective and used if tonic-clonic seizures are also present.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A classic vignette describes a child whose teacher complains of 'daydreaming' or 'not paying attention' in class. The diagnosis is confirmed by a 3 Hz spike-and-wave pattern on EEG, often induced by having the child hyperventilate.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Absence seizures</b> are unique among generalized seizures for their brief, non-convulsive nature, lack of postictal confusion, and a pathognomonic <mark>3 Hz spike-and-wave</mark> EEG pattern, making [[ethosuximide]] the specific and preferred treatment.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Thalamic T-type Ca2+ Channels] -- Overactivity --> B(Absence Seizure); C(Ethosuximide) -- Blocks --> A;"
    },
    "connections": [
