    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Acalculia</b> is an acquired neurological deficit characterized by the <i>inability to perform simple mathematical calculations</i>, resulting from damage to specific brain regions, most notably the dominant (usually left) parietal lobe.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Localization:</b> Acalculia is a key localizing sign for a lesion in the <mark>dominant angular gyrus</mark> of the parietal lobe.</li><li><b>Associated Syndrome:</b> It is one of the four classic components of [[38f3ed1f|Gerstmann syndrome]].</li><li><b>Gerstmann Syndrome Tetrad:</b> The full syndrome includes <b>Acalculia</b>, <b>Agraphia</b> (inability to write), <b>Finger Agnosia</b> (inability to distinguish fingers), and <b>Left-Right Disorientation</b>.</li><li><b>Vascular Territory:</b> These symptoms often result from a stroke in the territory of the [[143bb23d|Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)]] that supplies the dominant parietal lobe.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> When a patient presents with difficulty with calculations along with any of the other components of Gerstmann syndrome, immediately suspect a lesion in the dominant parietal lobe.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Acalculia</b> is more than just 'bad at math'; it is a specific neurological sign that strongly points to a lesion in the dominant angular gyrus, often as part of the clinically distinct [[38f3ed1f|Gerstmann syndrome]].</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
