      "Cranial Nerves"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Accessory Nerve (CN XI)</b> is a <i>motor cranial nerve</i> that provides innervation to the <u>sternocleidomastoid (SCM)</u> and <u>trapezius</u> muscles, which are crucial for head turning and shoulder shrugging, respectively.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Innervates the ipsilateral <b>Sternocleidomastoid (SCM)</b> muscle, which turns the head to the contralateral side, and the ipsilateral <b>Trapezius</b> muscle, which elevates and stabilizes the scapula (shoulder shrug).</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Uniquely arises from both the brainstem (medulla) and the spinal cord (C1-C5). The spinal root ascends through the foramen magnum to join the cranial root, and the combined nerve then exits the skull via the [[jugular_foramen|jugular foramen]].</li><li><b>Lesion Presentation (SCM):</b> Weakness in turning the head <u>away</u> from the side of the lesion. (e.g., Left CN XI lesion causes weakness turning head to the right).</li><li><b>Lesion Presentation (Trapezius):</b> <mark>Shoulder droop</mark>, weakness in shrugging the shoulder on the ipsilateral side, and winging of the scapula.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A common iatrogenic cause of an isolated CN XI lesion is injury during procedures in the <mark>posterior triangle of the neck</mark>, such as lymph node biopsy.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Accessory Nerve (CN XI)</b> is unique in its dual origin from both the medulla and cervical spinal cord, and a lesion presents with the distinct combination of weakness turning the head to the contralateral side and an ipsilateral shoulder droop.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[CN XI Nuclei Medulla & C1-C5] --> B(CN XI); B --> C[Exits via Jugular Foramen]; C --> D[Innervates SCM]; C --> E[Innervates Trapezius];"
