  "ed52e40b": {
    "title": "Acute Inflammatory Demyelinating Polyneuropathy (AIDP)",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Immunology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Peripheral Neuropathies"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Acute Inflammatory Demyelinating Polyneuropathy (AIDP)</b> is the most common subtype of <i>Guillain-Barr√© Syndrome</i>, an autoimmune condition characterized by the rapid onset of symmetric, ascending muscle weakness or paralysis and destruction of myelin sheaths of peripheral nerves by Schwann cells.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Often triggered by an antecedent infection (classically <mark>Campylobacter jejuni</mark>, also CMV, EBV, Zika). It is thought to be due to <mark>molecular mimicry</mark> between microbial antigens and peripheral nerve myelin or axons.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Rapidly progressive, symmetric <mark>ascending weakness/paralysis</mark> starting in the lower extremities. Patients often have absent or depressed deep tendon reflexes.</li><li><b>Key Complications:</b> Respiratory failure due to diaphragmatic weakness is a life-threatening complication. Autonomic dysfunction (tachycardia, arrhythmias, BP instability) is also common.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> CSF analysis shows <mark>albuminocytologic dissociation</mark> (high protein with a normal cell count). Nerve conduction studies show slowed nerve conduction velocity.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of recent diarrheal illness (*C. jejuni*) followed by ascending paralysis and high protein in the CSF with normal cell count is a classic vignette for Guillain-Barr√© Syndrome.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>AIDP (Guillain-Barr√© Syndrome)</b> is an acute, post-infectious autoimmune attack on peripheral nerve myelin, leading to a characteristic ascending paralysis; the hallmark diagnostic finding is <mark>albuminocytologic dissociation</mark> in the CSF, reflecting widespread inflammation of nerve roots without direct infection.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Antecedent Infection e.g., C. jejuni] --> B(Molecular Mimicry); B --> C[Immune Attack on Schwann Cells/Myelin]; C --> D[Peripheral Nerve Demyelination]; D --> E[Ascending Paralysis & Areflexia];"
    },
