        "to": "acute_respiratory_distress_syndrome"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_treated_with",
        "to": "naloxone"
      }
    ]
  },
  "76ba7f2e": {
    "title": "Adenohypophysis (Anterior Pituitary)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Endocrinology",
      "Anatomy",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Endocrine",
      "Anatomy",
      "Pituitary Gland"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Adenohypophysis</b>, or anterior pituitary, is the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland, an endocrine gland of ectodermal origin (from <i>Rathke's pouch</i>) that synthesizes and secretes six major peptide hormones in response to releasing and inhibiting hormones from the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Embryology:</b> Arises from an upward evagination of the oral ectoderm called <mark>Rathke's pouch</mark>. Remnants can form a [[7048db1e|craniopharyngioma]].</li><li><b>Hormones Secreted:</b> The anterior pituitary hormones can be remembered with the mnemonic <b>FLAT PiG</b>: <b>F</b>SH, <b>L</b>H, <b>A</b>CTH, <b>T</b>SH (Tropic hormones), and <b>P</b>rolactin, <b>i</b>(ignore), <b>G</b>H (Direct hormones).</li><li><b>Cell Types:</b> Somatotrophs (GH), Lactotrophs (Prolactin), Corticotrophs (ACTH), Thyrotrophs (TSH), and Gonadotrophs (FSH/LH).</li><li><b>Vascular Supply:</b> Receives blood from the superior hypophyseal artery, which forms a portal system (hypothalamic-hypophyseal portal system) that transports hypothalamic releasing/inhibiting hormones directly to the anterior pituitary.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The most common tumor of the pituitary is a [[5f3188bd|pituitary adenoma]], which is most frequently a prolactinoma. Its connection to the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]] is vascular, in contrast to the posterior pituitary's neural connection.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Adenohypophysis</b> is the hormonal powerhouse of the pituitary, controlled by the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]] via a unique portal venous system, and its diverse cell populations are responsible for regulating growth, stress, reproduction, and metabolism throughout the body.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Hypothalamus] --Releasing/Inhibiting Hormones--> B(Hypophyseal Portal System); B --> C(Adenohypophysis); C --> D[FSH, LH]; C --> E[ACTH]; C --> F[TSH]; C --> G[Prolactin]; C --> H[GH];"
    },
    "connections": [
