      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Microbiology:</b> Gram-negative coccobacillus. Requires both <mark>factor X (hematin)</mark> and <mark>factor V (NAD+)</mark> for growth, which are present in chocolate agar.</li><li><b>Neurological Infections:</b> A common cause of bacterial [[meningitis]] in children (age 6 months to 5 years) before the Hib vaccine. Also a major cause of [[a03641af|otitis media]], sinusitis, and epiglottitis.</li><li><b>Virulence:</b> The type b strain has a polyribosylribitol phosphate (PRP) polysaccharide capsule, which is antiphagocytic and is the target of the Hib conjugate vaccine.</li><li><b>Vaccination:</b> The Hib conjugate vaccine, which conjugates the PRP capsule to a protein carrier (like tetanus toxoid), has dramatically reduced the incidence of invasive H. influenzae disease.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> In a vignette about an unvaccinated child with meningitis, fever, and a stiff neck, <i>H. influenzae</i> type b should be a top differential. Remember it grows on <mark>chocolate agar</mark> but not blood agar.</li></ul>",
