    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Hearing loss</b> is a partial or total inability to hear, classified as either <i>conductive</i>, involving problems with the outer or middle ear, or <i>sensorineural</i>, involving damage to the inner ear (cochlea) or the auditory nerve pathway to the brain.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Conductive Hearing Loss:</b> Occurs when sound waves are not conducted efficiently to the inner ear. Causes include cerumen impaction, [[a03641af|otitis media]], otosclerosis, or tympanic membrane perforation.</li><li><b>Sensorineural Hearing Loss:</b> Caused by damage to the hair cells in the cochlea or the vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII). Causes include <mark>presbycusis</mark> (age-related), noise-induced damage, ototoxic drugs (e.g., aminoglycosides, cisplatin, loop diuretics), and acoustic neuromas ([[03ecb69e|schwannomas]]).</li><li><b>Diagnosis (Weber Test):</b> Tuning fork on vertex of skull. Conductive loss: lateralizes to the affected ear. Sensorineural loss: lateralizes to the unaffected ear.</li><li><b>Diagnosis (Rinne Test):</b> Compares air conduction (AC) to bone conduction (BC). Normal/Sensorineural: AC > BC. Conductive: <mark>BC > AC</mark>.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the diagnostic pattern. In conductive loss, the Weber test lateralizes <i>towards</i> the bad ear because it masks ambient noise, making bone conduction seem louder.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The differentiation between <b>conductive</b> and <b>sensorineural</b> hearing loss is critical for diagnosis; conductive loss is a mechanical problem of sound transmission (BC > AC on Rinne), while sensorineural loss is a nerve problem of sound transduction (AC > BC, but both are reduced).</p>",
