      "definition": "<p><b>Heat stroke</b> is a life-threatening medical emergency characterized by a core body temperature above 40¬∞C (104¬∞F) and central nervous system dysfunction, resulting from the failure of the body's thermoregulatory mechanisms.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Occurs when heat generation exceeds the body's ability to dissipate heat. This leads to systemic inflammation, multiorgan dysfunction, and CNS abnormalities. Unlike fever, the hypothalamic set-point is <u>not</u> elevated.</li><li><b>Types:</b> <b>Exertional</b> (occurs in healthy individuals during strenuous physical activity in hot/humid conditions) and <b>Non-exertional/Classic</b> (affects sedentary individuals, elderly, or chronically ill during heat waves).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Core temperature >40¬∞C, <mark>altered mental status</mark> (confusion, delirium, coma, seizures), and often, but not always, anhidrosis (absence of sweating), particularly in non-exertional heat stroke.</li><li><b>Management:</b> <u>Immediate rapid cooling</u> is the cornerstone of treatment (e.g., ice water immersion). Antipyretics like acetaminophen or NSAIDs are <u>ineffective</u> because the hypothalamic set-point is not altered.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from fever: in heat stroke, the cause is external heat load overwhelming thermoregulation, and antipyretics do not work. In fever, the cause is an elevated hypothalamic set-point due to pyrogens, and antipyretics are effective.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Heat stroke</b> is a failure of thermoregulation, not a change in the hypothalamic set-point. Therefore, the critical intervention is rapid physical cooling, as antipyretics that target the hypothalamus are completely ineffective.</p>",
