      "definition": "<p>A <b>Hemangioblastoma</b> is a benign, highly vascular tumor of the central nervous system, typically arising in the cerebellum, brainstem, or spinal cord, and is strongly associated with <i>von Hippel-Lindau disease</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Most often found in the <mark>cerebellum</mark>.</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> Appears as a well-circumscribed, cystic lesion with a brightly enhancing <mark>mural nodule</mark>.</li><li><b>Histology:</b> Composed of closely arranged, thin-walled capillaries with intervening stromal cells that have clear, lipid-rich cytoplasm.</li><li><b>Paraneoplastic Syndrome:</b> The tumor can ectopically produce <mark>erythropoietin (EPO)</mark>, leading to secondary polycythemia.</li><li><b>Genetic Association:</b> A hallmark of [[274cb033|von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) disease]], an autosomal dominant disorder. The presence of a hemangioblastoma should prompt investigation for other VHL-associated tumors (e.g., renal cell carcinoma, pheochromocytoma).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient with cerebellar symptoms (ataxia, dysmetria) and polycythemia should make you think of a hemangioblastoma. If there's a family history of similar tumors or renal cancer, suspect VHL.</li></ul>",
