    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Hemianopia</b> (or hemianopsia) is a visual field defect characterized by the loss of vision in <i>half of the visual field</i> of one or both eyes. The pattern of vision loss is critical for localizing lesions along the visual pathway.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Bitemporal Hemianopia:</b> Loss of the outer (temporal) half of the visual field in both eyes. Caused by a lesion compressing the <mark>optic chiasm</mark> (e.g., [[5f3188bd|pituitary adenoma]], [[7048db1e|craniopharyngioma]], ACom aneurysm).</li><li><b>Homonymous Hemianopia:</b> Loss of the same half (e.g., both right halves or both left halves) of the visual field in both eyes. Caused by a lesion <u>posterior</u> to the optic chiasm (e.g., optic tract, lateral geniculate nucleus, optic radiations, or visual cortex).</li><li><b>Macular Sparing:</b> In homonymous hemianopia caused by a [[b6a2cc31|Posterior Cerebral Artery (PCA)]] stroke, central vision may be spared due to dual blood supply to the occipital pole from the [[143bb23d|Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)]].</li><li><b>Quadrantanopia:</b> Loss of one quadrant of the visual field. A lesion in the temporal lobe (Meyer's loop) causes a contralateral superior quadrantanopia (\"pie in the sky\"). A lesion in the parietal lobe (Dorsal optic radiation) causes a contralateral inferior quadrantanopia (\"pie on the floor\").</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the crossing pattern: fibers from the nasal retina (representing the temporal visual field) cross at the chiasm. Therefore, a midline chiasmal lesion affects both temporal fields.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The pattern of <b>hemianopia</b> is a precise roadmap to the location of a neurological lesion: a bitemporal defect points directly to the optic chiasm, while a homonymous defect indicates a lesion anywhere from the optic tract back to the visual cortex.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Optic Chiasm Lesion] --> B(Bitemporal Hemianopia); C[Post-Chiasmal Lesion] --> D(Homonymous Hemianopia);"
