    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Hemiballismus</b> is a rare hyperkinetic movement disorder characterized by <i>wild, flinging, large-amplitude movements</i> of the proximal arm and leg on one side of the body, resulting from a lesion in the contralateral subthalamic nucleus.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> A lesion in the <mark>contralateral subthalamic nucleus (STN)</mark> disrupts the indirect pathway of the [[ed462927|basal ganglia]]. This leads to decreased inhibition of the thalamus, resulting in excessive, uncontrolled movements.</li><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly caused by a <mark>lacunar stroke</mark> affecting the small penetrating arteries that supply the STN. Other causes include hemorrhage, tumors, or hyperglycemia.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Sudden onset of violent, involuntary, flinging movements of one arm and/or leg. Mnemonic: In <b>hemi</b>ballismus, <b>half</b> of the body is going <b>ballistic</b>.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Often self-limiting, resolving over weeks to months. Symptomatic treatment can include dopamine antagonists (e.g., haloperidol) to reduce the hyperkinetic movements.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A sudden onset of wild, unilateral flinging movements in an elderly patient with a history of hypertension strongly suggests a lacunar stroke in the contralateral subthalamic nucleus.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Hemiballismus</b> is a dramatic clinical sign that precisely localizes a lesion to the contralateral subthalamic nucleus, demonstrating the critical role of the basal ganglia's indirect pathway in suppressing unwanted movements.</p>",
