    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Hemiparesis</b> (weakness on one side of the body) can be a devastating consequence of a ruptured <i>saccular (berry) aneurysm</i>, typically resulting from ischemic damage to motor pathways secondary to vasospasm or direct parenchymal hemorrhage.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism 1 (Vasospasm):</b> After a [[63f8b05f|subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH)]] from a ruptured aneurysm, breakdown products of blood can irritate cerebral arteries, causing severe vasoconstriction (vasospasm) days later. This can lead to an ischemic stroke.</li><li><b>Mechanism 2 (Intraparenchymal Extension):</b> A rupturing aneurysm can bleed directly into the brain parenchyma, causing a hemorrhagic stroke and direct damage to motor tracts.</li><li><b>Localization (ACom Aneurysm):</b> Rupture of an <mark>Anterior Communicating Artery</mark> aneurysm can cause vasospasm of the [[830c856c|Anterior Cerebral Artery (ACA)]], leading to contralateral leg-predominant hemiparesis.</li><li><b>Localization (MCA Aneurysm):</b> Rupture of a <mark>Middle Cerebral Artery</mark> aneurysm can cause vasospasm or direct hemorrhage into the MCA territory, leading to contralateral face and arm-predominant hemiparesis.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> If a patient presents with a \"thunderclap headache\" and then develops focal weakness a few days later, think vasospasm secondary to a ruptured saccular aneurysm.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Hemiparesis following a saccular aneurysm rupture is often not from the initial bleed itself, but rather a delayed ischemic stroke caused by severe vasospasm, a dangerous secondary complication of subarachnoid blood.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Saccular Aneurysm Rupture] --> B(Subarachnoid Hemorrhage); B --> C(Cerebral Vasospasm); C --> D(Ischemic Stroke); D --> E(Hemiparesis);"
    },
    "connections": [
