      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Spinal Cord Lesions"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Spinal Cord Hemisection</b>, clinically known as <b>Brown-S√©quard Syndrome</b>, is a neurological condition resulting from damage to one half of the spinal cord, leading to a classic pattern of <i>ipsilateral motor and proprioceptive loss</i> and <i>contralateral pain and temperature loss</i> below the level of the lesion.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly caused by penetrating trauma (e.g., stab wound, gunshot), but can also result from tumors, ischemia, or infection.</li><li><b>Ipsilateral Deficits (at and below lesion):</b> Loss of all sensation at the level of the lesion. Below the lesion: UMN signs (spastic paralysis from corticospinal tract damage) and loss of proprioception, vibration, and fine touch (from [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal column]] damage).</li><li><b>Contralateral Deficits (below lesion):</b> Loss of pain and temperature sensation (from spinothalamic tract damage). This begins 1-2 segments below the lesion because the spinothalamic tract fibers cross in the anterior white commissure over several segments.</li><li><b>At the Level of the Lesion:</b> Ipsilateral LMN signs (flaccid paralysis from anterior horn damage) and complete loss of sensation in the affected dermatome.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The key to identifying Brown-S√©quard is the dissociated sensory loss: loss of proprioception/vibration on the same side as the weakness, and loss of pain/temperature on the opposite side.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Brown-S√©quard Syndrome</b> is the quintessential example of how spinal cord anatomy dictates clinical findings; the ipsilateral deficits are due to tracts that have not yet crossed (corticospinal, dorsal columns), while the contralateral deficit is due to the spinothalamic tract which has already crossed at the spinal level.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Spinal Cord Hemisection at T10]; A --> B(Ipsilateral Deficits at T10); B --> B1[LMN Paralysis]; B --> B2[Loss of All Sensation]; A --> C(Ipsilateral Deficits below T10); C --> C1[UMN Paralysis - Corticospinal Tract]; C --> C2[Loss of Proprioception/Vibration - Dorsal Columns]; A --> D(Contralateral Deficits below T10); D --> D1[Loss of Pain/Temp - Spinothalamic Tract];"
    },
