  "dc54f7a6": {
    "title": "Hemispatial Neglect Syndrome",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Cognitive Deficit",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brain Lesions"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Hemispatial Neglect Syndrome</b>, also known as hemineglect, is a neuropsychological condition in which a patient is unaware of and fails to respond to stimuli on the side of space <i>contralateral</i> to a brain lesion, despite having intact sensory and motor function. This is a deficit of attention, not sensation.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Localization:</b> Most commonly caused by a lesion in the <mark>non-dominant (usually right) parietal lobe</mark>, specifically the angular gyrus.</li><li><b>Etiology:</b> Often results from a stroke in the territory of the right [[143bb23d|Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)]].</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients may ignore food on the left side of their plate, only shave or apply makeup to the right side of their face, or bump into objects on their left. When asked to draw a clock, they may cram all the numbers onto the right side.</li><li><b>Distinction:</b> It is an <b>attention</b> deficit, not a primary visual field defect like hemianopia. Patients with pure hemianopia are aware of their deficit, whereas patients with neglect are often unaware (anosognosia).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient who has had a stroke and now ignores one side of their body or environment (e.g., only draws the right half of a house) is the classic presentation. The lesion is in the contralateral parietal lobe.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Hemispatial Neglect Syndrome</b> is a profound deficit of attention, not vision, that localizes a lesion to the non-dominant parietal lobe. The patient's brain effectively 'deletes' one half of their universe, a concept distinct from simply being unable to see it.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
