  "dcfdcc1d": {
    "title": "Intracranial Hemorrhage",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Neurosurgery",
      "Vascular",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Cerebrovascular Disease"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Intracranial Hemorrhage</b> is bleeding within the cranial vault, which can be classified based on its location into <i>epidural</i>, <i>subdural</i>, <i>subarachnoid</i>, and <i>intraparenchymal</i> types. It is a neurological emergency that can lead to increased intracranial pressure and brain herniation.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Epidural Hematoma:</b> Arterial bleed (middle meningeal artery) between dura and skull. <mark>Lens-shaped (biconvex)</mark> on CT, does not cross suture lines. Often associated with temporal bone fracture and a 'lucid interval.'</li><li><b>Subdural Hematoma:</b> Venous bleed (bridging veins) between dura and arachnoid. <mark>Crescent-shaped</mark> on CT, crosses suture lines. Seen in elderly, alcoholics, and shaken babies.</li><li><b>Subarachnoid Hemorrhage:</b> Bleeding into the CSF space between arachnoid and pia. Presents with \"worst headache of my life.\" Caused by ruptured [[a1647fb2|saccular aneurysm]] or trauma. Blood seen in sulci and cisterns on CT.</li><li><b>Intraparenchymal Hemorrhage:</b> Bleeding within the brain parenchyma. Commonly caused by systemic hypertension (affecting basal ganglia, thalamus, pons), amyloid angiopathy, or tumors.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The shape on non-contrast CT is key for differentiation: Epidural = <b>L</b>ens-shaped (<b>L</b>ucid interval). Subdural = <b>C</b>rescent-shaped (<b>C</b>hronic/<b>C</b>rosses sutures).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The anatomical location of an <b>intracranial hemorrhage</b> dictates its characteristic appearance on CT and its clinical course; arterial epidural hematomas expand rapidly and are highly lethal, whereas venous subdural hematomas can be acute or chronic with a more variable presentation.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
