    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Hepatotoxicity</b> is a significant adverse effect of several <i>anticonvulsant drugs</i>, ranging from asymptomatic elevation of liver enzymes to acute liver failure, necessitating careful monitoring and drug selection.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Valproic Acid:</b> The most notorious for hepatotoxicity. Can cause a rare but fatal <mark>microvesicular steatosis</mark> and hepatic failure, especially in children <2 years old and those on multiple anticonvulsants. Requires regular LFT monitoring.</li><li><b>Carbamazepine:</b> Can cause a spectrum of liver injury, including cholestatic or hepatocellular patterns. Agranulocytosis and aplastic anemia are other major concerns.</li><li><b>Phenytoin:</b> Can cause a hypersensitivity reaction known as DRESS syndrome, which may include hepatitis. Can also cause a dose-dependent elevation in liver enzymes.</li><li><b>Phenobarbital:</b> Induces cytochrome P450 enzymes, which can alter the metabolism of other drugs and potentially produce toxic metabolites, though direct hepatotoxicity is less common than with valproate.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> For a patient on an anticonvulsant who develops jaundice, nausea, and markedly elevated AST/ALT, [[valproic_acid|Valproic acid]]-induced hepatotoxicity should be at the top of the differential, especially in a young child.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>While several anticonvulsants can affect the liver, <b>valproic acid</b> stands out for its potential to cause fatal hepatotoxicity through mitochondrial injury and impaired fatty acid metabolism, a risk that is highest in young children with metabolic disorders.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
