      "Peripheral Neuropathies"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Hereditary Motor and Sensory Neuropathy (HMSN)</b>, more commonly known as <b>Charcot-Marie-Tooth (CMT) disease</b>, is a group of inherited disorders affecting the <i>peripheral nerves</i>, leading to progressive muscle weakness, atrophy, and sensory loss, predominantly in the distal extremities.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Genetics:</b> Genetically heterogeneous, with autosomal dominant inheritance being most common. The most frequent type, CMT1A, is caused by a <mark>duplication of the PMP22 gene</mark>.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Involves defective production of proteins involved in the structure and function of either peripheral nerve axons or their myelin sheath. CMT1 is a demyelinating form, while CMT2 is an axonal form.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Classic findings include distal leg weakness leading to <mark>foot drop</mark> and a 'steppage gait.' Over time, muscle atrophy in the lower legs creates an <mark>\"inverted champagne bottle\"</mark> or \"stork leg\" appearance. Foot deformities like <i>pes cavus</i> (high arches) and hammer toes are common.</li><li><b>Sensory Loss:</b> Patients typically experience loss of proprioception and vibration sense in the distal extremities.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A young patient presenting with progressive distal weakness, foot drop, high-arched feet (pes cavus), and a family history of similar symptoms is the classic vignette for Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease</b> is the most common inherited peripheral neuropathy, characterized by a length-dependent degeneration of peripheral nerves that manifests clinically as a classic 'stork leg' deformity due to profound distal muscle atrophy.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[PMP22 Gene Duplication] --> B(Defective Myelin); B --> C(Demyelination of Peripheral Nerves); C --> D[Distal Muscle Weakness & Atrophy]; D --> E(Foot Drop & Pes Cavus);"
