      "definition": "<p><b>Pseudomonas aeruginosa</b> is an encapsulated, gram-negative, oxidase-positive rod known for causing a range of opportunistic infections, including <i>otitis externa</i> (swimmer's ear) and its severe, invasive form, malignant otitis externa.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Microbiology:</b> Gram-negative rod, aerobic, motile, oxidase-positive, and produces a characteristic blue-green (pyocyanin) pigment and a grape-like odor.</li><li><b>Otitis Externa (\"Swimmer's Ear\"):</b> A common cause of infection of the external auditory canal, particularly in settings of water exposure which macerates the skin.</li><li><b>Malignant Otitis Externa:</b> A severe, necrotizing infection that spreads from the external ear canal to the skull base, causing osteomyelitis of the temporal bone. This is a <mark>neurosurgical emergency</mark>.</li><li><b>Risk Factors for Malignant OE:</b> Classically seen in <mark>elderly diabetic patients</mark> and other immunocompromised individuals.</li><li><b>Presentation of Malignant OE:</b> Presents with exquisite otalgia (ear pain), purulent otorrhea, and the presence of granulation tissue in the ear canal. It can progress to involve cranial nerves, most commonly the [[dea9755f|facial nerve (CN VII)]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A vignette describing an elderly patient with poorly controlled diabetes, severe ear pain, and granulation tissue in the auditory canal is pathognomonic for malignant otitis externa caused by <i>Pseudomonas aeruginosa</i>.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>While <b>Pseudomonas aeruginosa</b> is a frequent cause of benign swimmer's ear, in the specific context of an elderly diabetic patient, it can cause a life-threatening invasive infection, malignant otitis externa, which erodes into the skull base and can cause cranial nerve palsies.</p>",
