      "definition": "<p><b>Psychogenic Nonepileptic Events (PNES)</b> are paroxysmal episodes that resemble epileptic [[64c08e92|seizures]] but are a manifestation of <i>psychological distress</i> rather than abnormal cortical electrical discharges, and are therefore not associated with epileptiform activity on an electroencephalogram (EEG).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Clinical Features:</b> Episodes often involve asynchronous, thrashing limb movements, side-to-side head shaking, pelvic thrusting, and <mark>forceful, prolonged eye closure</mark>. Vocalizations during the event are common.</li><li><b>Key Differentiators:</b> Compared to epileptic seizures, PNES episodes are often prolonged (> 2 minutes), consciousness may be preserved despite bilateral motor activity, and there is typically <u>no postictal confusion</u>. Self-injury is less common.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> The gold standard for diagnosis is <mark>video-EEG monitoring</mark> to capture a typical event and demonstrate the absence of corresponding epileptiform brain activity during the seizure-like behavior.</li><li><b>Associated Conditions:</b> High comorbidity with other psychiatric disorders, particularly post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), depression, anxiety, and personality disorders. A history of trauma or abuse is common.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Look for a patient with a psychiatric history presenting with dramatic, prolonged \"seizures\" where the eyes are <mark>forcefully closed</mark> (resisting opening), which is uncharacteristic of a true tonic-clonic seizure where eyes are typically open.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>PNES</b> are a physical manifestation of psychological distress, not a brain electrical disorder. The diagnosis hinges on capturing an event on video-EEG and observing seizure-like behavior without any underlying abnormal brain waves, distinguishing it from true epilepsy.</p>",
