    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Pupil</b> is the aperture in the center of the iris of the eye that allows light to enter and reach the retina. Its diameter is dynamically controlled by the iris muscles to regulate the amount of light entering the eye and to improve depth of focus.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Miosis (Constriction):</b> Mediated by the parasympathetic nervous system via the [[68c66997|oculomotor nerve (CN III)]]. The sphincter pupillae muscle contracts.</li><li><b>Mydriasis (Dilation):</b> Mediated by the sympathetic nervous system. The dilator pupillae muscle contracts.</li><li><b>Pupillary Light Reflex:</b> Afferent limb is the [[optic_nerve|Optic Nerve (CN II)]]; efferent limb is the [[68c66997|Oculomotor Nerve (CN III)]]. Light shone in one eye causes bilateral pupillary constriction (direct and consensual responses).</li><li><b>Relative Afferent Pupillary Defect (RAPD):</b> Also known as a Marcus Gunn pupil. A sign of optic nerve or severe retinal disease. When a light is swung from the normal to the affected eye, both pupils paradoxically dilate.</li><li><b>CN III Palsy:</b> A compressive lesion (e.g., PCom aneurysm) often causes a dilated, nonreactive pupil (<mark>\"blown pupil\"</mark>) due to compression of superficial parasympathetic fibers. Ischemic palsies often spare the pupil.</li></ul>",
