    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Pupillary Light Reflex</b> is an involuntary reflex that controls the diameter of the pupil in response to the intensity of light, allowing the eye to adapt to varying light levels and protecting the retina from damage by constricting the pupil.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Afferent Limb:</b> [[optic_nerve|Optic Nerve (CN II)]] senses the light stimulus.</li><li><b>Efferent Limb:</b> [[68c66997|Oculomotor Nerve (CN III)]] carries the parasympathetic motor command to constrict the pupil.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Light signal travels via CN II to the pretectal nucleus in the midbrain, which projects bilaterally to the Edinger-Westphal nuclei. From there, parasympathetic fibers travel with CN III to the ciliary ganglion, and then via short ciliary nerves to the sphincter pupillae muscle.</li><li><b>Responses:</b> The constriction of the pupil in the eye exposed to light is the <i>direct</i> response. The simultaneous constriction of the contralateral pupil is the <i>consensual</i> response, due to the bilateral projections from the pretectal nucleus.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A lesion of CN II in one eye will abolish both direct and consensual reflexes when light is shone in that eye. A lesion of CN III will abolish the direct reflex in the affected eye, but the consensual reflex in that eye (when light is shone in the other eye) will be intact.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The bilateral projection from the pretectal nucleus to both Edinger-Westphal nuclei is the anatomical basis for the consensual pupillary light reflex, meaning that a unilateral light stimulus results in a bilateral motor response, a crucial feature for localizing lesions in the reflex arc.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Light Stimulus] --> B(Retina); B --> C(CN II - Afferent); C --> D(Pretectal Nucleus); D --> E(Bilateral Edinger-Westphal Nuclei); E --> F(CN III - Efferent); F --> G(Sphincter Pupillae); G --> H(Pupillary Constriction);"
