    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>Pure Motor Stroke</b> is a common type of <i>lacunar stroke syndrome</i> characterized by unilateral weakness (hemiparesis) of the face, arm, and leg, <u>without</u> any associated sensory, visual, or cognitive deficits (i.e., no cortical signs).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Caused by a small, ischemic infarct (&lt;1.5 cm) in the deep penetrating arteries of the brain, most commonly the <mark>lenticulostriate arteries</mark>, which are branches of the [[143bb23d|MCA]].</li><li><b>Anatomical Location:</b> The lesion is typically located in the contralateral <mark>posterior limb of the internal capsule</mark> or the pons, where descending corticospinal and corticobulbar tracts are densely packed.</li><li><b>Etiology:</b> Strongly associated with chronic [[hypertension]], which leads to lipohyalinosis and microatheroma of the small vessels.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Sudden onset of contralateral weakness affecting the face, arm, and leg relatively equally. There are <u>no cortical signs</u> such as aphasia, neglect, or visual field cuts.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient with long-standing hypertension who develops unilateral weakness of the face, arm, and leg *without any sensory loss or other cortical signs* is the classic vignette for a pure motor lacunar stroke.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The \"pure\" nature of a <b>Pure Motor Stroke</b> is its key diagnostic feature, precisely localizing the small lacunar infarct to a subcortical structure like the internal capsule, where motor fibers are tightly bundled together, separate from sensory and cognitive pathways.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Hypertension] --> B(Lipohyalinosis of Lenticulostriate Arteries); B --> C(Lacunar Infarct); C --> D(Lesion in Posterior Limb of Internal Capsule); D --> E(Pure Motor Hemiparesis);"
