      "definition": "<p><b>Pyramidal Tract Demyelination</b> refers to the loss of myelin sheaths from the axons of the corticospinal tracts, a key pathological feature in diseases like [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]], leading to upper motor neuron signs.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Affected Tract:</b> The corticospinal (pyramidal) tracts, which are the major motor pathways responsible for voluntary movement.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> In [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]], autoimmune-mediated inflammation targets and destroys [[a24f9747|oligodendrocytes]], leading to plaques of demyelination in the CNS white matter, including the corticospinal tracts.</li><li><b>Clinical Manifestations:</b> Results in <mark>upper motor neuron (UMN) signs</mark> below the level of the lesion, including spasticity, hyperreflexia, a positive Babinski sign, and weakness (spastic paresis).</li><li><b>Presentation in MS:</b> Patients may present with paraparesis (weakness in both legs) if there are demyelinating plaques in the spinal cord, or hemiparesis if a plaque is located in the brainstem or cerebrum.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The presence of UMN signs in a young adult, especially when occurring in a relapsing-remitting pattern, is highly suggestive of [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Demyelination of the pyramidal tracts in [[45dd6d19|MS]] disrupts the normal inhibitory signals from the brain to the spinal cord, unmasking spinal reflexes and leading to the characteristic upper motor neuron syndrome of spastic weakness.</p>",
