      "Parkinson Disease Drugs"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Rasagiline</b> is an <i>irreversible inhibitor of monoamine oxidase B (MAO-B)</i> used for the treatment of [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]], which increases the levels of dopamine in the brain by preventing its breakdown.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Selectively and irreversibly inhibits MAO-B, the enzyme primarily responsible for breaking down [[90adc821|dopamine]] in the brain. This leads to increased synaptic dopamine levels, prolonging the action of both endogenous and exogenous (from levodopa) dopamine.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Can be used as monotherapy in early [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]] to provide mild symptomatic benefit, or as an adjunct to levodopa in more advanced disease to reduce \"off\" time and motor fluctuations.</li><li><b>Selectivity:</b> Its selectivity for MAO-B over MAO-A at therapeutic doses reduces the risk of hypertensive crisis (the \"cheese effect\") associated with non-selective MAO inhibitors, although caution is still advised with tyramine-rich foods at higher doses.</li><li><b>Comparison:</b> Similar to [[selegiline]], but it is more potent and does not have amphetamine metabolites, which may cause insomnia.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that MAO-<b>B</b> inhibitors like rasagiline and selegiline preferentially act on dopamine in the <b>B</b>rain.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Rasagiline</b> provides symptomatic relief in [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]] by a targeted mechanism: it specifically blocks MAO-B, the primary enzyme for dopamine degradation in the brain, thereby boosting dopaminergic neurotransmission without the significant dietary restrictions of older, non-selective MAO inhibitors.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Dopamine] --MAO-B--> B(DOPAC - Inactive Metabolite); C[Rasagiline] --|Inhibits|--> D(MAO-B);"
    },
