    "title": "Wernicke Aphasia (Receptive Aphasia)",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pathology",
      "Stroke",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Aphasias"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Wernicke aphasia</b>, also known as <i>receptive or fluent aphasia</i>, is a language disorder characterized by severely impaired language comprehension, with speech that is fluent and grammatically correct but is nonsensical, empty, and often contains neologisms and paraphasic errors.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Localization:</b> Caused by a lesion in <mark>Wernicke's area</mark>, located in the posterior superior temporal gyrus of the dominant (usually left) hemisphere.</li><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly caused by an ischemic stroke in the inferior division of the left [[143bb23d|Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)]].</li><li><b>Clinical Features:</b> <b>Fluent</b> but meaningless speech (\"word salad\"), <b>poor comprehension</b> of spoken and written language, and <b>impaired repetition</b>. Patients are typically unaware of their deficit (anosognosia) and may appear frustrated when not understood.</li><li><b>Comparison to Broca's Aphasia:</b> In contrast to [[7f6ed344|Broca's (expressive) aphasia]], where speech is non-fluent but comprehension is relatively intact, Wernicke's aphasia is fluent with poor comprehension. Mnemonic: <b>W</b>ernicke's is a <b>W</b>ordy but <b>W</b>orthless salad.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient who speaks in long, nonsensical sentences and cannot follow simple commands has Wernicke's aphasia. Look for an associated right superior quadrantanopia (\"pie in the sky\") due to involvement of the nearby optic radiations ([[6dcf9281|Meyer's loop]]).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The hallmark of <b>Wernicke's aphasia</b> is the profound disconnect between fluent speech production and the ability to comprehend language, localizing the lesion squarely to the posterior superior temporal gyrus of the dominant hemisphere.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
