    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Presbyopia</b> is the age-related, progressive loss of the eye's ability to focus on near objects, resulting from a decrease in the accommodative capacity of the lens.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Caused primarily by the hardening and loss of elasticity of the lens (lens sclerosis) that occurs with aging. This prevents the lens from becoming more convex (rounder) when the ciliary muscle contracts.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients, typically over age 40, report difficulty with near-vision tasks like reading, often holding reading material at arm's length to see it clearly. Symptoms include eye strain and headaches with near work.</li><li><b>Mechanism:</b> The [[81b5f5fe|accommodation]] reflex (ciliary muscle contraction) remains intact, but the stiff lens is unable to respond by changing its shape.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Corrected with the use of reading glasses or bifocals, which use a <mark>convex (converging) lens</mark> to add refractive power for near vision.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Do not confuse presbyopia with hyperopia (farsightedness). While both can cause blurry near vision and are corrected with convex lenses, presbyopia is due to loss of accommodation, whereas hyperopia is a refractive error due to the shape of the eyeball.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Presbyopia</b> is an inevitable consequence of aging where the lens loses its flexibility, impairing the eye's ability to accommodate for near vision, necessitating the use of reading glasses to compensate for the lost focusing power.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
