      "Pathology"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Preseptal cellulitis</b> is an infection of the eyelid and periorbital soft tissues located <i>anterior</i> to the orbital septum, which distinguishes it from the more serious orbital cellulitis.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Anatomy:</b> The orbital septum is a fibrous membrane that separates the superficial eyelid structures from the contents of the orbit (fat and muscles). Preseptal means in front of this barrier.</li><li><b>Etiology:</b> Often arises from a superficial source, such as a skin abrasion, insect bite, hordeolum, or spread from an upper respiratory tract infection or sinusitis. Common pathogens are <i>Staphylococcus aureus</i> and <i>Streptococcus pyogenes</i>.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Unilateral ocular pain, eyelid swelling, and erythema.</li><li><b>Key Differentiating Feature:</b> Unlike orbital cellulitis, in preseptal cellulitis, there is <u>no pain with eye movements</u>, <u>no proptosis</u> (bulging of the eye), and <u>no vision impairment or diplopia</u>. Extraocular movements are full and painless.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The most important step in evaluating a patient with a red, swollen eye is to assess for pain with eye movements. Absence of pain with movement strongly suggests preseptal cellulitis, while its presence points to the more dangerous [[5ccc91a9|orbital cellulitis]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Preseptal cellulitis</b> is an infection confined to the eyelid, anterior to the orbital septum. The integrity of the orbital septum prevents the infection from spreading to the orbit, thus preserving vision and eye movement, which is the key clinical distinction from the emergent condition of orbital cellulitis.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
