    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Pressure sensation</b> is a form of mechanoreception that allows for the perception of sustained touch and deep force applied to the skin, mediated by specific sensory receptors that transmit signals via the dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Receptors:</b> Mediated by slowly adapting mechanoreceptors. <mark>Merkel discs</mark> are responsible for sensing sustained pressure and deep static touch (e.g., shapes, edges). <mark>Ruffini corpuscles</mark> respond to sustained pressure and skin stretch.</li><li><b>Nerve Fibers:</b> Transmitted by large, myelinated AŒ≤ fibers.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Signals travel up the ipsilateral [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal columns]] (fasciculus gracilis and cuneatus) to the medulla, synapse, decussate, and ascend via the [[f19bc454|medial lemniscus]] to the VPL nucleus of the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]], and finally to the somatosensory cortex.</li><li><b>Distinction from Vibration:</b> While related, pressure is a sustained sensation, whereas vibration is sensed by rapidly adapting receptors like [[71867ae0|Pacinian corpuscles]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Loss of pressure sensation, along with vibration and proprioception, with preserved pain and temperature sensation, points to a lesion of the [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal columns]], as seen in [[71daebd6|Tabes Dorsalis]] or [[6f5bea90|Subacute Combined Degeneration]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Pressure sensation</b> is a critical component of discriminative touch, relying on slowly adapting receptors like Merkel discs and the high-fidelity dorsal column pathway to provide the brain with continuous information about the shape, texture, and force of objects in contact with the skin.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
