      "definition": "<p><b>Neurology Pharmacology</b> encompasses the study and application of drugs that affect the central and peripheral nervous systems. This field includes medications used to treat a wide range of conditions such as [[64c08e92|epilepsy]], [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]], [[26661e34|migraine headaches]], pain, and neurodegenerative disorders.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Anticonvulsants:</b> Drugs like [[5aea213f|phenytoin]], [[eddd2bc5|carbamazepine]], and [[0d37e045|valproate]] that stabilize neuronal membranes, often by blocking ion channels or enhancing [[5aa5cb91|GABAergic]] inhibition.</li><li><b>Parkinson Disease Drugs:</b> Medications aimed at increasing dopamine levels or activity, such as [[541cd176|levodopa/carbidopa]] and dopamine agonists.</li><li><b>Anesthetics:</b> General anesthetics induce unconsciousness, while local anesthetics block nerve conduction in a specific area.</li><li><b>Opioid Analgesics:</b> Powerful pain relievers that act on opioid receptors in the CNS.</li><li><b>Demyelinating Disease Therapies:</b> Immunomodulators like [[00e48ea3|interferon-Œ≤]] used to treat [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The core principle of many neurological drugs is the modulation of synaptic transmission, either by altering neurotransmitter levels (synthesis, release, reuptake, degradation) or by directly acting on postsynaptic receptors to either excite or inhibit neuronal activity.</p>",
