    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Phenobarbital</b> is a long-acting <i>barbiturate</i> that functions as a central nervous system depressant, used primarily as an anticonvulsant and sedative.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Potentiates the effect of [[5aa5cb91|GABA]] at the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor, which <mark>increases the duration</mark> of Cl<sup>-</sup> channel opening. This leads to prolonged hyperpolarization of the neuron, making it less excitable. Mnemonic: Barbi<b>durates</b> increase <b>duration</b>.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used for generalized tonic-clonic seizures and focal seizures. It is also a second-line agent for status epilepticus.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Major side effects include <mark>sedation</mark>, cognitive impairment, and respiratory and cardiovascular depression, especially when combined with other CNS depressants like alcohol.</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> It is a potent <mark>inducer of cytochrome P450</mark> enzymes in the liver, leading to numerous drug-drug interactions.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate its mechanism from benzodiazepines, which increase the <i>frequency</i> of Cl<sup>-</sup> channel opening. Phenobarbital's induction of CYP450 is a classic exam topic.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Phenobarbital</b> exerts its anticonvulsant and sedative effects by prolonging the opening of GABA<sub>A</sub>-associated chloride channels, a distinct mechanism from benzodiazepines, and its powerful induction of hepatic enzymes makes it a frequent culprit in drug interactions.</p>",
