    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Phenytoin</b> is a widely used <i>anticonvulsant</i> medication that works by blocking voltage-gated sodium channels, primarily used for treating focal and generalized tonic-clonic seizures.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Blocks high-frequency firing of neurons by inactivating voltage-gated <mark>Na<sup>+</sup> channels</mark>, thereby prolonging their refractory period.</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Exhibits <mark>zero-order (capacity-limited) elimination</mark> at therapeutic doses, meaning a small increase in dose can lead to a disproportionately large increase in plasma concentration and toxicity.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Common effects include nystagmus, diplopia, ataxia, and <mark>gingival hyperplasia</mark>. Long-term use can cause hirsutism, coarsening of facial features, and osteoporosis. It is also a teratogen (fetal hydantoin syndrome).</li><li><b>Drug Interactions:</b> It is a potent <mark>inducer of cytochrome P450</mark> enzymes, accelerating the metabolism of many other drugs.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the mnemonic <b>P-450</b> for inducers: <b>P</b>henytoin, <b>P</b>henobarbital, <b>C</b>arbamazepine, <b>R</b>ifampin, <b>G</b>riseofulvin, and <b>S</b>t. John's Wort (<b>P</b>CR<b>G</b>S). Gingival hyperplasia is a classic, visually identifiable side effect.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Phenytoin</b> is an effective anticonvulsant with a narrow therapeutic window due to its zero-order elimination kinetics, and its use is complicated by a distinctive side effect profile, including gingival hyperplasia, and its role as a powerful inducer of hepatic drug-metabolizing enzymes.</p>",
