    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Photophobia</b> is a symptom of abnormal intolerance to light, where exposure to light causes eye discomfort or pain. It is associated with various neurological and ophthalmological conditions.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> The exact pathway is not fully understood but is thought to involve the trigeminal pain pathway, which can be sensitized by underlying inflammation or neurological dysfunction.</li><li><b>Migraine Headache:</b> Photophobia is a key diagnostic criterion for [[26661e34|migraine headaches]], often accompanied by phonophobia (sensitivity to sound). Patients typically seek a dark, quiet room for relief.</li><li><b>Meningitis:</b> Inflammation of the meninges can irritate cranial nerves, including the trigeminal nerve, leading to significant photophobia. It is a classic symptom along with fever, headache, and nuchal rigidity.</li><li><b>Subarachnoid Hemorrhage:</b> The presence of blood in the subarachnoid space causes meningeal irritation, leading to severe headache and photophobia.</li><li><b>Ocular Causes:</b> Conditions causing inflammation of the eye, such as uveitis or keratitis, are common causes of photophobia.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The triad of fever, nuchal rigidity, and photophobia should immediately raise suspicion for meningitis.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Photophobia</b> is more than just light sensitivity; it is a neurological symptom of pain triggered by light, often indicating meningeal irritation (as in meningitis or subarachnoid hemorrhage) or trigeminal pathway sensitization (as in migraine).</p>",
