    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Neurological physiology</b> is the study of the function of the nervous system, from the molecular level of ion channels and neurotransmitters to the systemic level of sensory perception, motor control, and cognition.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Neuron Action Potential:</b> The fundamental unit of nerve communication, involving rapid changes in membrane potential due to voltage-gated Na<sup>+</sup> and K<sup>+</sup> channels.</li><li><b>Synaptic Transmission:</b> The process of transferring information from one neuron to another via the release of neurotransmitters.</li><li><b>Sensory Pathways:</b> Systems like the [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal columns]] and [[07eecef1|spinothalamic tract]] that transmit sensory information from the periphery to the brain.</li><li><b>Motor Pathways:</b> Systems like the corticospinal tract that convey motor commands from the brain to the muscles.</li><li><b>Special Senses:</b> Includes the complex physiology of vision, hearing ([[88e6f77e|hearing loss]]), balance (vestibular system), taste, and smell.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Understanding <b>neurological physiology</b> is essential for interpreting the clinical signs of nervous system disease, as deficits in function can often be precisely mapped to specific anatomical structures and physiological pathways.</p>",
