    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Physostigmine</b> is a reversible <i>acetylcholinesterase (AChE) inhibitor</i> that increases the concentration of acetylcholine at cholinergic synapses. Uniquely among clinically used AChE inhibitors, it is a tertiary amine and can cross the blood-brain barrier.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Reversibly inhibits AChE, the enzyme that breaks down [[6a005559|acetylcholine]], thereby increasing the level and duration of action of ACh at both muscarinic and nicotinic receptors.</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> As a <mark>tertiary amine</mark>, it is lipid-soluble and can cross the blood-brain barrier to exert effects in the central nervous system.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Primarily used as an antidote for <mark>anticholinergic toxicity</mark> (e.g., atropine overdose, Jimson weed poisoning) to reverse both central and peripheral symptoms.</li><li><b>Ophthalmology Use:</b> Can be used topically to induce miosis and treat [[3ce6c035|glaucoma]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember \"<b>Phy</b>sostigmine '<b>phy</b>xes' atropine overdose.\" Its ability to cross the BBB makes it the antidote of choice for reversing the central anticholinergic effects like delirium and confusion, unlike quaternary amines (e.g., neostigmine) which only act peripherally.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Physostigmine's</b> status as a tertiary amine is its defining feature, allowing it to cross the blood-brain barrier and serve as the primary antidote for reversing the life-threatening central nervous system toxicity of anticholinergic overdose.</p>",
