      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Meninges"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Pia Mater</b> is the delicate, innermost layer of the [[805d0677|meninges]], a thin, highly vascular membrane that closely adheres to the surface of the brain and spinal cord, following all of its contours (gyri and sulci).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Directly covers the surface of the brain and spinal cord. It is separated from the arachnoid mater by the subarachnoid space, which contains cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).</li><li><b>Structure:</b> A thin, transparent, mesh-like membrane composed of fibrous connective tissue. It is impermeable to fluid, forming a barrier.</li><li><b>Function:</b> Provides a supportive scaffold for cerebral and spinal blood vessels as they penetrate the brain tissue. The pia mater and astrocytes form the perivascular spaces (Virchow-Robin spaces).</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> The pia mater, along with the arachnoid mater (together known as the leptomeninges), is the primary site of inflammation in [[meningitis]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the order of the meninges from superficial to deep: <b>D-A-P</b> (<b>D</b>ura, <b>A</b>rachnoid, <b>P</b>ia). The pia is the layer that is 'intimately' attached to the brain.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Pia Mater</b> serves as the brain's 'shrink wrap,' a delicate but crucial barrier that encases the CNS and supports the vasculature as it dives into the neural parenchyma, making it a key player in both vascular supply and infectious processes like meningitis.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
