  "f54d873a": {
    "title": "Pilocarpine",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Autonomic",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Autonomic Drugs"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Pilocarpine</b> is a <i>direct-acting muscarinic agonist</i> (a parasympathomimetic) that is primarily used in ophthalmology to treat glaucoma and as a miotic agent, and systemically to treat dry mouth.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Directly stimulates muscarinic (M3) receptors. In the eye, it causes contraction of the ciliary muscle and the sphincter pupillae muscle.</li><li><b>Use in Glaucoma:</b> In <mark>open-angle glaucoma</mark>, ciliary muscle contraction increases the outflow of aqueous humor through the trabecular meshwork, lowering intraocular pressure. In <mark>acute angle-closure glaucoma</mark>, it causes miosis, which pulls the peripheral iris away from the trabecular meshwork, opening the angle for drainage.</li><li><b>Use for Xerostomia:</b> Stimulates muscarinic receptors on salivary glands to increase saliva production in conditions like Sj√∂gren syndrome or after radiation therapy.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Can cause systemic parasympathomimetic effects like sweating, nausea, bronchospasm, and bradycardia. Ocular effects include blurred vision and brow ache.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember \"You cry, drool, and sweat on your '<b>pilo</b>w'\" to recall the secretagogue effects of pilocarpine. It is a key drug for the emergency management of acute angle-closure glaucoma.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Pilocarpine</b> effectively lowers intraocular pressure in both open-angle and acute angle-closure glaucoma by physically altering the eye's drainage anatomy through M3 receptor-mediated contraction of the ciliary and pupillary sphincter muscles.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Pilocarpine] --> B(Muscarinic M3 Agonist); B --> C(Ciliary Muscle Contraction); C --> D(Increased Aqueous Outflow); D --> E(Decreased IOP); B --> F(Sphincter Pupillae Contraction); F --> G(Miosis);"
    },
    "connections": [
