  "912187bd": {
    "title": "Pilocytic Astrocytoma",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Oncology",
      "Pediatrics",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brain Tumors"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>Pilocytic Astrocytoma</b> is a low-grade (WHO grade I), slow-growing glioma that is the <i>most common primary brain tumor in childhood</i>, typically arising in the cerebellum.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Most commonly found in the <mark>posterior fossa (cerebellum)</mark>. Can also occur in the optic nerve pathway (optic glioma), hypothalamus, or cerebral hemispheres.</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> Classically appears as a <mark>cystic lesion with a brightly enhancing mural nodule</mark> on MRI or CT.</li><li><b>Histology:</b> Composed of well-differentiated, bipolar astrocytes with long, thin, 'hair-like' processes (pilocytic means 'hair-like'). Key features include <mark>Rosenthal fibers</mark> (thick, eosinophilic, corkscrew-shaped inclusions) and eosinophilic granular bodies. The tumor is GFAP-positive.</li><li><b>Prognosis:</b> Generally has a good prognosis with surgical resection.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A child with cerebellar signs (e.g., ataxia, dysmetria) and an MRI showing a cystic mass with a mural nodule in the cerebellum is the classic vignette for a pilocytic astrocytoma.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Pilocytic Astrocytoma</b> is the most common and most benign pediatric brain tumor, characterized by its classic cerebellar location, cystic-plus-mural-nodule appearance on imaging, and distinctive histological findings of Rosenthal fibers.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Childhood Brain Tumor] --> B{Most Common}; B --> C(Pilocytic Astrocytoma); C --> D[Location: Cerebellum]; C --> E[Imaging: Cyst + Mural Nodule]; C --> F[Histology: Rosenthal Fibers & GFAP+];"
    },
    "connections": [
