  "6fc77315": {
    "title": "Pineal Gland",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Endocrinology",
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Endocrine",
      "Anatomy",
      "Brain"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Pineal Gland</b> is a small endocrine gland located in the epithalamus, near the center of the brain, whose primary function is to receive information about the daily light-dark cycle and produce and secrete the hormone <i>melatonin</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Situated in the posterior aspect of the third ventricle, superior to the superior colliculi of the midbrain.</li><li><b>Function:</b> Synthesizes and secretes <mark>melatonin</mark>, a hormone that regulates circadian rhythms and sleep-wake cycles. Melatonin production is stimulated by darkness and inhibited by light.</li><li><b>Innervation:</b> Receives sympathetic innervation from the superior cervical ganglion, which is driven by input from the suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) of the hypothalamus.</li><li><b>Pathology (Pineal Tumors):</b> Tumors of the pineal gland (e.g., pinealoma, germinoma) are rare but can cause specific syndromes by compressing adjacent structures.</li><li><b>Parinaud Syndrome:</b> Compression of the dorsal midbrain (superior colliculi) by a pineal tumor can cause <mark>Parinaud syndrome</mark>, characterized by upward gaze palsy, convergence-retraction nystagmus, and light-near dissociation of the pupils.</li><li><b>Hydrocephalus:</b> A pineal tumor can also compress the cerebral aqueduct, leading to obstructive (non-communicating) [[0bc2f200|hydrocephalus]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Pineal Gland</b> acts as the body's neuroendocrine transducer of light, converting photic information from the retina into the hormonal signal of melatonin to entrain the body's circadian rhythms to the 24-hour day-night cycle.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Light] --> B(Retina); B --> C(Suprachiasmatic Nucleus); C --> D(Superior Cervical Ganglion); D --|Sympathetic Fibers|--> E(Pineal Gland); E --|Darkness|--> F(Melatonin Secretion); F --> G(Circadian Rhythm Regulation);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "produces",
        "to": "melatonin"
      },
