  "5f3188bd": {
    "title": "Pituitary Adenoma",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Endocrinology",
      "Neurology",
      "Oncology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Endocrine",
      "Pathology",
      "Pituitary Tumors"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>Pituitary Adenoma</b> is a benign tumor of the [[76ba7f2e|anterior pituitary gland]] that can cause symptoms either through mass effect on surrounding structures or by hypersecretion of one or more pituitary hormones.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Classification:</b> Categorized by size (microadenoma <1 cm, macroadenoma ‚â•1 cm) and by hormonal activity (functional vs. non-functional).</li><li><b>Mass Effect Symptoms:</b> Macroadenomas can compress the optic chiasm, causing a classic <mark>bitemporal hemianopia</mark>. They can also cause headaches and hypopituitarism by compressing normal pituitary tissue.</li><li><b>Functional Adenomas (Hypersecretion):</b><br>  - <b>Prolactinoma:</b> Most common type. Causes galactorrhea, amenorrhea, and infertility in women; decreased libido and impotence in men.<br>  - <b>Somatotroph Adenoma:</b> Secretes Growth Hormone (GH), causing acromegaly in adults and gigantism in children.<br>  - <b>Corticotroph Adenoma:</b> Secretes ACTH, causing Cushing disease.</li><li><b>Pituitary Apoplexy:</b> An acute hemorrhage or infarction within a pituitary adenoma, presenting with sudden severe headache, visual changes, and altered mental status. It is a neurosurgical emergency.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient presenting with bitemporal hemianopia should immediately make you think of a pituitary adenoma compressing the optic chiasm. If a woman presents with amenorrhea and galactorrhea, suspect a prolactinoma.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Pituitary adenomas</b> manifest a dual pathology: they can disrupt the endocrine system through hormone overproduction (most commonly prolactin) and disrupt the nervous system through mass effect, classically causing bitemporal hemianopia by compressing the optic chiasm.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Pituitary Adenoma]; A --> B(Mass Effect); B --> B1[Bitemporal Hemianopia]; B --> B2[Headache]; B --> B3[Hypopituitarism]; A --> C(Hormone Hypersecretion); C --> C1[Prolactinoma]; C --> C2[GH-secreting]; C --> C3[ACTH-secreting];"
    },
