  "da045b40": {
    "title": "Pituitary Apoplexy",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Endocrinology",
      "Neurology",
      "Emergency Medicine",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Endocrine",
      "Pathology",
      "Pituitary Tumors"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Pituitary Apoplexy</b> is a rare but life-threatening clinical syndrome caused by acute hemorrhage or infarction within a pre-existing [[5f3188bd|pituitary adenoma]], leading to a rapid increase in intrasellar pressure.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Spontaneous hemorrhage or infarction of a [[5f3188bd|pituitary adenoma]]. It can be precipitated by factors like head trauma, surgery, or anticoagulation.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Characterized by the sudden onset of an excruciating <mark>\"thunderclap\" headache</mark>, visual disturbances (diplopia from CN III, IV, VI palsy; bitemporal hemianopia from chiasmal compression), and altered mental status.</li><li><b>Endocrine Dysfunction:</b> The rapid destruction of pituitary tissue can lead to acute hypopituitarism. Acute adrenal insufficiency (due to lack of ACTH) is the most life-threatening consequence, leading to severe hypotension and shock.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> MRI is the imaging modality of choice, showing hemorrhage and necrosis within an enlarged sella turcica.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from subarachnoid hemorrhage: both can cause a thunderclap headache, but pituitary apoplexy is distinguished by signs of cranial nerve palsies (especially CN III) and acute pituitary failure (e.g., hypotension).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Pituitary apoplexy</b> is a neurological and endocrinological emergency where a pituitary tumor suddenly bleeds or dies, causing a triad of severe headache, visual impairment, and acute pituitary hormone deficiency, with the potential for fatal adrenal crisis.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Pituitary Adenoma] --> B(Acute Hemorrhage/Infarction); B --> C(Rapid Expansion); C --> D[Compression of Sellar Structures]; D --> D1(CN III, IV, VI Palsies); D --> D2(Optic Chiasm Compression); C --> E[Destruction of Pituitary]; E --> F(Acute Hypopituitarism); F --> G(Adrenal Crisis/Shock);"
    },
    "connections": [
