  "beefb152": {
    "title": "Plantar Reflex (Babinski Sign)",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Spinal Cord"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Plantar Reflex</b> is a superficial reflex elicited by stroking the sole of the foot. A normal response in adults is plantar flexion (curling down) of the toes. An abnormal response, known as the <b>Babinski sign</b>, is dorsiflexion of the great toe and fanning of the other toes, indicating an upper motor neuron lesion.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Normal Response (Flexor):</b> Stroking the lateral aspect of the sole from heel to ball results in flexion (curling) of the toes.</li><li><b>Abnormal Response (Extensor / Babinski Sign):</b> The same stimulus causes dorsiflexion (upward extension) of the great toe and fanning of the other toes.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The Babinski sign indicates damage to the <mark>corticospinal (pyramidal) tracts</mark>. It represents a release of a primitive reflex that is normally suppressed by descending inhibitory signals from the motor cortex.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> A positive Babinski sign is a key indicator of an <mark>upper motor neuron (UMN) lesion</mark>. It can be seen in conditions like stroke, spinal cord injury, [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]], and [[4ed629f9|amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The Babinski sign is normal in infants up to about 1 year of age due to incomplete myelination of the corticospinal tracts. Its presence in an adult is <u>always</u> pathological. Mnemonic: <b>U</b>pper motor neuron lesion = toes go <b>U</b>p.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Babinski sign</b> is a powerful clinical indicator of upper motor neuron dysfunction, reflecting a loss of cortical inhibition over primitive spinal reflexes; its presence transforms a simple foot stroke into a significant neurological finding.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_sign_of",
        "to": "upper_motor_neuron_lesion"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_caused_by_damage_to",
        "to": "corticospinal_tract"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
        "to": "primitive_reflex"
      }
    ]
