  "bf549b2f": {
    "title": "Pons",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Brainstem"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Pons</b> is a major division of the brainstem, located superior to the medulla oblongata and inferior to the midbrain. It serves as a critical relay station for signals between the cerebrum and cerebellum and contains nuclei for several cranial nerves.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Part of the hindbrain (metencephalon), anterior to the cerebellum.</li><li><b>Cranial Nerve Nuclei:</b> Contains the nuclei for cranial nerves <b>V (Trigeminal)</b>, <b>VI (Abducens)</b>, <b>VII (Facial)</b>, and <b>VIII (Vestibulocochlear)</b>. Mnemonic: 4 nerves in the pons.</li><li><b>Key Tracts:</b> Contains ascending sensory tracts (medial lemniscus, spinothalamic) and descending motor tracts (corticospinal, corticobulbar).</li><li><b>Specialized Centers:</b> Includes the pontine micturition center, and the Paramedian Pontine Reticular Formation (PPRF), which is the horizontal gaze center.</li><li><b>Stroke Syndromes:</b> Lesions can cause specific syndromes. <mark>Medial Pontine Syndrome</mark> (basilar artery branches) affects corticospinal tracts and CN VI. <mark>Lateral Pontine Syndrome</mark> (AICA) affects CN V, VII, VIII, spinothalamic tract, and sympathetic fibers.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the 'Rule of 4s' for the brainstem: 4 cranial nerves are in the pons (V, VI, VII, VIII).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Pons</b> acts as a crucial bridge ('pons' is Latin for bridge) connecting the cerebrum and cerebellum and houses the nuclei for key cranial nerves controlling facial sensation, movement, eye abduction, and hearing/balance.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
