    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Parkinson Disease</b> is a progressive <i>neurodegenerative disorder</i> caused by the loss of dopaminergic neurons in the <b>substantia nigra pars compacta</b>, leading to a characteristic syndrome of tremor, rigidity, bradykinesia, and postural instability.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Loss of [[90adc821|dopamine]]-producing neurons in the substantia nigra leads to decreased stimulation of the direct pathway and decreased inhibition of the indirect pathway in the [[ed462927|basal ganglia]], resulting in an overall inhibition of movement.</li><li><b>Histology:</b> Presence of intracellular eosinophilic inclusions called <mark>Lewy bodies</mark> (composed of Œ±-synuclein) within the remaining neurons of the substantia nigra.</li><li><b>Clinical Tetrad (TRAP):</b> <b>T</b>remor (pill-rolling, at rest), <b>R</b>igidity (cogwheel or leadpipe), <b>A</b>kinesia/bradykinesia (shuffling gait, micrographia), and <b>P</b>ostural instability.</li><li><b>Neurotransmitter Changes:</b> Significant decrease in [[90adc821|dopamine]] in the nigrostriatal pathway. Relative excess of [[6a005559|acetylcholine]].</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Symptomatic therapy aims to increase dopamine levels using agents like [[541cd176|Levodopa/Carbidopa]], dopamine agonists (e.g., pramipexole), and MAO-B inhibitors (e.g., [[2883864d|rasagiline]]). Antimuscarinics (e.g., benztropine) can help with tremor.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of a resting tremor, shuffling gait, and cogwheel rigidity in an older patient is classic for Parkinson disease. The pathological hallmark is the Lewy body.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Parkinson Disease</b> is fundamentally a disorder of dopamine deficiency in the basal ganglia, leading to an over-inhibition of movement. Therapeutic strategies are all centered on restoring this dopaminergic tone, either by replacing dopamine, mimicking its effects, or preventing its breakdown.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Loss of Dopaminergic Neurons in Substantia Nigra] --> B(Decreased Dopamine); B --> C(Basal Ganglia Dysfunction); C --> D(Inhibition of Movement); D --> E(TRAP Symptoms);"
