      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Seizures"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Focal seizures</b>, formerly known as partial seizures, are epileptic events that originate within a localized network of neurons in <i>one cerebral hemisphere</i>. Their clinical manifestations depend on the specific cortical area involved.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Focal Aware Seizure (Simple Partial):</b> Consciousness is fully maintained. Symptoms can be motor (e.g., jerking of a limb - Jacksonian march), sensory (e.g., paresthesias), autonomic (e.g., epigastric rising sensation), or psychic (e.g., d√©j√† vu).</li><li><b>Focal Impaired Awareness Seizure (Complex Partial):</b> Consciousness is altered or lost. Often preceded by an aura (which is itself a focal aware seizure). Characterized by <mark>automatisms</mark> (e.g., lip smacking, chewing, fumbling with clothes). A postictal state of confusion is common.</li><li><b>Origin:</b> The <mark>temporal lobe</mark> is the most common site of origin for focal impaired awareness seizures.</li><li><b>Secondary Generalization:</b> A focal seizure can spread to involve both hemispheres, evolving into a bilateral tonic-clonic seizure.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Treated with <mark>narrow-spectrum anticonvulsants</mark> such as [[eddd2bc5|carbamazepine]], [[5aea213f|phenytoin]], or lamotrigine. Broad-spectrum agents like levetiracetam or valproic acid are also effective.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The key distinction in <b>focal seizures</b> is the state of awareness: if the patient remains fully aware and interactive, it is a focal aware seizure; if awareness is impaired, it is a focal impaired awareness seizure, which is often associated with temporal lobe origin and automatisms.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Focal Seizure]; A --> B{Awareness}; B --Intact--> C(Focal Aware Seizure); B --Impaired--> D(Focal Impaired Awareness Seizure); A --Can spread to--> E(Secondarily Generalized Seizure);"
