  "3847e263": {
    "title": "Patellar Reflex",
    "primaryType": "physiology",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Spinal Cord"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Patellar Reflex</b>, also known as the knee-jerk reflex, is a deep tendon reflex that involves contraction of the quadriceps femoris muscle and extension of the leg in response to tapping the patellar tendon, testing the integrity of the <mark>L2-L4</mark> spinal nerve roots.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Nerve Roots:</b> Primarily tests the <b>L4</b> nerve root, with contributions from L2 and L3. Mnemonic: L2, 3, <b>4</b>, kick the door.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Tapping the tendon stretches the quadriceps muscle, activating muscle spindle stretch receptors. The afferent signal travels via the femoral nerve to the L2-L4 spinal cord segments, synapses on an alpha motor neuron, and an efferent motor signal returns via the femoral nerve to cause quadriceps contraction.</li><li><b>Diminished/Absent Reflex:</b> Suggests a lower motor neuron lesion, such as a herniated disc compressing the L4 root, or peripheral neuropathy.</li><li><b>Exaggerated Reflex (Hyperreflexia):</b> Suggests an upper motor neuron lesion, such as a stroke or spinal cord injury above the L2-L4 level.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> This is one of the most commonly tested reflexes. Its absence can be a key sign of an L4 radiculopathy, which also presents with weakness of knee extension and sensory loss over the medial lower leg.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Patellar Reflex</b> is a monosynaptic stretch reflex that provides a rapid and reliable clinical assessment of the L4 spinal segment and its peripheral connections; an abnormal response is a crucial indicator of either upper or lower motor neuron pathology.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Tap Patellar Tendon] --> B(Stretch Quadriceps); B --> C(Afferent Signal via Femoral N.); C --> D[L2-L4 Spinal Cord]; D --> E(Efferent Signal via Femoral N.); E --> F(Quadriceps Contraction/Leg Extension);"
