    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Neuronal pathology</b> describes the structural and functional changes that occur in neurons in response to injury, ischemia, or degenerative processes, which can be identified through characteristic histological findings.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Acute Neuronal Injury (\"Red Neurons\"):</b> Seen 12-24 hours after an irreversible hypoxic/ischemic insult. Characterized by intense eosinophilic (red) cytoplasm, pyknotic (shrunken, dark) nucleus, and loss of Nissl substance.</li><li><b>Axonal Reaction (Central Chromatolysis):</b> The response of a neuron's cell body to axonal injury. Characterized by cell body swelling, dispersion of Nissl substance to the periphery (chromatolysis), and displacement of the nucleus to the periphery.</li><li><b>Neuronal Atrophy/Degeneration:</b> A slow process of neuronal death seen in neurodegenerative diseases like [[77ae6148|Alzheimer's]] or [[58c8ea03|Parkinson's]]. Results in neuronal loss and reactive gliosis.</li><li><b>Neuronal Inclusions:</b> Accumulation of abnormal proteins or structures within neurons, which are often hallmarks of specific diseases. Examples include <mark>Lewy bodies</mark> in Parkinson's, <mark>neurofibrillary tangles</mark> in Alzheimer's, and <mark>Negri bodies</mark> in rabies.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The appearance of \"red neurons\" on histology is a key indicator of irreversible ischemic brain injury that occurred at least 12-24 hours prior.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The histological appearance of a neuron provides a timeline and etiology of CNS injury; from the acute eosinophilia of \"red neurons\" in stroke to the chronic accumulation of protein aggregates in neurodegenerative diseases, the neuron's morphology tells the story of its pathology.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
