    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Pediatric neurological disorders</b> encompass a wide range of conditions affecting the brain, spinal cord, and peripheral nerves in infants and children, including congenital malformations, genetic syndromes, seizures, and tumors.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Seizures:</b> [[12108f05|Febrile seizures]] are common and benign. [[a0c128f4|Absence seizures]] present as staring spells. Infantile spasms are another important type.</li><li><b>Primary Brain Tumors:</b> Unlike in adults, pediatric brain tumors are most commonly located in the <mark>infratentorial</mark> space (posterior fossa). The most common is the [[912187bd|pilocytic astrocytoma]], followed by [[16d613bb|medulloblastoma]].</li><li><b>Intraventricular Hemorrhage:</b> A common complication in premature infants, originating from the fragile germinal matrix.</li><li><b>Leukocoria (\"White Pupil\"):</b> A critical sign in a child that can indicate serious pathology, most notably [[63b964af|retinoblastoma]] or congenital cataracts.</li><li><b>Neurocutaneous Disorders:</b> Conditions like [[83302339|Tuberous Sclerosis]] and [[015a73ab|Neurofibromatosis]] often present with neurological symptoms (seizures, developmental delay) in childhood.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The landscape of neurological disorders in children is distinct from that in adults, with a predominance of congenital and genetic conditions, and a different spectrum and location of brain tumors, making developmental history and age-specific presentations key to diagnosis.</p>",
