    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Pentobarbital</b> is a short- to intermediate-acting <i>barbiturate</i> used as a sedative, hypnotic, and anticonvulsant, and for inducing comas in cases of severe brain injury to reduce metabolic rate and intracranial pressure.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Potentiates the effect of [[5aa5cb91|GABA]] at the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor by <mark>increasing the duration</mark> of Cl<sup>-</sup> channel opening, leading to prolonged neuronal hyperpolarization.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Historically used for insomnia and anxiety, but largely replaced by benzodiazepines due to a narrower therapeutic index. Currently used for status epilepticus refractory to other agents and to induce a 'barbiturate coma' for managing refractory increased intracranial pressure.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Significant risk of <mark>respiratory and cardiovascular depression</mark>, which can be fatal in overdose. High potential for tolerance, dependence, and abuse.</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Induces cytochrome P450 enzymes, leading to drug interactions.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Like all barbiturates, there is <u>no reversal agent</u> for pentobarbital overdose; treatment is purely supportive (airway management, blood pressure support).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Pentobarbital</b> is a powerful CNS depressant that enhances GABAergic inhibition by increasing the duration of chloride channel opening, a mechanism that provides potent sedation and seizure control but also carries a high risk of fatal respiratory depression, especially in overdose.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
