  "a1a54523": {
    "title": "Peripheral Facial Palsy",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Cranial Neuropathies"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Peripheral facial palsy</b> is a lower motor neuron (LMN) lesion of the [[dea9755f|facial nerve (CN VII)]] that results in paralysis of all muscles of facial expression on the <i>ipsilateral</i> side of the face, including the forehead.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Unilateral facial paralysis affecting both the upper and lower face. Patients are unable to raise their eyebrow, wrinkle their forehead, or close their eye tightly on the affected side. They also exhibit a drooping corner of the mouth and a flattened nasolabial fold.</li><li><b>Etiology:</b> The most common cause is Bell's palsy (idiopathic, presumed viral). Other causes include [[09fa1b0f|Ramsay Hunt syndrome]] (VZV), Lyme disease, tumors (e.g., [[03ecb69e|schwannoma]]), and trauma.</li><li><b>Distinction from Central Lesion:</b> A central (upper motor neuron) facial palsy, caused by a stroke, spares the forehead muscles. This is because the upper face receives bilateral cortical innervation, while the lower face receives only contralateral innervation.</li><li><b>Associated Symptoms:</b> Depending on the location of the lesion along CN VII, may also have decreased tearing, hyperacusis (due to stapedius muscle paralysis), and loss of taste from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The key to differentiating a peripheral from a central facial palsy is the forehead. If the patient <u>can</u> wrinkle their forehead, the lesion is central (UMN). If they <u>cannot</u>, the lesion is peripheral (LMN).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>peripheral facial palsy</b> is a definitive lower motor neuron sign affecting the entire ipsilateral face, including the forehead. This complete hemifacial paralysis is the crucial feature that distinguishes it from the forehead-sparing weakness of a central (UMN) lesion like a stroke.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[LMN Lesion of CN VII] --> B(Peripheral Facial Palsy); B --> C(Paralysis of Ipsilateral Upper & Lower Face); D[UMN Lesion e.g., Stroke] --> E(Central Facial Palsy); E --> F(Paralysis of Contralateral Lower Face ONLY);"
    },
