  "c44ae4c5": {
    "title": "Peripheral Nervous System (PNS)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Overview"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Peripheral Nervous System (PNS)</b> consists of all nervous tissue outside of the central nervous system (brain and spinal cord), including cranial nerves (III-XII), spinal nerves, ganglia, and sensory receptors. It serves as the communication relay between the CNS and the rest of the body.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Components:</b> Cranial nerves and their ganglia, spinal nerves and their dorsal root ganglia, autonomic nerves and ganglia, and the enteric nervous system.</li><li><b>Glial Cells:</b> The main supporting cells are [[c65a8909|Schwann cells]] (which form myelin sheaths) and satellite cells (which support neuron cell bodies in ganglia).</li><li><b>Embryonic Origin:</b> Most components of the PNS, including neurons and glial cells, are derived from the <mark>neural crest</mark>.</li><li><b>Nerve Structure:</b> Peripheral nerves are composed of bundles of axons (fascicles). Each axon is surrounded by endoneurium, each fascicle by [[ae1bcf9a|perineurium]], and the entire nerve by epineurium.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Diseases of the PNS are called peripheral neuropathies, which can be demyelinating (e.g., [[ed52e40b|Guillain-Barr√© syndrome]]) or axonal (e.g., diabetic neuropathy).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Peripheral Nervous System</b> is the extensive network of nerves and ganglia that connects the central nervous system to the limbs and organs, with its neurons and glial cells primarily originating from the versatile neural crest during embryonic development.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
