  "5811ad9e": {
    "title": "Peripheral Vertigo",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Otology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Otology",
      "Pathology"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Peripheral vertigo</b> is a sensation of spinning or dizziness that originates from a problem within the <i>inner ear or the vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII)</i>, which are parts of the peripheral vestibular system.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Common causes include Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo (BPPV), Vestibular Neuritis/Labyrinthitis, and [[6f2228c1|M√©ni√®re disease]].</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Characterized by sudden, intense episodes of vertigo, often triggered by head movements. Nausea and vomiting are common.</li><li><b>Nystagmus:</b> Typically presents with a <mark>horizontal or torsional (rotary) nystagmus</mark> that is unidirectional and fatigable. It is suppressed by visual fixation.</li><li><b>Associated Symptoms:</b> May be accompanied by hearing loss and/or tinnitus if the cochlea or cochlear nerve is also affected (e.g., in M√©ni√®re disease or labyrinthitis).</li><li><b>Distinction from Central Vertigo:</b> Unlike [[350f1c8b|central vertigo]], it is not associated with other brainstem signs like dysarthria, dysphagia, or limb ataxia. The nystagmus is rarely purely vertical.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The Dix-Hallpike maneuver is used to diagnose BPPV. A positive test (reproduction of vertigo and torsional nystagmus after a short delay) is characteristic of peripheral vertigo.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Peripheral vertigo</b> is an inner ear problem, not a brain problem. Its key features are intense, episodic spinning, often with nausea, and a characteristic horizontal/torsional nystagmus, without the additional 'red flag' neurological signs seen in central vertigo.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
