  "d9286430": {
    "title": "Periventricular Plaques",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Radiology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Demyelinating Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Periventricular plaques</b> are focal areas of demyelination and gliosis located in the white matter adjacent to the lateral ventricles of the brain. They are the most characteristic radiological finding in <i>Multiple Sclerosis (MS)</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Appearance on MRI:</b> On T2-weighted and FLAIR MRI sequences, they appear as <mark>hyperintense (bright) ovoid lesions</mark> oriented perpendicular to the ventricles. This orientation follows the path of the deep medullary veins and is sometimes referred to as 'Dawson's fingers.'</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> The plaques represent areas where autoimmune inflammation has destroyed [[a24f9747|oligodendrocytes]] and their myelin sheaths, which is then replaced by an astrocytic scar (gliosis).</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> The presence of periventricular plaques is a key component of the McDonald criteria for diagnosing [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]]. Their distribution helps fulfill the criterion of 'dissemination in space.'</li><li><b>Location:</b> While periventricular is the classic location, MS plaques can also be found in juxtacortical, infratentorial, and spinal cord locations.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> An MRI showing multiple hyperintense lesions in the periventricular white matter, especially in a young woman with relapsing neurological symptoms, is pathognomonic for [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Periventricular plaques</b> are the radiological signature of [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]], representing focal scars of demyelination that cluster around the ventricles and serve as the primary imaging evidence for the diagnosis.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
