      "Neurodegenerative Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Pes cavus</b> is a foot deformity characterized by an abnormally high plantar arch, which is a classic musculoskeletal finding in patients with <i>Friedreich Ataxia</i>, resulting from chronic neuromuscular imbalance.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> In [[39bc1763|Friedreich Ataxia]], degeneration of peripheral nerves and spinal cord tracts leads to an imbalance between the intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the foot, causing the arch to become excessively high.</li><li><b>Associated Condition:</b> [[39bc1763|Friedreich Ataxia]] is an autosomal recessive trinucleotide repeat (GAA) disorder affecting the frataxin gene, leading to progressive neurodegeneration.</li><li><b>Other Clinical Features of Friedreich Ataxia:</b> Besides pes cavus, patients present with progressive gait and limb ataxia, dysarthria, loss of deep tendon reflexes, loss of proprioception/vibration sense, and hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.</li><li><b>Other Foot Deformities:</b> Hammer toes are also commonly seen in conjunction with pes cavus in this condition.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of neurological symptoms (ataxia, areflexia) with non-neurological findings like hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and skeletal deformities (pes cavus, kyphoscoliosis) is highly suggestive of [[39bc1763|Friedreich Ataxia]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Pes cavus</b> in the context of [[39bc1763|Friedreich Ataxia]] is not an isolated orthopedic issue but a direct consequence of the underlying neurodegeneration, serving as a key physical exam clue to this multisystem genetic disorder.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
