    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Outer Ear</b> is the most external portion of the auditory system, consisting of the <i>pinna (auricle)</i> and the <i>external auditory canal</i>, which terminates at the tympanic membrane. Its primary function is to collect sound waves and channel them to the middle ear.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Components:</b> Includes the pinna (the visible part of the ear) and the external auditory canal (the ear canal).</li><li><b>Function:</b> The pinna helps to collect and localize sound. The external auditory canal funnels the sound waves to the tympanic membrane, causing it to vibrate.</li><li><b>Innervation:</b> Sensory innervation to the external ear is complex, involving branches from multiple cranial nerves (CN V<sub>3</sub>, VII, X) and cervical nerves (C2, C3).</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> The most common pathology of the outer ear is [[otitis_externa|otitis externa]] (\"swimmer's ear\"), an infection of the external auditory canal, often caused by <i>Pseudomonas aeruginosa</i>.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that manipulation of the pinna or tragus causes pain in [[otitis_externa|otitis externa]], a key feature distinguishing it from [[a03641af|otitis media]] where the pain is internal and not exacerbated by external touch.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Outer Ear</b> functions as a biological funnel, capturing and directing sound waves toward the tympanic membrane to initiate the mechanical process of hearing, and its exposure to the environment makes it susceptible to infections like otitis externa.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
