    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Oxazepam</b> is a short-to-intermediate acting <i>benzodiazepine</i> used for the treatment of anxiety and acute alcohol withdrawal. It is notable for its metabolism via glucuronidation, making it safer in patients with liver disease.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Like other benzodiazepines, it facilitates the action of [[5aa5cb91|GABA]] at the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor, increasing the <mark>frequency</mark> of Cl<sup>-</sup> channel opening and causing CNS depression.</li><li><b>Metabolism:</b> Undergoes direct glucuronidation in the liver without involving the cytochrome P450 system. This makes its metabolism less affected by liver disease or drugs that inhibit/induce CYP enzymes.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used for anxiety disorders, panic attacks, and management of alcohol withdrawal symptoms.</li><li><b>Safe in Liver Disease:</b> Along with Lorazepam and Temazepam, Oxazepam is a preferred benzodiazepine in patients with severe liver disease or in the elderly. Mnemonic: <b>O</b>utside <b>T</b>he <b>L</b>iver (<b>O</b>xazepam, <b>T</b>emazepam, <b>L</b>orazepam).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> For a patient with cirrhosis and alcohol withdrawal requiring a benzodiazepine, choose one that is metabolized 'Outside The Liver' like Oxazepam or Lorazepam.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Oxazepam's</b> key feature is its metabolism through glucuronidation, bypassing the cytochrome P450 system. This makes it a significantly safer benzodiazepine choice for patients with compromised liver function, such as those with alcoholic cirrhosis who are undergoing withdrawal.</p>",
