    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Oxytocin</b> is a peptide hormone and neuropeptide that is synthesized in the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]] and released from the posterior pituitary. It plays a crucial role in uterine contractions during labor and milk let-down during lactation, and is also involved in social bonding.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Synthesis and Release:</b> Synthesized primarily in the <mark>paraventricular nuclei</mark> of the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]], transported down axons, and stored and released from the posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis).</li><li><b>Uterine Contractions:</b> Stimulates uterine smooth muscle contraction, which is essential for labor and delivery. Exogenous oxytocin (Pitocin) is used to induce or augment labor.</li><li><b>Milk Ejection (Let-down reflex):</b> Suckling stimulates oxytocin release, which causes contraction of myoepithelial cells surrounding the mammary alveoli, ejecting milk.</li><li><b>Social Bonding:</b> Acts as a neurotransmitter in the brain, involved in social recognition, pair bonding, maternal behavior, and trust.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that oxytocin and ADH are both produced in the hypothalamus and released from the posterior pituitary. Oxytocin is for 'squeezing' (uterine contractions, milk ejection), while ADH is for 'saving' water.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Oxytocin</b> functions as both a peripheral hormone and a central neurotransmitter; peripherally, it is the primary driver of uterine contractions and milk ejection, while centrally, it modulates complex social behaviors, earning it the nickname 'the love hormone'.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Hypothalamus - Paraventricular Nucleus] --> B(Posterior Pituitary); B --Release--> C(Oxytocin); C --> D(Uterine Contraction); C --> E(Milk Ejection);"
