    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Pacinian corpuscles</b> are large, encapsulated sensory receptors located in the deep dermis and subcutaneous tissue that are specialized to detect high-frequency <i>vibration</i> and deep <i>pressure</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Structure:</b> Large, onion-like (lamellated) capsule surrounding a single nerve ending.</li><li><b>Function:</b> They are <mark>rapidly adapting</mark> mechanoreceptors, meaning they respond to changes in stimuli (onset and offset of pressure) rather than sustained pressure. This property makes them ideal for sensing vibration.</li><li><b>Location:</b> Found deep in the dermis, subcutaneous tissue, ligaments, and joint capsules. Abundant in fingertips and genitals.</li><li><b>Nerve Fibers:</b> Transmitted by large, myelinated AŒ≤ fibers.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Signals for vibration and pressure travel via the [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> When testing sensory modalities, remember the specific receptors: Vibration = Pacinian corpuscles. Fine touch = Meissner's corpuscles. Sustained pressure = Merkel discs.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The unique, onion-like layered structure of <b>Pacinian corpuscles</b> acts as a mechanical filter, allowing them to respond only to rapid changes in pressure, which makes them exquisitely sensitive to high-frequency vibration rather than static touch.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
