    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Pain</b> (nociception) is an unpleasant sensory and emotional experience associated with actual or potential tissue damage. It is transmitted from the periphery to the central nervous system via specialized nerve fibers and pathways.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Sensory Receptors:</b> Mediated by <mark>free nerve endings</mark> of nociceptors, which respond to noxious thermal, mechanical, or chemical stimuli.</li><li><b>Nerve Fibers:</b> Transmitted by two types of fibers: <br> - <b>AŒ¥ fibers:</b> Thinly myelinated, transmit fast, sharp, well-localized pain.<br> - <b>C fibers:</b> Unmyelinated, transmit slow, dull, poorly-localized pain.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Signals travel to the dorsal horn of the spinal cord, synapse, decussate at the anterior white commissure, and ascend in the contralateral <mark>spinothalamic tract</mark> to the VPL nucleus of the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]], and then to the somatosensory cortex.</li><li><b>Periorbital Pain:</b> A key feature of [[21760f80|cluster headaches]], often described as excruciating.</li><li><b>Pain in MS:</b> Neuropathic pain is a common symptom in [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]], often treated with anticonvulsants or TCAs.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The sensation of <b>pain</b> is not a single modality but is dually encoded by fast AŒ¥ fibers for initial sharp warning and slow C fibers for prolonged aching, both of which travel through the dedicated spinothalamic tract to alert the brain to tissue damage.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Noxious Stimulus] --> B(Free Nerve Endings); B --> C(AŒ¥ & C Fibers); C --> D(Dorsal Horn); D --> E(Decussation); E --> F(Spinothalamic Tract); F --> G(Thalamus); G --> H(Somatosensory Cortex);"
    },
