  "ea694390": {
    "title": "Palmar Reflex",
    "primaryType": "physiology",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pediatrics",
      "Physical Exam",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Reflexes"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Palmar Reflex</b>, also known as the grasp reflex, is a primitive, involuntary reflex found in infants, characterized by the fingers closing and grasping an object when the palm is stroked.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Elicitation:</b> Placing a finger or object into an infant's open palm causes them to reflexively grasp it.</li><li><b>Developmental Timeline:</b> Present at birth and typically disappears by <mark>5-6 months of age</mark> as voluntary motor control develops.</li><li><b>Neurological Basis:</b> It is a spinal reflex that is inhibited by the maturing frontal lobes.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance in Infants:</b> Its presence is a sign of normal neurological development. Its absence or asymmetry may indicate CNS damage or peripheral nerve injury.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance in Adults:</b> The re-emergence of the palmar reflex in an adult is a <mark>frontal release sign</mark>, indicating damage to the frontal lobe (e.g., from dementia, stroke, or traumatic brain injury), which has removed the normal cortical inhibition of this primitive reflex.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The reappearance of primitive reflexes like the palmar, rooting, or sucking reflex in an adult patient is a strong indicator of frontal lobe pathology.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Palmar Reflex</b> serves as a developmental milestone; its presence in infancy is normal, but its persistence or re-emergence in later life is a pathological sign of frontal lobe disinhibition, unmasking a primitive spinal circuit.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
        "to": "ccf246d3"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_a_sign_of",
        "to": "frontal_lobe_lesion"
      }
    ]
  },
  "243d4db1": {
    "title": "Pancuronium",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Anesthesiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neuromuscular Blockers"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Pancuronium</b> is a long-acting, <i>non-depolarizing neuromuscular blocking agent</i> that acts as a competitive antagonist at nicotinic acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction, causing skeletal muscle paralysis.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Competitively antagonizes [[6a005559|ACh]] at the nicotinic (N<sub>M</sub>) receptors on the motor endplate, preventing muscle cell depolarization and contraction.</li><li><b>Class:</b> It is an aminosteroid non-depolarizing blocker, similar to rocuronium and vecuronium.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used in anesthesia to facilitate endotracheal intubation and provide skeletal muscle relaxation during surgery. Also used in ICUs to facilitate mechanical ventilation.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Can cause tachycardia and hypertension due to its vagolytic effect (muscarinic receptor blockade) and slight sympathomimetic action.</li><li><b>Reversal:</b> Its effects can be reversed by increasing the amount of ACh in the synapse, which is achieved by administering an acetylcholinesterase inhibitor (e.g., neostigmine) along with an antimuscarinic agent (e.g., glycopyrrolate) to prevent systemic muscarinic side effects.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate non-depolarizing blockers like pancuronium from the depolarizing blocker succinylcholine. Non-depolarizing blockade is reversed by AChE inhibitors, whereas Phase I of succinylcholine block is potentiated by them.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Pancuronium</b> induces muscle paralysis by competitively blocking acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction, and its vagolytic side effect of causing tachycardia distinguishes it from other agents in its class.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
