  "4ae219da": {
    "title": "Papilledema",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Physical Findings"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Papilledema</b> is swelling of the optic disc due to <i>increased intracranial pressure (ICP)</i>. It is almost always bilateral and results from impaired axoplasmic flow within the optic nerve.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Elevated ICP is transmitted through the subarachnoid space, which is continuous with the optic nerve sheath. This increased pressure obstructs axoplasmic transport in the optic nerve axons, leading to swelling of the nerve head (optic disc).</li><li><b>Funduscopic Appearance:</b> Characterized by <mark>blurring of the optic disc margins</mark>, elevation of the optic disc, venous engorgement, and loss of the spontaneous venous pulsation. In severe cases, flame-shaped hemorrhages and cotton-wool spots may be present.</li><li><b>Causes of Increased ICP:</b> Brain tumors, [[c20521ce|intracranial hemorrhage]], [[meningitis]], [[0bc2f200|hydrocephalus]], and [[7c4e7c74|idiopathic intracranial hypertension]] (pseudotumor cerebri).</li><li><b>Symptoms:</b> Vision is often preserved initially, but patients may report transient visual obscurations. It is a sign of a serious underlying condition that can lead to permanent vision loss if the underlying cause is not treated. Patients often have headaches that are worse when lying down.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Papilledema is a key physical exam finding that signals elevated intracranial pressure. Its presence in a patient with a headache is a major red flag that warrants urgent neuroimaging.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Papilledema</b> is the eye's window to intracranial pressure; swelling of the optic disc is a direct physical consequence of high pressure within the skull being transmitted down the optic nerve sheath, serving as a critical sign of a potentially life-threatening neurological condition.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
