  "a2e1097b": {
    "title": "Paralysis",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Motor Deficits"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Paralysis</b> is the loss of muscle function in part of the body, which can be complete or partial (paresis). It occurs when the communication pathway between the brain and the muscles is disrupted.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Flaccid Paralysis:</b> Characterized by loss of muscle tone, muscle atrophy, and absent deep tendon reflexes. It is a sign of a <mark>lower motor neuron (LMN) lesion</mark>, affecting the nerve pathway from the anterior horn of the spinal cord to the muscle. Seen in [[75f2b918|poliomyelitis]] and [[ed52e40b|Guillain-Barr√© syndrome]].</li><li><b>Spastic Paralysis:</b> Characterized by increased muscle tone (spasticity), hyperreflexia, and a positive Babinski sign. It is a sign of an <mark>upper motor neuron (UMN) lesion</mark>, affecting motor pathways in the brain or spinal cord (e.g., corticospinal tract). Seen in [[c5da3c57|stroke]] and spinal cord injury.</li><li><b>Facial Paralysis:</b> A peripheral lesion of CN VII causes paralysis of the entire ipsilateral face. A central (UMN) lesion causes paralysis of the contralateral lower face only, sparing the forehead.</li><li><b>Osmotic Demyelination Syndrome:</b> Rapid correction of hyponatremia can cause acute paralysis and dysarthria.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The type of paralysis (flaccid vs. spastic) is crucial for localizing the neurological lesion to either the lower or upper motor neuron system.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The clinical character of <b>paralysis</b>‚Äîwhether it is flaccid with atrophy or spastic with hyperreflexia‚Äîprovides a fundamental distinction that allows clinicians to localize the site of injury to either the peripheral (LMN) or central (UMN) motor pathways.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
