  "61d955b1": {
    "title": "Paramedian Pontine Reticular Formation (PPRF)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Brainstem"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Paramedian Pontine Reticular Formation (PPRF)</b>, also known as the horizontal gaze center, is a collection of neurons in the pons that is essential for coordinating voluntary horizontal eye movements (saccades).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> The PPRF on one side controls gaze <u>toward the ipsilateral side</u>. For example, the right PPRF coordinates looking to the right.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> The PPRF receives input from the contralateral frontal eye fields. It then projects to the ipsilateral [[dd11dde6|abducens nerve (CN VI)]] nucleus.</li><li><b>Coordination:</b> The abducens nucleus does two things: 1) sends a signal via CN VI to contract the ipsilateral lateral rectus muscle, and 2) sends a signal via the contralateral [[59ad6172|medial longitudinal fasciculus (MLF)]] to the [[68c66997|oculomotor nerve (CN III)]] nucleus to contract the contralateral medial rectus muscle.</li><li><b>Lesion Effects:</b> A unilateral lesion of the PPRF results in an <mark>ipsilateral gaze palsy</mark>, meaning the patient cannot look toward the side of the lesion. The eyes will deviate away from the side of the lesion.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate a PPRF lesion from a frontal eye field (FEF) lesion. A destructive PPRF lesion causes eyes to look <i>away</i> from the lesion. A destructive FEF lesion causes eyes to look <i>toward</i> the lesion.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>PPRF</b> is the final common pathway for horizontal gaze; its unilateral activation orchestrates the precise, yoked contraction of one eye's lateral rectus and the other's medial rectus to direct both eyes in unison toward the ipsilateral side.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Contralateral Frontal Eye Field] --> B(PPRF); B --> C(Ipsilateral CN VI Nucleus); C --> D(Ipsilateral Lateral Rectus); C --> E(Contralateral MLF); E --> F(Contralateral CN III Nucleus); F --> G(Contralateral Medial Rectus);"
    },
    "connections": [
