  "7759e8c1": {
    "title": "Parasympathetic Nervous System (Cranial Innervation)",
    "primaryType": "physiology",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Autonomic",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Autonomic Nervous System"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>cranial division of the parasympathetic nervous system</b> provides involuntary \"rest and digest\" innervation to structures in the head, neck, thorax, and abdomen via four specific cranial nerves: the Oculomotor (III), Facial (VII), Glossopharyngeal (IX), and Vagus (X) nerves.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>CN III (Oculomotor):</b> Preganglionic fibers from the Edinger-Westphal nucleus synapse in the ciliary ganglion. Postganglionic fibers innervate the sphincter pupillae (causing miosis) and the ciliary muscle (causing [[81b5f5fe|accommodation]]).</li><li><b>CN VII (Facial):</b> Preganglionic fibers from the superior salivatory nucleus synapse in the pterygopalatine and submandibular ganglia. Postganglionic fibers stimulate secretion from the lacrimal, submandibular, and sublingual glands.</li><li><b>CN IX (Glossopharyngeal):</b> Preganglionic fibers from the inferior salivatory nucleus synapse in the otic ganglion. Postganglionic fibers stimulate secretion from the parotid gland.</li><li><b>CN X (Vagus):</b> The major parasympathetic nerve, providing innervation to the heart, lungs, and GI tract down to the splenic flexure. Its dorsal motor nucleus is a key autonomic center in the medulla.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the cranial nerves with parasympathetic function: CN III, VII, IX, and X.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The cranial outflow of the parasympathetic system precisely controls visceral functions in the head and torso, from constricting the pupil with CN III to slowing the heart with CN X, all originating from specific nuclei within the brainstem.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
