  "e7b51f5c": {
    "title": "Paraventricular Nucleus (PVN)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Endocrinology",
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Endocrine",
      "Anatomy",
      "Hypothalamus"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Paraventricular Nucleus (PVN)</b> is a key nucleus in the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]] that synthesizes and secretes several hormones, most notably <i>oxytocin</i> and corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH), and plays a central role in regulating stress, metabolism, and autonomic functions.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Hormone Synthesis:</b> Synthesizes <mark>oxytocin</mark>, which is then transported to and released from the posterior pituitary. It also synthesizes a smaller amount of ADH.</li><li><b>HPA Axis Control:</b> Synthesizes and secretes <mark>corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH)</mark> into the hypophyseal portal system, which stimulates the anterior pituitary to release ACTH, initiating the stress response.</li><li><b>Other Hormones:</b> Also produces thyrotropin-releasing hormone (TRH) and somatostatin.</li><li><b>Autonomic Regulation:</b> Projects to autonomic centers in the brainstem and spinal cord to regulate sympathetic and parasympathetic activity.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Associate the Paraventricular Nucleus primarily with <b>oxytocin</b> and <b>CRH</b> synthesis. Contrast it with the supraoptic nucleus, which primarily synthesizes ADH.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Paraventricular Nucleus</b> is a master regulator within the hypothalamus, integrating endocrine and autonomic signals and producing key hormones like oxytocin and CRH to control everything from childbirth and social bonding to the body's stress response.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Paraventricular Nucleus]; A --> B(Oxytocin --> Posterior Pituitary); A --> C(CRH --> Anterior Pituitary); A --> D(Autonomic Centers);"
