  "26efa771": {
    "title": "Parietal Lobe",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Cerebral Cortex"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Parietal Lobe</b> is one of the four major lobes of the cerebral cortex, located superior to the occipital and temporal lobes and posterior to the frontal lobe. It is primarily responsible for processing somatosensory information, spatial awareness, and navigation.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Primary Somatosensory Cortex:</b> Located in the postcentral gyrus, it receives sensory information (touch, pressure, pain, temperature, proprioception) from the contralateral side of the body via the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]].</li><li><b>Dominant Parietal Lobe (usually Left):</b> Damage can cause <mark>Gerstmann syndrome</mark>, which includes agraphia, [[8558c64b|acalculia]], finger agnosia, and left-right disorientation.</li><li><b>Non-dominant Parietal Lobe (usually Right):</b> Damage can cause <mark>hemispatial neglect syndrome</mark>, where the patient ignores the contralateral side of their body and space.</li><li><b>Optic Radiations:</b> The superior optic radiation (Baum's loop) passes through the parietal lobe. A lesion here causes a contralateral inferior quadrantanopia (\"pie on the floor\").</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Lesions of the parietal lobe are all about sensory and spatial deficits. Remember to distinguish between the functions of the dominant (language-related, calculation) and non-dominant (spatial awareness) sides.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Parietal Lobe</b> integrates sensory information to form a coherent perception of the world and our relationship to it; lesions here do not cause simple blindness or paralysis but rather profound deficits in spatial awareness and interpretation, such as hemineglect.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
