  "9f603521": {
    "title": "Parinaud Syndrome",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Oncology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brainstem Syndromes"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Parinaud Syndrome</b>, also known as dorsal midbrain syndrome, is a neurological condition resulting from compression of the dorsal midbrain (specifically the superior colliculus and pretectal area), characterized by a classic triad of vertical gaze palsy, pupillary abnormalities, and convergence-retraction nystagmus.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly caused by a <mark>pineal gland tumor</mark> (e.g., pinealoma, germinoma) compressing the dorsal midbrain. Other causes include stroke, [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]], or obstructive [[0bc2f200|hydrocephalus]].</li><li><b>Classic Triad:</b><br>1. <b>Upward Gaze Palsy:</b> The most prominent feature is the inability to look up.<br>2. <b>Pupillary Light-Near Dissociation:</b> Pupils do not constrict to light but do constrict with [[81b5f5fe|accommodation]] (pseudo-Argyll Robertson pupils).<br>3. <b>Convergence-Retraction Nystagmus:</b> On attempted upward gaze, the eyes converge and retract into the orbits.</li><li><b>Other Signs:</b> Eyelid retraction (Collier's sign) may also be present.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A young male patient presenting with an inability to look up, headache (from hydrocephalus), and pupillary abnormalities should make you strongly suspect a pineal tumor causing Parinaud syndrome.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Parinaud Syndrome</b> is a specific constellation of neuro-ophthalmologic signs that precisely localizes a lesion to the dorsal midbrain, with the upward gaze palsy being the most striking feature resulting from compression of the vertical gaze center.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Pineal Tumor] --Compresses--> B(Dorsal Midbrain); B --> C(Parinaud Syndrome); C --> D(Upward Gaze Palsy); C --> E(Pupillary Light-Near Dissociation); C --> F(Convergence-Retraction Nystagmus);"
