    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Ophthalmoplegia</b> is the paralysis or weakness of one or more of the extraocular muscles that control eye movement. It can be caused by lesions affecting the cranial nerves (III, IV, VI), their nuclei in the brainstem, or the muscles themselves.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Internuclear Ophthalmoplegia (INO):</b> A specific gaze palsy caused by a lesion in the <mark>medial longitudinal fasciculus (MLF)</mark>. It results in impaired adduction of the ipsilateral eye and nystagmus of the abducting contralateral eye. Bilateral INO is highly suggestive of [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]].</li><li><b>Cranial Nerve Palsies:</b> Lesions of [[68c66997|CN III]], [[bba6093a|CN IV]], or [[dd11dde6|CN VI]] each produce characteristic patterns of ophthalmoplegia.</li><li><b>Cavernous Sinus Syndrome:</b> Can cause painful ophthalmoplegia involving multiple cranial nerves (III, IV, VI, V1, V2) as they pass through the [[c260efc8|cavernous sinus]].</li><li><b>Wernicke Encephalopathy:</b> A classic triad of encephalopathy, oculomotor dysfunction (ophthalmoplegia, nystagmus), and gait ataxia due to thiamine deficiency.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> [[58c684bd|Internuclear ophthalmoplegia]] is a key finding to recognize. Remember <b>INO</b> = <b>I</b>psilateral adduction failure, <b>N</b>ystagmus <b>O</b>pposite.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Ophthalmoplegia</b> is a critical neurological sign that points to dysfunction along the complex pathways controlling eye movement, with specific patterns like [[58c684bd|internuclear ophthalmoplegia]] precisely localizing lesions within the brainstem.</p>",
