    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Opioid analgesics</b> are a class of potent pain-relieving drugs that act as agonists at opioid receptors in the central and peripheral nervous systems to modulate the perception of pain.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Act as agonists at opioid receptors (Œº, Œ¥, Œ∫), which are G-protein coupled receptors. They close presynaptic Ca<sup>2+</sup> channels (decreasing neurotransmitter release) and open postsynaptic K<sup>+</sup> channels (causing hyperpolarization and decreased neuronal excitability).</li><li><b>Examples:</b> Morphine, fentanyl, codeine, meperidine, methadone, buprenorphine.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Management of moderate to severe acute and chronic pain, diarrhea (loperamide), cough suppression (dextromethorphan), and treatment of [[d268ace0|acute pulmonary edema]] (morphine).</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> <mark>Respiratory depression</mark> is the most life-threatening side effect. Others include sedation, constipation, miosis (pinpoint pupils), nausea/vomiting, and high potential for addiction and dependence.</li><li><b>Overdose Treatment:</b> An opioid overdose (presenting with coma, respiratory depression, and miosis) is treated with an opioid antagonist like <mark>naloxone</mark>.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Tolerance develops to most effects of opioids (analgesia, sedation) but notably <u>not</u> to <mark>constipation and miosis</mark>.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Opioid analgesics</b> provide powerful pain relief by mimicking endogenous endorphins at opioid receptors, but their clinical utility is limited by a narrow therapeutic window and significant adverse effects, most dangerously respiratory depression, which can be rapidly reversed by naloxone.</p>",
