      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Major Subtypes:</b> The three classic subtypes are <b>Œº (mu)</b>, <b>Œ¥ (delta)</b>, and <b>Œ∫ (kappa)</b>.</li><li><b>Endogenous Ligands:</b> Œ≤-endorphin (Œº), enkephalin (Œ¥), and dynorphin (Œ∫).</li><li><b>Œº-Receptor:</b> The primary mediator of the analgesic effects of most clinically used opioids (e.g., morphine). Also responsible for euphoria, respiratory depression, and physical dependence.</li><li><b>Signal Transduction:</b> As G<sub>i/o</sub>-coupled receptors, their activation leads to inhibition of adenylyl cyclase, closing of presynaptic voltage-gated Ca<sup>2+</sup> channels (‚Üì neurotransmitter release), and opening of postsynaptic K<sup>+</sup> channels (hyperpolarization).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The Œº-receptor is the most important for clinical pharmacology, as it mediates both the desired analgesic effects and the most dangerous side effects (respiratory depression) of drugs like morphine and fentanyl.</li></ul>",
