    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Optic Nerve (CN II)</b> is a paired cranial nerve that transmits visual information from the retina to the brain. Uniquely, it is an extension of the central nervous system rather than a true peripheral nerve, and is myelinated by [[a24f9747|oligodendrocytes]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Purely sensory, responsible for vision.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Composed of the axons of retinal ganglion cells. It exits the orbit via the optic canal, joins the contralateral optic nerve at the optic chiasm, and continues as the optic tract to the lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus.</li><li><b>Clinical Examination:</b> Assessed by testing visual acuity, visual fields, and pupillary light reflexes. The optic disc (the head of the optic nerve) can be visualized on fundoscopy.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> A complete lesion of the optic nerve causes ipsilateral monocular blindness (anopia) and an afferent pupillary defect (Marcus Gunn pupil). [[98a63a59|Optic neuritis]], an inflammation of the optic nerve, is a common presentation of [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Because it is a CNS tract, the optic nerve is affected by CNS diseases. Its myelination by [[a24f9747|oligodendrocytes]] makes it a target in [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Optic Nerve</b> is functionally a tract of the brain extending to the eye, not a peripheral nerve. This distinction is clinically crucial as it explains its involvement in CNS-specific pathologies like [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]] and its myelination by oligodendrocytes, not Schwann cells.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
