    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Optic neuritis</b> is an inflammatory, demyelinating condition of the [[66b11030|optic nerve (CN II)]] that causes acute, monocular vision loss, and is the most common initial presentation of <i>Multiple Sclerosis</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Strongly associated with [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis (MS)]]. It is often the first demyelinating event in MS.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Characterized by a triad of <mark>monocular vision loss</mark> (developing over hours to days), <mark>pain with eye movement</mark>, and loss of color vision (dyschromatopsia).</li><li><b>Physical Exam Findings:</b> The key finding is a <mark>relative afferent pupillary defect (RAPD)</mark>, also known as a Marcus Gunn pupil. The optic disc may appear normal or swollen on fundoscopy.</li><li><b>Prognosis:</b> Vision typically improves over several weeks, often with steroid treatment, but some residual deficits may remain.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A young woman presenting with sudden, painful vision loss in one eye and a Marcus Gunn pupil is the classic vignette for optic neuritis and should raise high suspicion for underlying [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Optic neuritis</b> is the quintessential ophthalmologic manifestation of [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]], where an autoimmune attack on the optic nerve's myelin sheath leads to a characteristic triad of painful monocular vision loss, dyschromatopsia, and an afferent pupillary defect.</p>",
