    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Optic neuropathy</b> is damage to the [[66b11030|optic nerve (CN II)]] from any cause, leading to vision loss and changes in the appearance of the optic disc. It can be caused by ischemia, inflammation, compression, toxins, or hereditary factors.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Glaucomatous Optic Neuropathy:</b> The most common form. A progressive neuropathy characterized by optic disc cupping and visual field loss, typically associated with elevated intraocular pressure.</li><li><b>Ischemic Optic Neuropathy:</b> Caused by infarction of the optic nerve head. Can be arteritic (due to giant cell arteritis) or non-arteritic (more common, associated with vascular risk factors). Presents with sudden, painless, monocular vision loss.</li><li><b>Inflammatory Optic Neuropathy:</b> This is [[98a63a59|optic neuritis]], strongly associated with [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]].</li><li><b>Compressive Optic Neuropathy:</b> Caused by a mass lesion (e.g., [[5f3188bd|pituitary adenoma]], meningioma) compressing the optic nerve, chiasm, or tract.</li><li><b>Toxic/Nutritional Optic Neuropathy:</b> Caused by toxins (e.g., methanol, ethambutol) or nutritional deficiencies (e.g., B12).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The pattern of vision loss and associated symptoms helps determine the etiology. Sudden, painless loss in an elderly patient suggests ischemic neuropathy. Pain with eye movement in a young woman suggests [[98a63a59|optic neuritis]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Optic neuropathy</b> is the final common pathway of damage to the optic nerve, regardless of the cause. The clinical challenge lies in identifying the underlying etiology‚Äîbe it pressure, ischemia, inflammation, or compression‚Äîto guide appropriate management and prevent irreversible blindness.</p>",
