    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Orbital cellulitis</b> is a serious infection of the fat and muscles located <i>posterior</i> to the orbital septum, which can lead to vision loss and intracranial complications. It is an ophthalmologic emergency.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly arises from the spread of a bacterial sinus infection (especially ethmoid sinusitis) through the thin lamina papyracea. Other causes include trauma or dental infections. Common pathogens are <i>Staphylococcus aureus</i> and <i>Streptococcus</i> species.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients present with eyelid swelling and erythema, similar to preseptal cellulitis, but with additional <mark>\"red flag\" signs</mark>.</li><li><b>Key Differentiating Features:</b> The presence of <mark>pain with eye movements</mark>, <mark>proptosis</mark> (bulging eye), and <mark>ophthalmoplegia</mark> (restricted eye movements) or diplopia distinguishes orbital from [[087079b0|preseptal cellulitis]]. Vision may be impaired.</li><li><b>Complications:</b> Can lead to vision loss (from optic nerve compression), [[a830692a|cavernous sinus thrombosis]], meningitis, or brain abscess.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Pain on eye movement is the critical sign that separates orbital cellulitis from the less severe [[087079b0|preseptal cellulitis]]. This finding mandates urgent imaging (CT scan) and inpatient treatment with IV antibiotics.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Orbital cellulitis</b> is an infection that has breached the orbital septum, putting the vital structures of the orbit at risk. The presence of pain with eye movements, proptosis, or ophthalmoplegia signals this deeper involvement and elevates the condition to a true emergency requiring immediate intervention.</p>",
