    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Organ of Corti</b> is the sensory organ of hearing, located within the cochlea of the inner ear. It contains the mechanoreceptive hair cells that transduce the mechanical energy of sound vibrations into nerve impulses.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Sits on the basilar membrane within the scala media of the cochlea.</li><li><b>Structure:</b> Composed of sensory hair cells (one row of inner hair cells, three rows of outer hair cells) and various supporting cells. The stereocilia of the hair cells are in contact with the overlying tectorial membrane.</li><li><b>Function (Transduction):</b> Sound vibrations cause the basilar membrane to move, creating a shearing force between the basilar and tectorial membranes. This force bends the stereocilia of the hair cells, opening ion channels and causing depolarization, which triggers neurotransmitter release and an action potential in the auditory nerve.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Damage to the hair cells is the cause of <mark>sensorineural hearing loss</mark>. This can be due to excessive noise exposure (<mark>noise-induced hearing loss</mark>), aging ([[0957fd39|presbycusis]]), or ototoxic drugs.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that high-frequency sounds are detected at the stiff, narrow base of the cochlea, while low-frequency sounds are detected at the flexible, wide apex. Noise-induced hearing loss typically damages the hair cells at the base first, leading to high-frequency hearing loss.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Organ of Corti</b> is the biological microphone of the inner ear, where the mechanical vibrations of sound are precisely converted into electrical signals by the bending of specialized hair cells, a delicate process vulnerable to damage from noise, age, and toxins.</p>",
