    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Organum Vasculosum of the Lamina Terminalis (OVLT)</b> is one of the circumventricular organs, a highly vascularized structure in the anterior wall of the third ventricle that lacks a normal [[dd47b9cc|blood-brain barrier]] and contains osmosensory neurons critical for detecting plasma osmolarity.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Anterior wall of the third ventricle.</li><li><b>Function:</b> As a circumventricular organ, its fenestrated capillaries allow it to directly sense the composition of the blood. It contains <mark>osmoreceptors</mark> that detect changes in plasma osmolarity.</li><li><b>Role in Thirst and ADH Release:</b> When the OVLT detects an increase in plasma osmolarity (hypertonicity), it stimulates thirst and signals the supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei of the hypothalamus to release <mark>antidiuretic hormone (ADH)</mark>.</li><li><b>Role in Fever:</b> The OVLT is also a site where circulating pyrogens like PGE<sub>2</sub> can act on the brain to induce fever by altering the hypothalamic temperature set-point.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the OVLT as the brain's primary 'osmostat,' constantly sampling the blood to regulate water balance through thirst and ADH secretion.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>OVLT's</b> lack of a blood-brain barrier is its key functional feature, allowing its specialized osmosensory neurons to act as a direct interface between the bloodstream and the hypothalamus, thereby orchestrating the body's response to dehydration.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
