  "bb51a0dc": {
    "title": "Osmoreceptors",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Physiology",
      "Endocrinology",
      "Neuroscience",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Endocrine",
      "Physiology",
      "Hypothalamic-Pituitary Axis"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Osmoreceptors</b> are specialized neurons, primarily located in the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]], that respond to changes in the osmotic pressure (osmolarity) of the extracellular fluid, thereby regulating the body's water balance through thirst and the secretion of antidiuretic hormone (ADH).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Primarily found in the circumventricular organs of the brain that lack a blood-brain barrier, especially the <mark>Organum Vasculosum of the Lamina Terminalis (OVLT)</mark> and the subfornical organ (SFO). Also located within the supraoptic nucleus itself.</li><li><b>Mechanism:</b> These neurons function as mechanoreceptors, shrinking or swelling in response to changes in plasma osmolarity. Cell shrinkage (in a hypertonic state) opens stretch-inhibited cation channels, leading to depolarization and firing.</li><li><b>Function:</b> When stimulated by increased plasma osmolarity, osmoreceptors trigger two key responses: 1) Stimulation of the sensation of <mark>thirst</mark>. 2) Stimulation of ADH synthesis and release from the posterior pituitary.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> Dysfunction of this system can lead to disorders of water balance like diabetes insipidus or SIADH.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The osmoreceptor system is exquisitely sensitive, responding to as little as a 1-2% change in plasma osmolarity to maintain tight control over the body's water balance.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Osmoreceptors</b> are the body's cellular osmometers, translating minute changes in blood concentration into the powerful physiological drives of thirst and ADH release to defend plasma osmolarity with remarkable precision.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Increased Plasma Osmolarity] --> B(Osmoreceptor Shrinkage); B --> C(Neuron Firing); C --> D(Thirst Sensation); C --> E(ADH Release); E --> F(Renal Water Reabsorption); D & F --> G(Decreased Plasma Osmolarity);"
    },
