  "7a680d3d": {
    "title": "Osmotic Demyelination Syndrome (ODS)",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pathology",
      "Emergency Medicine",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Demyelinating Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Osmotic Demyelination Syndrome (ODS)</b>, classically known as <b>Central Pontine Myelinolysis</b>, is an acute, iatrogenic demyelination of the central nervous system caused by the overly rapid correction of chronic hyponatremia.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> In chronic hyponatremia, brain cells adapt by extruding organic osmolytes to prevent swelling. If the serum sodium is corrected too quickly, the extracellular space becomes hypertonic relative to the brain cells. Water is rapidly pulled out of the cells, leading to cell shrinkage and demyelination, particularly in osmotically sensitive areas.</li><li><b>Location of Lesion:</b> The <mark>pons</mark> is the most classic and severely affected location (Central Pontine Myelinolysis), but demyelination can also occur in extrapontine sites like the basal ganglia and cerebellum.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Symptoms typically develop 2-6 days after the rapid sodium correction. Presents with acute paralysis (quadriplegia), dysarthria, dysphagia, diplopia, and loss of consciousness. Can progress to a <mark>\"locked-in\" syndrome</mark>.</li><li><b>Prevention:</b> The key is slow and controlled correction of chronic hyponatremia. Correction rates should generally not exceed 8-12 mEq/L in 24 hours.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the mnemonic: \"From <b>low</b> to <b>high</b>, your <b>pons</b> will <b>die</b>.\" (ODS). \"From <b>high</b> to <b>low</b>, your <b>brain</b> will <b>blow</b>.\" (Cerebral edema from rapid correction of hypernatremia).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Osmotic Demyelination Syndrome</b> is a devastating iatrogenic injury caused by correcting chronic hyponatremia too quickly, forcing brain cells that had adapted to a low-salt environment to suddenly dehydrate, leading to demyelination, especially in the vulnerable pons.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
