    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Otitis Externa</b>, commonly known as \"swimmer's ear,\" is an inflammation or infection of the external auditory canal, the tube leading from the outer ear to the eardrum.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly caused by bacteria, with <mark>Pseudomonas aeruginosa</mark> being the most frequent pathogen, followed by <i>Staphylococcus aureus</i>. Fungal infections (otomycosis) can also occur.</li><li><b>Risk Factors:</b> Water exposure (swimming) that macerates the skin of the ear canal, trauma from cotton swabs or hearing aids, and dermatologic conditions like eczema.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> The hallmark symptom is severe ear pain (<mark>otalgia</mark>) that is characteristically worsened by manipulation of the pinna or tragus. Other symptoms include pruritus, purulent discharge, and a feeling of fullness in the ear.</li><li><b>Malignant Otitis Externa:</b> A severe, necrotizing form that can spread to the skull base, causing osteomyelitis. It is a medical emergency seen almost exclusively in elderly diabetic or immunocompromised patients.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Pain on pulling the pinna is the key physical exam finding that differentiates otitis externa from [[a03641af|otitis media]], where the pain is internal and not affected by external manipulation.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Otitis Externa</b> is an infection of the skin lining the ear canal, not the middle ear space. Its diagnosis hinges on the classic sign of exquisite tenderness with external ear manipulation, a feature absent in middle ear infections.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
