    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Otitis Media</b> is an inflammation or infection of the middle ear, the air-filled space behind the eardrum. Acute otitis media (AOM) is one of the most common childhood infections.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Typically follows a viral upper respiratory infection, which leads to eustachian tube dysfunction and obstruction. This causes negative pressure and fluid accumulation in the middle ear, which then becomes secondarily infected by bacteria colonizing the nasopharynx.</li><li><b>Common Pathogens:</b> The three most common bacterial causes are <mark>Streptococcus pneumoniae</mark>, non-typeable <mark>Haemophilus influenzae</mark>, and <mark>Moraxella catarrhalis</mark>.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Infants and young children present with fever, irritability, and ear pulling. Otoscopy reveals a <mark>bulging, erythematous tympanic membrane</mark> with poor mobility.</li><li><b>Complications:</b> Can lead to tympanic membrane perforation, mastoiditis, meningitis, or brain abscess. Recurrent episodes can cause conductive hearing loss.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The classic triad of pathogens for AOM is <i>S. pneumoniae</i>, <i>H. influenzae</i> (non-typeable), and <i>M. catarrhalis</i>. Remember that the introduction of the pneumococcal conjugate vaccine has decreased the incidence of AOM caused by <i>S. pneumoniae</i>.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Acute Otitis Media</b> is fundamentally a complication of eustachian tube dysfunction following a viral URI, where trapped fluid in the middle ear becomes a culture medium for nasopharyngeal bacteria, leading to a painful, bulging eardrum.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
