    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Otology</b> is the branch of medicine that studies the normal and pathological anatomy and physiology of the ear, as well as its diseases, diagnosis, and treatment. It encompasses hearing and balance disorders.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Anatomy:</b> The ear is divided into the [[944bb118|outer ear]] (pinna, canal), middle ear ([[3aea8cac|ossicles]]), and inner ear (cochlea, vestibular system).</li><li><b>Physiology:</b> Hearing involves the transduction of sound waves into neural signals by the [[2e814378|organ of Corti]]. Balance is maintained by the vestibular system (semicircular canals, utricle, saccule).</li><li><b>Common Pathologies:</b> Include [[88e6f77e|hearing loss]] (conductive vs. sensorineural), [[a03641af|otitis media]], [[67063a58|otitis externa]], and vertigo (e.g., BPPV, [[6f2228c1|M√©ni√®re disease]]).</li><li><b>Key Nerves:</b> The [[6fded3e7|vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII)]] is central to otology, carrying both auditory and vestibular information to the brainstem.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A solid understanding of the distinction between conductive and sensorineural hearing loss, and between peripheral and central vertigo, is essential for otology questions.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Otology</b> integrates the complex anatomy and physiology of the ear to diagnose and manage disorders of its two primary functions: hearing and balance, which are subserved by the cochlear and vestibular systems, respectively.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
