      "definition": "<p><b>Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus (NPH)</b> is a form of <i>communicating hydrocephalus</i> in older adults, characterized by ventricular enlargement with only intermittently elevated cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) pressure, leading to a classic clinical triad of gait apraxia, cognitive dysfunction, and urinary incontinence.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The exact cause is often idiopathic, but it is thought to result from impaired CSF absorption at the arachnoid granulations. This leads to ventricular expansion, which stretches the corona radiata fibers.</li><li><b>Clinical Triad (\"Wet, Wobbly, and Wacky\"):</b><br>1. <b>Wobbly:</b> Gait apraxia is often the first and most prominent symptom. Described as a <mark>magnetic gait</mark>, where the feet appear stuck to the floor.<br>2. <b>Wacky:</b> Cognitive dysfunction/dementia.<br>3. <b>Wet:</b> Urinary incontinence/urgency.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> Brain imaging (CT or MRI) shows <mark>ventriculomegaly</mark> out of proportion to sulcal enlargement. A lumbar puncture (LP) will show a normal opening pressure.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> A large-volume LP that temporarily improves symptoms is both diagnostic and predictive of response to treatment. The definitive treatment is surgical placement of a <mark>ventriculoperitoneal (VP) shunt</mark> to divert CSF.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> NPH is a reversible cause of dementia. The triad of gait disturbance, dementia, and urinary incontinence in an elderly patient should immediately bring NPH to mind.</li></ul>",
