    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Nystagmus</b> is a condition of involuntary, rhythmic eye movements, which can be horizontal, vertical, or rotary. It is a sign of dysfunction in the systems responsible for controlling eye position and movement, such as the vestibular system or the cerebellum.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Jerk Nystagmus:</b> The most common form, characterized by a slow drift of the eyes in one direction (slow phase) followed by a rapid corrective jerk back in the opposite direction (fast phase). Nystagmus is named for the direction of the fast phase.</li><li><b>Peripheral vs. Central Vertigo:</b> The characteristics of nystagmus help differentiate the cause of vertigo. <mark>Peripheral vertigo</mark> (inner ear) typically causes horizontal or torsional nystagmus that is suppressed by visual fixation. <mark>Central vertigo</mark> (brainstem/cerebellum) can cause purely vertical or purely torsional nystagmus that is not suppressed by fixation.</li><li><b>Internuclear Ophthalmoplegia (INO):</b> A lesion of the MLF causes nystagmus in the <mark>abducting</mark> eye during horizontal gaze.</li><li><b>Friedreich Ataxia:</b> Nystagmus is a common finding in this neurodegenerative disease due to cerebellar involvement.</li><li><b>Retinoblastoma:</b> Can present with nystagmus in an infant if the tumor affects central vision.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Purely vertical or purely torsional nystagmus is a major red flag for a central (brainstem or cerebellar) lesion.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Nystagmus</b> is a key objective sign of vestibular or cerebellar dysfunction, and a careful analysis of its direction, trajectory, and response to fixation can precisely localize the lesion to either the peripheral or central nervous system.</p>",
