    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Ocular motility</b> refers to the movement of the eyes, which is controlled by six extraocular muscles innervated by three cranial nerves (III, IV, and VI). These movements allow for fixation, tracking, and scanning of the visual environment.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Extraocular Muscles:</b> Four rectus muscles (superior, inferior, medial, lateral) and two oblique muscles (superior, inferior).</li><li><b>Cranial Nerve Innervation:</b> Mnemonic: <b>LR<sub>6</sub>SO<sub>4</sub>R<sub>3</sub></b> (<b>L</b>ateral <b>R</b>ectus by CN <b>VI</b>, <b>S</b>uperior <b>O</b>blique by CN <b>IV</b>, <b>R</b>est by CN <b>III</b>).</li><li><b>Primary Actions:</b><br> - <b>Abduction:</b> [[f7b5ee5d|Lateral Rectus]] (CN VI)<br> - <b>Adduction:</b> Medial Rectus (CN III)<br> - <b>Elevation:</b> Superior Rectus & Inferior Oblique (CN III)<br> - <b>Depression:</b> Inferior Rectus (CN III) & Superior Oblique (CN IV)</li><li><b>Clinical Testing:</b> Assessed by having the patient follow a target in the six cardinal positions of gaze (the 'H' pattern).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> To isolate the vertical actions of the rectus muscles, have the patient look out (abduct). To isolate the vertical actions of the oblique muscles, have the patient look in (adduct).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The precise and coordinated control of <b>ocular motility</b> by cranial nerves III, IV, and VI allows for the complex eye movements necessary for binocular vision; any weakness or paralysis (ophthalmoplegia) results in misalignment and diplopia.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
