  "68c66997": {
    "title": "Oculomotor Nerve (CN III)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Cranial Nerves"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Oculomotor Nerve (CN III)</b> is a cranial nerve that controls most of the eye's movements, including constriction of the pupil and maintaining an open eyelid. It contains both somatic motor and visceral motor (parasympathetic) fibers.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Motor Function:</b> Innervates the superior, medial, and inferior rectus muscles, the inferior oblique muscle, and the levator palpebrae superioris (eyelid elevation).</li><li><b>Parasympathetic Function:</b> Carries preganglionic parasympathetic fibers from the Edinger-Westphal nucleus to the ciliary ganglion. Postganglionic fibers innervate the sphincter pupillae (pupillary constriction) and the ciliary muscle ([[81b5f5fe|accommodation]]).</li><li><b>Palsy Presentation:</b> A complete CN III palsy results in a <mark>\"down and out\"</mark> eye position (due to unopposed action of the lateral rectus and superior oblique), severe [[6202e6af|ptosis]], and a fixed, dilated pupil (<mark>\"blown pupil\"</mark>).</li><li><b>Pupil Sparing vs. Pupil Involving:</b> A compressive lesion (e.g., PCom aneurysm, uncal herniation) typically affects the superficial parasympathetic fibers first, causing a blown pupil. An ischemic lesion (e.g., diabetic neuropathy) often affects the deeper motor fibers while sparing the pupil.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of a CN III palsy with a dilated, nonreactive pupil is a neurological emergency, highly suggestive of an aneurysm compressing the nerve.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Oculomotor Nerve</b> is the primary motor nerve of the eye, and its dual somatic and parasympathetic functions mean that a complete palsy presents with a dramatic triad of a deviated eye, a drooping eyelid, and a dilated pupil, with the pupillary involvement being a key sign for differentiating compressive from ischemic causes.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "controls",
