  "84b5e4f6": {
    "title": "Oculosympathetic Pathway",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Autonomic Nervous System"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Oculosympathetic Pathway</b> is a three-neuron chain that provides sympathetic innervation to the eye and face, controlling pupillary dilation, eyelid elevation, and facial sweating.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>First-Order Neuron (Central):</b> Originates in the posterior [[89e86633|hypothalamus]], descends through the brainstem and synapses in the ciliospinal center of Budge (C8-T2) in the spinal cord.</li><li><b>Second-Order Neuron (Preganglionic):</b> Exits the spinal cord at T1, travels up the sympathetic chain, and synapses in the <mark>superior cervical ganglion</mark>. This neuron passes over the apex of the lung.</li><li><b>Third-Order Neuron (Postganglionic):</b> Ascends along the internal carotid artery, passes through the [[c260efc8|cavernous sinus]], and travels with the ophthalmic division of the trigeminal nerve (CN V1) to innervate the dilator pupillae muscle, superior tarsal muscle, and facial sweat glands.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> Disruption of this pathway at any point results in <mark>Horner Syndrome</mark> (ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The location of the lesion along the three-neuron arc determines the pattern of anhidrosis. A lesion of the 1st or 2nd neuron causes anhidrosis of the entire ipsilateral face, while a lesion of the 3rd neuron (distal to the carotid bifurcation) spares sweating on the forehead.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The long and circuitous route of the <b>Oculosympathetic Pathway</b>‚Äîfrom the hypothalamus down the spinal cord, up the neck, and back into the head‚Äîmakes it vulnerable to a wide range of pathologies, from brainstem strokes to apical lung tumors, all of which can produce the same classic triad of Horner syndrome.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[1st Order: Hypothalamus] --> B(Ciliospinal Center C8-T2); B --> C[2nd Order: Superior Cervical Ganglion]; C --> D[3rd Order: Eye & Face];"
    },
    "connections": [
