  "c6cf9420": {
    "title": "Olfaction",
    "primaryType": "physiology",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Physiology",
      "Special Senses",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Cranial Nerves"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Olfaction</b> is the sense of smell, a chemical sense mediated by olfactory receptor neurons in the nasal cavity that detect odorant molecules and transmit this information to the brain via the [[4487bc38|olfactory nerve (CN I)]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Receptors:</b> Olfactory receptor neurons are located in the olfactory epithelium in the superior part of the nasal cavity.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Axons of these neurons form the olfactory nerve (CN I), which passes through the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone to synapse in the olfactory bulb. From the bulb, olfactory tracts project directly to the primary olfactory cortex (piriform cortex) in the temporal lobe.</li><li><b>Unique Feature:</b> Olfaction is the <u>only</u> sensory modality that does not have a primary relay in the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]] before projecting to the cortex.</li><li><b>Limbic System Connection:</b> The olfactory cortex has strong connections to the [[73ace357|limbic system]], particularly the amygdala and hippocampus, which is why smells can evoke strong emotions and memories.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> Loss of smell is called anosmia. It can be caused by trauma (shearing of olfactory nerve fibers at the cribriform plate), viral infections, or neurodegenerative diseases like Parkinson's and Alzheimer's.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Olfaction</b> is a unique and primitive sense that bypasses the thalamic relay common to all other senses, projecting directly to cortical areas intertwined with the [[73ace357|limbic system]], providing a direct and powerful link between smells, emotions, and memory.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_mediated_by",
