  "4487bc38": {
    "title": "Olfactory Nerve (CN I)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "Special Senses",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Cranial Nerves"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Olfactory Nerve (CN I)</b> is the first and shortest cranial nerve, a purely sensory nerve responsible for the sense of <i>olfaction</i> (smell).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Special visceral afferent (SVA) fibers for smell.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Composed of the axons of olfactory receptor neurons located in the olfactory epithelium of the nasal cavity. These axons pass through the <mark>cribriform plate</mark> of the ethmoid bone to synapse on mitral cells in the olfactory bulb.</li><li><b>Central Projections:</b> The olfactory tract then projects from the bulb to the primary olfactory cortex (piriform cortex) without relaying through the thalamus.</li><li><b>Lesion Effects:</b> Damage to the olfactory nerve results in <mark>anosmia</mark> (loss of smell). This can be caused by head trauma (shearing forces at the cribriform plate), viral infections, or tumors at the base of the frontal lobe (e.g., olfactory groove meningioma).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Anosmia following a frontal head injury is a classic presentation of CN I damage due to shearing of its delicate fibers as they pass through the cribriform plate.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Olfactory Nerve</b> is unique among cranial nerves as it is a direct extension of the telencephalon, consists of unmyelinated axons that regenerate, and its pathway is the only sensory system to bypass the thalamus, projecting directly to the cortex.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_responsible_for",
        "to": "c6cf9420"
