  "a24f9747": {
    "title": "Oligodendrocytes",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Histology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Glial Cells"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Oligodendrocytes</b> are a type of glial cell found in the central nervous system (CNS) whose primary function is to produce the <i>myelin sheath</i> that insulates neuronal axons, allowing for rapid saltatory conduction of action potentials.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Myelination of axons in the CNS (brain, spinal cord, and optic nerve). A single oligodendrocyte can myelinate <mark>multiple axons</mark> (up to ~30).</li><li><b>Appearance:</b> Histologically, they have a \"fried egg\" appearance with a round nucleus and clear cytoplasm, especially prominent in [[c932ed4e|oligodendrogliomas]].</li><li><b>Embryonic Origin:</b> Derived from neuroectoderm of the neural tube.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> They are the primary target of autoimmune attack in <mark>[[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]]</mark>. They are also damaged in progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy (PML) by the JC virus and in various leukodystrophies.</li><li><b>Distinction from Schwann Cells:</b> [[c65a8909|Schwann cells]] perform the same function (myelination) but in the peripheral nervous system (PNS). A key difference is that one Schwann cell myelinates only one segment of a single axon.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The destruction of oligodendrocytes is the central pathological event in [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Oligodendrocytes</b> are the myelin-producing cells of the CNS, with each cell extending multiple processes to ensheath numerous axons; this 'one-to-many' relationship contrasts with Schwann cells and explains the widespread, patchy nature of demyelination when these cells are destroyed in diseases like MS.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
        "to": "glial_cell"
      },
