  "c932ed4e": {
    "title": "Oligodendroglioma",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Oncology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brain Tumors"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>An <b>Oligodendroglioma</b> is a relatively rare, slow-growing primary brain tumor derived from [[a24f9747|oligodendrocytes]]. It is most commonly found in the cerebral hemispheres of adults, particularly the frontal lobes.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Typically located in the white matter of the cerebral hemispheres, with a predilection for the <mark>frontal lobes</mark>.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Often presents with seizures due to its cortical location. Other symptoms include headaches and focal neurologic deficits.</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> On CT scans, these tumors are often <mark>calcified</mark>. On MRI, they appear as well-circumscribed masses.</li><li><b>Histology:</b> Characterized by sheets of uniform cells with round nuclei, clear cytoplasm, and well-defined cell borders, creating a classic <mark>\"fried egg\" appearance</mark>. A delicate network of branching capillaries, often described as a <mark>\"chicken-wire\" pattern</mark>, is also characteristic.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of a calcified frontal lobe tumor in an adult presenting with seizures, and a \"fried egg\" appearance on histology, is pathognomonic for an oligodendroglioma.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Oligodendroglioma</b> is defined by its classic histological appearance of \"fried egg\" cells and a \"chicken-wire\" vascular pattern, which reflects its origin from the myelin-producing cells of the CNS and often presents with seizures due to its typical frontal lobe location.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
