  "5ea7b741": {
    "title": "Open-Angle Glaucoma",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Geriatrics",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Pathology"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Open-Angle Glaucoma</b> is the most common type of [[3ce6c035|glaucoma]], a chronic, progressive optic neuropathy characterized by an open, normal-appearing anterior chamber angle and increased intraocular pressure (IOP) due to decreased aqueous humor outflow.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The primary defect is an increased resistance to aqueous humor drainage through the <mark>trabecular meshwork</mark>. The anterior chamber angle itself is open and not obstructed.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Typically asymptomatic in the early stages, earning it the name \"silent thief of sight.\" The first noticeable symptom is often a gradual loss of <mark>peripheral vision</mark>, which progresses to central vision loss and blindness if untreated.</li><li><b>Risk Factors:</b> Increased age, African American ethnicity, family history, and diabetes mellitus.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> Diagnosed based on elevated IOP, characteristic optic disc cupping on fundoscopy, and corresponding visual field defects on perimetry.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> The goal is to lower IOP. First-line agents are typically prostaglandin analogs (e.g., latanoprost) which increase uveoscleral outflow, or beta-blockers (e.g., timolol) which decrease aqueous humor production.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from angle-closure glaucoma: open-angle is chronic, painless, and involves peripheral vision loss, while acute angle-closure is sudden, painful, and presents with a red eye and blurry vision.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Open-Angle Glaucoma</b> is a chronic and insidious disease where the eye's drainage system (the trabecular meshwork) becomes clogged over time, leading to a slow, painless rise in pressure that gradually damages the optic nerve from the periphery inward.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Decreased Outflow through Trabecular Meshwork] --> B(Increased IOP); B --> C(Optic Nerve Damage); C --> D(Progressive Peripheral Vision Loss);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
