    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>neuron action potential</b> is a rapid, all-or-none electrical signal that propagates down an axon, caused by the sequential opening and closing of <i>voltage-gated ion channels</i>, which temporarily reverses the membrane potential and allows for long-distance communication in the nervous system.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Resting Potential (~-70 mV):</b> Maintained by the Na<sup>+</sup>/K<sup>+</sup> pump and high resting permeability to K<sup>+</sup> (K<sup>+</sup> leak channels).</li><li><b>Depolarization:</b> A stimulus reaching threshold potential (~-55 mV) triggers the rapid opening of voltage-gated <mark>Na<sup>+</sup> channels</mark>, causing a massive influx of Na<sup>+</sup> and a sharp rise in membrane potential.</li><li><b>Repolarization:</b> Voltage-gated Na<sup>+</sup> channels inactivate, and voltage-gated <mark>K<sup>+</sup> channels</mark> open, leading to an efflux of K<sup>+</sup> that brings the membrane potential back down.</li><li><b>Hyperpolarization:</b> K<sup>+</sup> channels are slow to close, causing the membrane potential to briefly dip below the resting potential.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Many neurotoxins and drugs target these channels. [[tetrodotoxin|Tetrodotoxin]] (pufferfish) and [[lidocaine|local anesthetics]] block voltage-gated Na<sup>+</sup> channels, preventing action potential propagation.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The neuron action potential is fundamentally a precisely orchestrated sequence of ionic movements: a rapid influx of <b>Na<sup>+</sup></b> causes the rising phase (depolarization), and a subsequent efflux of <b>K<sup>+</sup></b> causes the falling phase (repolarization), enabling high-speed signal transmission.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A(Resting State) --Stimulus--> B(Threshold); B --Na+ Influx--> C(Depolarization); C --Na+ Inactivation & K+ Efflux--> D(Repolarization); D --Slow K+ Channel Closing--> E(Hyperpolarization); E --> A;"
