    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Neurons</b> are the fundamental, signal-transmitting cells of the nervous system, composed of a cell body (soma), dendrites that receive input, and an axon that sends output. They are permanent cells that do not typically divide in adults.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Structure:</b> The cell body contains the nucleus and Nissl substance (rough ER). Dendrites receive signals, and the axon transmits signals via [[832463e6|action potentials]].</li><li><b>Axonal Injury Response:</b> When an axon is severed, the distal portion undergoes <mark>Wallerian degeneration</mark>. The cell body swells, the nucleus moves to the periphery, and Nissl substance disperses (central chromatolysis or axonal reaction).</li><li><b>Spinal Tracts:</b> Neurons are organized into tracts in the spinal cord. First-order neurons bring sensory information from the periphery. Second-order neurons decussate and ascend to the thalamus. Third-order neurons project from the thalamus to the cortex. Motor pathways involve upper and lower motor neurons.</li><li><b>Markers:</b> Neurons can be identified by immunohistochemical stains for neurofilament protein and synaptophysin.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The histological changes of axonal reaction (central chromatolysis) are a classic sign of a neuron attempting to repair itself after its axon has been damaged.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Neurons</b> are highly specialized for communication, with a complex structure that supports the generation and propagation of electrical signals over long distances. Their response to injury, particularly the process of central chromatolysis, reflects a robust but often incomplete attempt at regeneration.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
