    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Neurotransmitters</b> are chemical messengers that transmit signals across a synapse from one neuron to another target neuron, muscle cell, or gland cell. Their synthesis, release, and degradation are tightly regulated and are the targets of many psychoactive drugs.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Acetylcholine (ACh):</b> Decreased in [[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]] and [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]]. Synthesized in the [[361438f2|basal nucleus of Meynert]].</li><li><b>Dopamine:</b> Decreased in [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]]. Increased in schizophrenia. Synthesized in the ventral tegmentum and substantia nigra.</li><li><b>GABA (Œ≥-aminobutyric acid):</b> Main inhibitory neurotransmitter. Decreased in anxiety and [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]]. Synthesized in the nucleus accumbens.</li><li><b>Norepinephrine:</b> Increased in anxiety; decreased in depression. Synthesized in the locus coeruleus.</li><li><b>Serotonin (5-HT):</b> Decreased in anxiety and depression. Synthesized in the raphe nuclei.</li><li><b>Glutamate:</b> Main excitatory neurotransmitter. Implicated in excitotoxicity.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The balance of key <b>neurotransmitters</b> in specific brain regions is critical for normal neurological function; imbalances are the core pathophysiology of many major neurological and psychiatric disorders, such as the dopamine deficit in Parkinson's and the acetylcholine deficit in Alzheimer's.</p>",
