    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>Nevus Flammeus</b>, commonly known as a <b>port-wine stain</b>, is a congenital capillary vascular malformation characterized by a flat, pink-to-reddish-purple patch of skin. When it occurs in the trigeminal nerve distribution, it is a hallmark of <i>Sturge-Weber syndrome</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> A congenital malformation of dermal capillaries, resulting in ectasia (dilation) of these vessels. It does not involute and grows in proportion with the child.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> A flat, erythematous patch present at birth.</li><li><b>Sturge-Weber Syndrome:</b> A nevus flammeus in the ophthalmic (V1) and/or maxillary (V2) distribution of the trigeminal nerve is the key cutaneous finding of [[fd52a8b8|Sturge-Weber syndrome]].</li><li><b>Associated Findings in Sturge-Weber:</b> The syndrome also includes an ipsilateral leptomeningeal angioma (leading to seizures and intellectual disability) and may involve episcleral hemangioma (leading to early-onset glaucoma).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A newborn with a port-wine stain following the V1/V2 dermatome must be evaluated for [[fd52a8b8|Sturge-Weber syndrome]], including an ophthalmologic exam for glaucoma and neuroimaging to look for leptomeningeal angiomas.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>nevus flammeus</b> is more than a birthmark when it appears on the face in a trigeminal distribution; it serves as a critical external clue to the potential presence of underlying vascular malformations in the brain and eye, as seen in [[fd52a8b8|Sturge-Weber syndrome]].</p>",
