    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Nigrostriatal Pathway</b> is a critical dopaminergic tract that projects from the <i>substantia nigra pars compacta (SNc)</i> to the <i>striatum</i> (caudate and putamen). It is a key component of the [[ed462927|basal ganglia]] motor loop, responsible for modulating the initiation of voluntary movement.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Origin:</b> Substantia nigra pars compacta (SNc) in the midbrain.</li><li><b>Termination:</b> Dorsal striatum (caudate nucleus and putamen).</li><li><b>Neurotransmitter:</b> [[90adc821|Dopamine]].</li><li><b>Function:</b> Modulates motor activity by exciting the direct pathway (via D1 receptors) and inhibiting the indirect pathway (via D2 receptors), with a net effect of facilitating movement.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Degeneration of this pathway is the primary cause of the motor symptoms in [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]]. The loss of dopamine leads to overactivity of the indirect pathway and underactivity of the direct pathway, resulting in bradykinesia, rigidity, and tremor.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The destruction of the nigrostriatal pathway is the central event in [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]]. Antipsychotic drugs can block D2 receptors in this pathway, causing drug-induced parkinsonism (extrapyramidal side effects).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Nigrostriatal Pathway</b> acts as the 'gas pedal' for the basal ganglia's motor circuit; its dopaminergic input facilitates movement, and its degeneration in Parkinson's disease effectively 'puts the brakes on,' leading to the characteristic poverty of motion.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Substantia Nigra pars compacta] --Dopamine--> B(Striatum); B --> C(Modulation of Direct/Indirect Pathways); C --> D(Initiation of Movement);"
