    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Nimodipine</b> is a dihydropyridine <i>calcium channel blocker</i> with a high affinity for cerebral blood vessels, used specifically to prevent cerebral vasospasm following a [[63f8b05f|subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH)]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Blocks L-type calcium channels on smooth muscle cells, leading to vasodilation. It is more selective for cerebral arteries than other calcium channel blockers.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> <u>Exclusively</u> used to improve neurological outcomes by preventing or reducing the severity of <mark>cerebral vasospasm</mark>, a delayed complication that occurs 3-10 days after a [[63f8b05f|subarachnoid hemorrhage]].</li><li><b>Administration:</b> Typically given orally or via nasogastric tube for 21 days following an aneurysmal SAH.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> The most common side effect is hypotension. Others include headache, nausea, and bradycardia.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> If a question describes a patient who had a subarachnoid hemorrhage and then develops new focal neurological deficits several days later, the cause is vasospasm. The prophylactic treatment for this complication is nimodipine.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Nimodipine</b> is a specialized calcium channel blocker whose primary role is not to treat hypertension but to prevent the devastating secondary ischemic strokes caused by vasospasm after a subarachnoid hemorrhage, thereby improving survival and functional outcomes.</p>",
