    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Noise-induced hearing loss</b> is a type of <i>sensorineural hearing loss</i> caused by damage to the delicate hair cells in the [[2e814378|organ of Corti]] within the cochlea, resulting from exposure to loud sounds.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Loud noise causes mechanical damage and metabolic exhaustion of the stereociliated hair cells in the [[2e814378|organ of Corti]]. Damage is typically irreversible.</li><li><b>Frequency Pattern:</b> The hearing loss characteristically begins at high frequencies, with a classic audiogram showing a <mark>\"notch\" or dip at 4000 Hz</mark>. This is because the basal part of the cochlea, which is responsible for high-frequency hearing, is most susceptible to damage.</li><li><b>Causes:</b> Can be caused by a single, intense acoustic trauma (e.g., explosion) or, more commonly, by chronic exposure to loud noise (e.g., occupational, recreational music).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients report difficulty hearing, especially in noisy environments, and may experience tinnitus.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> An audiogram showing a bilateral, symmetric hearing loss with a characteristic notch at 4000 Hz is the classic finding for noise-induced hearing loss.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Noise-induced hearing loss</b> is a direct result of mechanical trauma to the hair cells of the inner ear, characteristically affecting high-frequency hearing first (especially at 4000 Hz) because the region of the cochlea responsible for these frequencies is most vulnerable to the damaging energy of loud sounds.</p>",
