    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Non-REM (NREM) sleep</b> is one of the two main stages of sleep, comprising three distinct stages (N1, N2, N3) characterized by progressively slower brain waves and deeper relaxation. It is the period when the body repairs and regrows tissues, builds bone and muscle, and strengthens the immune system.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Stage N1 (Light Sleep):</b> Transition between wakefulness and sleep. EEG shows low-voltage, mixed-frequency waves.</li><li><b>Stage N2 (Intermediate Sleep):</b> The largest percentage of total sleep time. EEG is characterized by <mark>sleep spindles</mark> (bursts of rhythmic activity) and <mark>K-complexes</mark> (large, high-voltage slow waves). Bruxism (teeth grinding) occurs in this stage.</li><li><b>Stage N3 (Deep Sleep/Slow-Wave Sleep):</b> The deepest stage of sleep. EEG shows low-frequency, high-amplitude <mark>delta waves</mark>. This is the stage where sleepwalking (somnambulism), night terrors, and bedwetting (enuresis) occur.</li><li><b>Physiology:</b> Characterized by decreased heart rate, blood pressure, and respiratory rate.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Associate specific EEG findings and parasomnias with their respective NREM stages: N2 with sleep spindles and K-complexes, and N3 with delta waves, sleepwalking, and night terrors.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Non-REM sleep</b> is a period of deep physiological rest and restoration, progressing through stages of increasing depth, with Stage N3 (slow-wave sleep) being the most restorative and the time when disorders of arousal like sleepwalking and night terrors manifest.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Awake] --> B(NREM Stage 1); B --> C(NREM Stage 2); C --> D(NREM Stage 3); D --> C; C --> E(REM Sleep);"
    },
