    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Nonbenzodiazepine hypnotics</b>, often called \"Z-drugs,\" are a class of psychoactive drugs used for the treatment of insomnia. While structurally unrelated to benzodiazepines, they act on a specific subtype of the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor to produce sedative effects.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Examples:</b> <b>Z</b>olpidem, <b>Z</b>aleplon, es<b>Z</b>opiclone.</li><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Act as selective agonists at the <mark>BZ1 (œâ1) subtype</mark> of the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor. This enhances the effect of GABA, leading to increased Cl<sup>-</sup> conductance and neuronal hyperpolarization, but with more specificity for sedation than benzodiazepines.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Short-term treatment of insomnia.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Ataxia, headaches, confusion. Can cause anterograde amnesia and complex sleep-related behaviors (e.g., sleepwalking, sleep-driving).</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Have a rapid onset and short duration of action. Effects are reversed by <mark>flumazenil</mark>, the same antidote used for benzodiazepine overdose.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Z-drugs are preferred over benzodiazepines for insomnia due to a lower risk of dependence and less disruption of sleep architecture. However, they are still controlled substances and carry risks. Remember that their effects are reversed by flumazenil.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Nonbenzodiazepine hypnotics</b> are 'smarter' sleeping pills than benzodiazepines because they selectively target the sedative (BZ1) subtype of the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor, inducing sleep with less anxiolytic, muscle relaxant, and anticonvulsant effects, and a lower risk of altering sleep stages.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
