  "a1ef0cd9": {
    "title": "Non-Communicating Hydrocephalus",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Neurosurgery",
      "Pediatrics",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Hydrocephalus"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Non-communicating hydrocephalus</b>, also known as <i>obstructive hydrocephalus</i>, is the accumulation of excess cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) due to a physical blockage within the ventricular system, leading to ventricular dilation proximal to the obstruction and increased intracranial pressure.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> A structural lesion blocks the flow of CSF from one part of the ventricular system to another or into the subarachnoid space. This leads to a buildup of CSF and pressure in the ventricles 'upstream' of the blockage.</li><li><b>Common Sites of Obstruction:</b><br> - <b>Cerebral Aqueduct (of Sylvius):</b> The narrowest part of the ventricular system, connecting the 3rd and 4th ventricles. Aqueductal stenosis is a common cause in children.<br> - <b>Foramen of Monro:</b> Can be blocked by a colloid cyst.<br> - <b>Fourth Ventricle Outlets:</b> Can be compressed by posterior fossa tumors like a [[16d613bb|medulloblastoma]] or [[14365ef4|ependymoma]].</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Symptoms of increased intracranial pressure, such as headache, nausea, vomiting, and [[4ae219da|papilledema]]. In infants, presents with an enlarging head circumference and bulging fontanelle.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A [[16d613bb|medulloblastoma]] in a child is a classic cause of obstructive hydrocephalus due to compression of the fourth ventricle.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Non-communicating hydrocephalus</b> is a 'plumbing problem' within the brain's ventricular system, where a physical blockage leads to a dam-like effect, causing upstream ventricular dilation and a dangerous rise in intracranial pressure.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[CSF Production in Lateral/Third Ventricles] --> B(Flow through Cerebral Aqueduct); B --Blockage (e.g., Tumor)--> C(Obstruction); B --> D(Fourth Ventricle); C --> E(Dilation of Lateral & Third Ventricles); E --> F(Increased ICP);"
