  "48f817e6": {
    "title": "Non-Depolarizing Neuromuscular Blocking Drugs",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Anesthesiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neuromuscular Blockers"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Non-depolarizing neuromuscular blocking drugs</b> are a class of agents that cause skeletal muscle paralysis by acting as <i>competitive antagonists</i> at the nicotinic acetylcholine (ACh) receptors at the neuromuscular junction.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Examples:</b> Rocuronium, vecuronium, atracurium, cisatracurium, [[243d4db1|pancuronium]]. Mnemonic: End in '-curonium' or '-curium'.</li><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Competitively bind to N<sub>M</sub> receptors on the motor endplate, preventing [[6a005559|ACh]] from binding and thus inhibiting muscle cell depolarization and contraction.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used as adjuncts in general anesthesia to induce skeletal muscle relaxation, facilitating endotracheal intubation and surgical procedures.</li><li><b>Reversal:</b> The blockade can be overcome by increasing the concentration of ACh in the synapse. This is achieved by administering an <mark>acetylcholinesterase inhibitor</mark> (e.g., neostigmine). An antimuscarinic (e.g., glycopyrrolate) is co-administered to prevent systemic muscarinic side effects. Sugammadex can also be used to reverse rocuronium and vecuronium.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from succinylcholine (a depolarizing blocker). Non-depolarizing blockade shows a 'fade' on train-of-four stimulation, and its effects are reversed by AChE inhibitors.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Non-depolarizing neuromuscular blockers</b> act like a key that fits in the lock (the ACh receptor) but doesn't turn, competitively preventing the real key (ACh) from opening the channel and causing muscle contraction. Their effects can be overcome by flooding the synapse with more ACh.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
