  "45dce26f": {
    "title": "Nonproliferative Diabetic Retinopathy",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Endocrinology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Pathology"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Nonproliferative diabetic retinopathy (NPDR)</b> is the most common form of [[73b00ab0|diabetic retinopathy]], characterized by damage to the retinal blood vessels leading to leakage and ischemia, but without the growth of new, abnormal blood vessels (neovascularization).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Chronic hyperglycemia damages retinal capillaries, leading to loss of pericytes, basement membrane thickening, and breakdown of the blood-retinal barrier.</li><li><b>Funduscopic Findings:</b><br> - <mark>Microaneurysms:</mark> Earliest sign. Small, saccular outpouchings of capillaries.<br> - <mark>Dot and Blot Hemorrhages:</mark> Bleeding into the deeper layers of the retina.<br> - <mark>Hard Exudates:</mark> Yellow lipid deposits resulting from chronic plasma leakage.<br> - <mark>Cotton-Wool Spots:</mark> Fluffy white patches representing nerve fiber layer infarcts from capillary occlusion.</li><li><b>Major Cause of Vision Loss:</b> The primary cause of vision loss in NPDR is <mark>macular edema</mark>, where fluid and lipids leak into the macula, causing central vision to become blurred.</li><li><b>Progression:</b> NPDR can progress to the more severe proliferative form if retinal ischemia becomes widespread.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Be able to identify the funduscopic findings of NPDR. The presence of microaneurysms, hemorrhages, and exudates without neovascularization defines this stage.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Nonproliferative diabetic retinopathy</b> is a disease of leaky and occluded retinal vessels. The pathology is confined to the existing vasculature, and the main threat to vision is not from new vessel growth but from the chronic leakage of fluid into the macula, causing macular edema.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
        "to": "73b00ab0"
      },
      {
