        "to": "rhegmatogenous_retinal_detachment"
      },
      {
        "type": "can_be_caused_by",
        "to": "23455320"
      }
    ]
  },
  "682952a2": {
    "title": "NSAIDs for Headaches",
    "primaryType": "concept",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neurology",
      "Pain Management",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Analgesics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs)</b> are a cornerstone of abortive therapy for mild to moderate primary [[26661e34|headaches]], particularly tension-type and migraine headaches, by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> NSAIDs (e.g., ibuprofen, naproxen, diclofenac) reversibly inhibit cyclooxygenase (COX-1 and COX-2) enzymes, which blocks the conversion of arachidonic acid to prostaglandins. Prostaglandins are key mediators of inflammation and pain.</li><li><b>Tension-Type Headache:</b> NSAIDs are often the <u>first-line</u> treatment for acute tension headaches.</li><li><b>Migraine Headache:</b> Effective for mild to moderate migraine attacks. They can be used alone or in combination with triptans for more severe attacks.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Common side effects include GI upset and peptic ulcer disease. Chronic use can lead to renal injury (analgesic nephropathy) and increased risk of cardiovascular events.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> While effective for acute attacks, overuse of NSAIDs and other analgesics for headaches (e.g., >10-15 days per month) can paradoxically lead to medication-overuse headaches.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>NSAIDs treat primary headaches by targeting the inflammatory component of pain, reducing the synthesis of prostaglandins that sensitize nociceptors, making them a fundamental first-line option for acute attacks.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_treatment_for",
        "to": "26661e34"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
        "to": "nsaid"
      },
      {
        "type": "inhibits_enzyme",
        "to": "cyclooxygenase"
      }
    ]
  },
  "aedeee6d": {
    "title": "Norepinephrine (CNS)",
    "primaryType": "molecule",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Psychiatry",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Neurotransmitters"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Norepinephrine (NE)</b> is a catecholamine that functions as a major neurotransmitter in the central nervous system, where it is crucial for regulating attention, arousal, sleep-wake cycles, learning, memory, and mood.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Synthesis:</b> Synthesized from [[90adc821|dopamine]] via dopamine Œ≤-hydroxylase. The primary site of NE synthesis in the brain is the <mark>locus coeruleus</mark>, a nucleus in the pons.</li><li><b>Function:</b> As part of the ascending reticular activating system, the locus coeruleus projects widely throughout the CNS, modulating alertness and arousal. NE is a key neurotransmitter in the 'fight or flight' response.</li><li><b>Role in Mood Disorders:</b> Decreased levels of norepinephrine are implicated in the pathophysiology of <mark>depression</mark>. Increased levels are associated with <mark>anxiety</mark> and panic disorders.</li><li><b>Pharmacological Targets:</b> Many antidepressants, such as SNRIs (e.g., venlafaxine) and TCAs (e.g., amitriptyline), work by increasing synaptic levels of norepinephrine (and serotonin).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the locus coeruleus as the principal source of CNS norepinephrine. Its role in arousal and mood makes it a key target for drugs treating depression and ADHD.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>In the CNS, <b>norepinephrine</b> released from the locus coeruleus acts as a global 'alertness' signal, modulating attention and arousal across the brain, with dysregulation of this system being a cornerstone of the pathophysiology of mood and anxiety disorders.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Locus Coeruleus] --Synthesizes & Releases--> B(Norepinephrine); B --> C(Widespread CNS Projections); C --> D(Arousal & Attention); C --> E(Mood Regulation);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_synthesized_in",
        "to": "locus_coeruleus"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_decreased_in",
