      "definition": "<p><b>Neural development</b> is the complex process by which the nervous system forms during embryogenesis, beginning with the induction of the neural plate from the ectoderm and proceeding through neurulation, proliferation, migration, and differentiation of neurons and glial cells.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Induction:</b> The notochord induces the overlying ectoderm to differentiate into the neuroectoderm, forming the neural plate.</li><li><b>Neurulation:</b> The neural plate folds to form the [[a87cbede|neural tube]], which will become the CNS, and the [[14c6f2a7|neural crest cells]], which will become the PNS and other structures. This process is critically dependent on folate.</li><li><b>Vesicle Formation:</b> The rostral end of the neural tube develops into three primary brain vesicles (prosencephalon, mesencephalon, rhombencephalon), which then subdivide into five secondary vesicles.</li><li><b>Plate Differentiation:</b> The neural tube differentiates along its dorsal-ventral axis into the alar plate (sensory functions, induced by BMPs) and the basal plate (motor functions, induced by Sonic hedgehog [SHH]).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Failure of the neural tube to close results in [[neural_tube_defects|neural tube defects]]. Failure of the rostral neuropore to close causes anencephaly; failure of the caudal neuropore causes spina bifida.</li></ul>",
