      "definition": "<p><b>Trigeminal Neuralgia</b> (also known as tic douloureux) is a chronic pain disorder characterized by recurrent, sudden, severe, shock-like episodes of unilateral facial pain in the distribution of the <i>trigeminal nerve (CN V)</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly caused by <mark>vascular compression</mark> of the trigeminal nerve root as it enters the brainstem, often by the superior cerebellar artery. Demyelination (e.g., from [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]]) is another important cause, especially in younger patients.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Paroxysms of excruciating, electric shock-like pain, lasting from a few seconds to minutes. The pain is unilateral and typically affects the V2 (maxillary) and/or V3 (mandibular) divisions.</li><li><b>Triggers:</b> Pain can be triggered by innocuous stimuli in specific 'trigger zones,' such as light touch, chewing, talking, or a cold breeze.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> <u>First-line</u> medical treatment is <mark>carbamazepine</mark>. Other options include oxcarbazepine and gabapentin. For refractory cases, surgical microvascular decompression may be performed.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient describing sudden, severe, electric shock-like pain on one side of their face, triggered by brushing their teeth or feeling a breeze, is the classic presentation. The first-line treatment is carbamazepine.</li></ul>",
