    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Neurodegenerative disease therapy</b> encompasses pharmacological strategies aimed at managing symptoms and, in some cases, slowing the progression of diseases characterized by the progressive loss of neurons, such as Alzheimer's, Parkinson's, and Huntington's disease.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Alzheimer Disease:</b> Treatment is symptomatic. <mark>Acetylcholinesterase inhibitors</mark> (e.g., [[47d0372e|donepezil]], rivastigmine, galantamine) are used to increase ACh levels. <mark>Memantine</mark>, an NMDA receptor antagonist, is used in moderate-to-severe disease to prevent excitotoxicity.</li><li><b>Parkinson Disease:</b> Therapy focuses on increasing dopamine levels. <mark>[[541cd176|Levodopa/carbidopa]]</mark> is the mainstay. Dopamine agonists, MAO-B inhibitors, and COMT inhibitors are also used.</li><li><b>Huntington Disease:</b> Treatment focuses on managing symptoms. Tetrabenazine and deutetrabenazine, which inhibit the vesicular monoamine transporter (VMAT), are used to treat chorea.</li><li><b>Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS):</b> <mark>Riluzole</mark>, which is thought to reduce glutamate excitotoxicity, may modestly increase survival.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> For exams, focus on the primary neurotransmitter deficit and the corresponding drug mechanism: Alzheimer's = ‚ÜìACh (use AChE inhibitors); Parkinson's = ‚ÜìDopamine (use Levodopa).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Current therapies for most <b>neurodegenerative diseases</b> are largely symptomatic and do not halt the underlying disease process; they work by compensating for the specific neurotransmitter deficiencies that result from neuronal loss.</p>",
