      "definition": "<p><b>Neurodegenerative disorders</b> are a heterogeneous group of chronic, progressive diseases characterized by the selective and symmetric loss of neurons in specific areas of the central nervous system, often associated with the intracellular or extracellular aggregation of misfolded proteins.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Dementias:</b> Characterized by cognitive decline. The most common is [[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]] (AŒ≤ plaques, tau tangles). Others include [[db2f16e5|Lewy body dementia]] (Œ±-synuclein) and [[5fff42cd|Frontotemporal dementia]] (tau or TDP-43).</li><li><b>Movement Disorders:</b> Characterized by motor dysfunction. Includes [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]] (Œ±-synuclein Lewy bodies, loss of dopaminergic neurons) and [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]] (huntingtin aggregates, loss of GABAergic neurons).</li><li><b>Motor Neuron Diseases:</b> Characterized by weakness and muscle atrophy. Includes [[4ed629f9|Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)]] (TDP-43 aggregates, loss of upper and lower motor neurons).</li><li><b>Prion Diseases:</b> Such as [[86fe59ba|Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease]], characterized by rapidly progressive dementia and spongiform changes due to aggregation of misfolded prion protein (PrP<sup>Sc</sup>).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> For board exams, it is crucial to associate the major neurodegenerative diseases with their hallmark protein aggregate and the primary brain region affected.</li></ul>",
