      "definition": "<p><b>Neurofibromatosis (NF)</b> is a group of autosomal dominant genetic disorders that cause tumors to grow on nervous tissue. The two major types are Neurofibromatosis Type 1 (NF1) and Neurofibromatosis Type 2 (NF2).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Neurofibromatosis Type 1 (NF1):</b> Caused by a mutation in the <i>NF1</i> gene on chromosome <b>17</b>. Characterized by <mark>caf√©-au-lait spots</mark>, cutaneous neurofibromas, <mark>Lisch nodules</mark> (iris hamartomas), optic gliomas, and axillary/inguinal freckling. Mnemonic: 17 letters in 'von Recklinghausen'.</li><li><b>Neurofibromatosis Type 2 (NF2):</b> Caused by a mutation in the <i>NF2</i> gene on chromosome <b>22</b>. Characterized by bilateral vestibular [[03ecb69e|schwannomas]]. Also associated with meningiomas and ependymomas. Mnemonic: NF<b>2</b> affects <b>2</b> ears (bilateral schwannomas) and is on chromosome <b>22</b>.</li><li><b>Inheritance:</b> Both are autosomal dominant with high penetrance, but NF1 has variable expressivity.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Both <i>NF1</i> (neurofibromin) and <i>NF2</i> (merlin) are tumor suppressor genes. Their inactivation leads to uncontrolled cell growth.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The distinction between NF1 and NF2 is high-yield. NF1 is characterized by skin findings (caf√©-au-lait, neurofibromas) and Lisch nodules. NF2 is defined by bilateral vestibular schwannomas.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Neurofibromatosis</b> represents two distinct genetic disorders linked by their predisposition to nerve sheath tumors; NF1 is primarily a disease of skin and peripheral nerves, while NF2 is a disease of central nervous system tumors, most notably bilateral acoustic neuromas.</p>",
