    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Neurogenic bladder</b> is a general term for bladder dysfunction (either flaccid or spastic) caused by damage to the nerves that control urination.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Spastic (Hyperreflexic) Bladder:</b> Caused by an <mark>upper motor neuron (UMN) lesion</mark> above the sacral spinal cord (e.g., spinal cord injury, [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]]). The sacral micturition reflex is intact but is no longer inhibited by the brain. Results in detrusor hyperreflexia, leading to <mark>urge incontinence</mark>.</li><li><b>Flaccid (Hypotonic) Bladder:</b> Caused by a <mark>lower motor neuron (LMN) lesion</mark> affecting the sacral micturition center or peripheral nerves (e.g., cauda equina syndrome, diabetic neuropathy). The bladder cannot contract effectively. Results in urinary retention and <mark>overflow incontinence</mark>.</li><li><b>Multiple Sclerosis:</b> A common cause of neurogenic bladder. Patients often present with urge incontinence due to UMN lesions in the spinal cord.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Management depends on the type. Spastic bladder is treated with antimuscarinic drugs (e.g., oxybutynin) or botulinum toxin injections. Flaccid bladder is managed with timed voiding and intermittent self-catheterization.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient with [[45dd6d19|MS]] who develops urinary frequency and urgency has a spastic bladder due to a UMN lesion. A patient with diabetes and a large post-void residual volume has a flaccid bladder due to an LMN/autonomic neuropathy.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The behavior of a <b>neurogenic bladder</b> directly reflects the level of the neurological lesion: UMN lesions lead to a spastic, hyperactive bladder (urge incontinence), while LMN lesions result in a flaccid, hypotonic bladder (overflow incontinence).</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
