  "6d290af4": {
    "title": "Neurohypophysis (Posterior Pituitary)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Endocrinology",
      "Anatomy",
      "Neuroscience",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Endocrine",
      "Anatomy",
      "Pituitary Gland"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Neurohypophysis</b>, or posterior pituitary, is the posterior lobe of the pituitary gland. It is composed of neural tissue and functions as a storage and release site for two hormones synthesized in the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]]: antidiuretic hormone (ADH) and oxytocin.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Embryology:</b> Arises from a downward extension of neural ectoderm from the developing diencephalon.</li><li><b>Structure:</b> Composed of the axons and nerve terminals of magnocellular neurons whose cell bodies are located in the supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei of the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]]. Also contains glial cells called pituicytes.</li><li><b>Hormones:</b> It does <u>not</u> synthesize hormones. It stores and releases: <br> - <b>Antidiuretic Hormone (ADH/Vasopressin):</b> Primarily synthesized in the supraoptic nucleus. <br> - <b>Oxytocin:</b> Primarily synthesized in the [[e7b51f5c|paraventricular nucleus]].</li><li><b>Connection to Hypothalamus:</b> Connected to the hypothalamus via the <mark>hypothalamo-hypophyseal tract</mark>, a bundle of axons. This is a direct neural connection, contrasting with the portal venous system of the anterior pituitary.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that the posterior pituitary is essentially nerve tissue that stores and releases hypothalamic hormones. A lesion of the pituitary stalk or posterior pituitary can cause central diabetes insipidus due to lack of ADH release.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Neurohypophysis</b> is not a true endocrine gland but rather a specialized neurosecretory terminal, acting as a storage depot for hypothalamic hormones and releasing them directly into the bloodstream upon neural command from the hypothalamus.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Hypothalamus<br>(Supraoptic & Paraventricular Nuclei)] --Axonal Transport--> B(Neurohypophysis); B --Release into Blood--> C(ADH & Oxytocin);"
    },
    "connections": [
