  "38e52c3e": {
    "title": "Neurokinin-1 (NK1) Receptors",
    "primaryType": "molecule",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Gastroenterology",
      "Neuroscience",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Gastrointestinal",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Antiemetics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Neurokinin-1 (NK1) receptors</b> are G-protein coupled receptors for the neuropeptide Substance P. They are found in the central and peripheral nervous systems and are critically involved in the pathways for pain and, most notably, emesis (vomiting).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Ligand:</b> The primary endogenous ligand is <mark>Substance P</mark>.</li><li><b>Location in Emesis Pathway:</b> NK1 receptors are highly concentrated in the <mark>area postrema</mark> (chemoreceptor trigger zone) and the <mark>nucleus tractus solitarius (NTS)</mark>, which are key components of the central vomiting center in the brainstem.</li><li><b>Role in Vomiting:</b> Activation of NK1 receptors by Substance P is a key step in inducing both acute and, particularly, delayed nausea and vomiting.</li><li><b>Pharmacology (NK1 Antagonists):</b> Drugs that block NK1 receptors (e.g., <mark>aprepitant</mark>, fosaprepitant) are potent antiemetics. Their names often end in '-pitant'.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> NK1 antagonists are primarily used for the prevention of chemotherapy-induced nausea and vomiting (CINV), especially the delayed phase, and for postoperative nausea and vomiting (PONV).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> For chemotherapy-induced vomiting, remember the different receptor targets. Serotonin (5-HT3) antagonists (e.g., ondansetron) are best for acute CINV, while NK1 antagonists (e.g., aprepitant) are crucial for delayed CINV.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>NK1 receptors</b> are the primary target for Substance P in the brain's vomiting center; blocking these receptors with '-pitant' drugs like aprepitant is a highly effective strategy for preventing the delayed nausea and vomiting associated with chemotherapy.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Chemotherapy] --> B(Release of Substance P); B --> C(Binds to NK1 Receptors in Area Postrema/NTS); C --> D(Emesis); E[Aprepitant] --|Blocks|--> C;"
    },
    "connections": [
