  "7e727989": {
    "title": "Neuromuscular Junction (NMJ)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Physiology",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Peripheral Nervous System"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Neuromuscular Junction (NMJ)</b> is a highly specialized synapse between the axon terminal of a motor neuron and the motor end plate of a skeletal muscle fiber, responsible for converting the neuron's electrical signal into muscle contraction.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Neurotransmitter:</b> The sole neurotransmitter at the NMJ is <mark>acetylcholine (ACh)</mark>.</li><li><b>Receptor:</b> ACh binds to <mark>nicotinic (N<sub>M</sub>) receptors</mark> on the postsynaptic muscle membrane (motor end plate).</li><li><b>Mechanism:</b> An action potential arriving at the axon terminal triggers the opening of voltage-gated Ca<sup>2+</sup> channels. Ca<sup>2+</sup> influx causes the release of ACh into the synaptic cleft. ACh binds to N<sub>M</sub> receptors, opening them to allow Na<sup>+</sup> influx, which generates an end-plate potential and triggers a muscle action potential.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> The NMJ is the site of pathology in several diseases: <br> - <b>Myasthenia Gravis:</b> Autoantibodies against postsynaptic ACh receptors. <br> - <b>Lambert-Eaton Myasthenic Syndrome:</b> Autoantibodies against presynaptic voltage-gated Ca<sup>2+</sup> channels. <br> - <b>Botulism:</b> Botulinum toxin cleaves SNARE proteins, preventing presynaptic ACh release.</li><li><b>Pharmacology:</b> Targeted by [[1aaaffd2|neuromuscular blocking drugs]] used in anesthesia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Neuromuscular Junction</b> is a high-fidelity synapse designed for obligatory one-to-one transmission, where every motor neuron action potential reliably leads to a muscle fiber action potential, a process that can be disrupted by autoantibodies or toxins, leading to muscle weakness or paralysis.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Motor Neuron AP] --> B(Ca2+ Influx); B --> C(ACh Release); C --> D(Binds to Nicotinic Receptors); D --> E(Na+ Influx); E --> F(End-Plate Potential); F --> G(Muscle AP & Contraction);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "uses_neurotransmitter",
        "to": "6a005559"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_affected_in",
        "to": "myasthenia_gravis"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_affected_in",
        "to": "lambert_eaton_syndrome"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_affected_by",
        "to": "botulinum_toxin"
      }
    ]
  }
}
