      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Movement Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Myoclonus</b> is a clinical sign characterized by a sudden, brief, shock-like, involuntary muscle jerk or twitch. It can be a symptom of a wide range of underlying neurological disorders, including epilepsy, metabolic encephalopathies, and neurodegenerative diseases.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Description:</b> A quick, involuntary muscle contraction. It can be focal, multifocal, or generalized. Examples range from benign hiccups to the severe jerks seen in certain epilepsies.</li><li><b>Epileptic Myoclonus:</b> Occurs as part of a [[1c6cb12b|myoclonic seizure]], as seen in Juvenile Myoclonic Epilepsy.</li><li><b>Metabolic Myoclonus:</b> Often seen in metabolic encephalopathies such as uremic or hepatic encephalopathy.</li><li><b>Post-hypoxic Myoclonus (Lance-Adams Syndrome):</b> A debilitating action myoclonus that can occur after a severe hypoxic brain injury.</li><li><b>Neurodegenerative Disease:</b> Prominent 'startle myoclonus' (jerks in response to loud sounds or touch) is a characteristic feature of [[86fe59ba|Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The clinical context is key to interpreting myoclonus. In an adolescent, think JME. In a patient with rapidly progressive dementia, think CJD. In a patient with renal failure, think uremic encephalopathy.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Myoclonus</b> is a non-specific sign of neuronal hyperexcitability that can originate from the cortex, brainstem, or spinal cord. Its diagnostic value lies in its association with other clinical features, which helps to pinpoint the underlying etiology.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
