  "c154b69c": {
    "title": "Myopia",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Pathology"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Myopia</b>, commonly known as nearsightedness, is a refractive error of the eye in which parallel light rays from distant objects are focused <i>in front of</i> the retina, causing distant objects to appear blurry while near objects are seen clearly.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Occurs when the eye is either too long (axial myopia) or the cornea/lens system has too much refractive power (refractive myopia).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients can see near objects clearly but have difficulty seeing distant objects (e.g., a chalkboard, road signs).</li><li><b>Correction:</b> Corrected with a <mark>concave (diverging) lens</mark> (e.g., glasses or contact lenses with a negative diopter prescription). The diverging lens spreads out the light rays before they enter the eye, effectively moving the focal point backward onto the retina.</li><li><b>Complications:</b> High myopia is a risk factor for [[38c092f9|retinal detachment]] and glaucoma.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the correction: Myopia (nearsightedness) requires a di<b>v</b>erging (conca<b>v</b>e) lens. Hyperopia (farsightedness) requires a converging (convex) lens.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Myopia</b> is a mismatch between the eye's focusing power and its length, causing distant images to be focused in the vitreous humor instead of on the retina. This is corrected by using a concave lens to diverge the light rays and push the focal point back to its proper location.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
