    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Otology",
      "Pathology"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>M√©ni√®re disease</b> is a disorder of the inner ear characterized by recurrent episodes of vertigo, sensorineural hearing loss, and tinnitus, caused by an increase in the volume and pressure of endolymph (endolymphatic hydrops).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Caused by <mark>endolymphatic hydrops</mark>, an excessive accumulation of endolymph in the membranous labyrinth of the inner ear, leading to distention and potential rupture of these membranes.</li><li><b>Classic Triad:</b><br>1. <b>Episodic Vertigo:</b> Spontaneous, recurrent episodes of spinning vertigo that can last from minutes to hours.<br>2. <b>Sensorineural Hearing Loss:</b> Typically fluctuating and low-frequency in the early stages, becoming permanent over time.<br>3. <b>Tinnitus:</b> Ringing or roaring sound in the affected ear, often low-pitched.</li><li><b>Associated Symptom:</b> A feeling of aural fullness or pressure in the affected ear is also common.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Management focuses on symptom control. A low-salt diet and diuretics (e.g., hydrochlorothiazide) are used to reduce endolymphatic pressure. Antiemetics and vestibular suppressants are used for acute vertigo attacks.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The triad of episodic vertigo, tinnitus, and sensorineural hearing loss is the key to diagnosing M√©ni√®re disease.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>M√©ni√®re disease</b> is essentially 'glaucoma of the inner ear,' where an excess of endolymphatic fluid increases pressure within the labyrinth, leading to a characteristic triad of episodic vertigo, hearing loss, and tinnitus due to dysfunction of both the vestibular and cochlear apparatus.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
