      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Analgesics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Nalbuphine</b> is a synthetic <i>opioid analgesic</i> with a mixed agonist-antagonist profile, acting as a Œ∫-opioid receptor agonist and a Œº-opioid receptor partial agonist or antagonist.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> It is a <mark>Œ∫-opioid receptor agonist</mark>, which provides analgesia. It is also a <mark>Œº-opioid receptor antagonist</mark>.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used for the management of moderate to severe pain. It can also be used as a supplement to balanced anesthesia.</li><li><b>Ceiling Effect:</b> Due to its mixed agonist-antagonist properties, it exhibits a ceiling effect for respiratory depression, meaning that beyond a certain dose, further increases do not cause greater respiratory depression. This makes it potentially safer than full Œº-agonists like morphine.</li><li><b>Precipitation of Withdrawal:</b> Because it is a Œº-antagonist, administering nalbuphine to a patient who is physically dependent on a full Œº-agonist (e.g., heroin, morphine) can precipitate an <mark>acute opioid withdrawal syndrome</mark>.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the mixed agonist-antagonist opioids (nalbuphine, butorphanol, pentazocine). Their key features are the ceiling effect on respiratory depression and the risk of precipitating withdrawal in opioid-dependent individuals.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Nalbuphine</b> offers analgesia primarily through Œ∫-receptor agonism while its Œº-receptor antagonism provides a safety advantage with a ceiling effect on respiratory depression, but this same property makes it dangerous to use in patients already dependent on full Œº-agonist opioids.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
