    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Immunomodulators"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Natalizumab</b> is a humanized monoclonal antibody that targets the Œ±4-integrin, used as a disease-modifying therapy for relapsing forms of <i>Multiple Sclerosis (MS)</i> and Crohn disease.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Binds to the Œ±4-subunit of integrins (specifically Œ±4Œ≤1-integrin, also known as VLA-4) on the surface of leukocytes. This blocks the interaction of leukocytes with vascular cell adhesion molecule-1 (VCAM-1) on endothelial cells.</li><li><b>Effect:</b> By blocking this interaction, natalizumab prevents lymphocytes from migrating across the [[dd47b9cc|blood-brain barrier]] into the CNS parenchyma, thereby reducing the inflammatory demyelinating lesions of [[45dd6d19|MS]].</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Highly effective for reducing relapse rates in patients with active relapsing-remitting [[45dd6d19|MS]]. Also used for moderate to severe Crohn disease.</li><li><b>Major Adverse Effect:</b> The most serious risk is the development of <mark>Progressive Multifocal Leukoencephalopathy (PML)</mark>, a rare and often fatal brain infection caused by reactivation of the JC virus.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The association between natalizumab and PML is extremely high-yield. Patients must be tested for JC virus antibodies before starting therapy and monitored closely.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Natalizumab</b> acts as a 'gatekeeper' for the blood-brain barrier, preventing inflammatory lymphocytes from entering the CNS. While highly effective for MS, this powerful immunosuppressive mechanism carries the significant risk of allowing latent JC virus to reactivate, leading to PML.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Lymphocyte] --Œ±4-Integrin--> B(VCAM-1 on BBB); B --> C(CNS Infiltration); D[Natalizumab] --|Blocks|--> A;"
    },
    "connections": [
