  "288bdfc2": {
    "title": "Nausea",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Gastroenterology",
      "Neurology",
      "Symptom",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Gastrointestinal",
      "Pathology",
      "Symptoms"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Nausea</b> is the unpleasant sensation of the urge to vomit. It is a complex protective reflex coordinated by the vomiting center in the brainstem, which receives inputs from multiple sources.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Neurological Control:</b> The vomiting center is located in the medulla and receives inputs from: <br> - The <mark>chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ)</mark> in the [[5dd343d3|area postrema]], which senses toxins in the blood.<br> - The vestibular system (motion sickness).<br> - The GI tract (via the vagus nerve).<br> - The CNS (e.g., from increased intracranial pressure or psychological stimuli).</li><li><b>Migraine Headaches:</b> Nausea is a key diagnostic criterion for [[26661e34|migraine headaches]], often accompanying the pulsating head pain.</li><li><b>Increased Intracranial Pressure:</b> Nausea and vomiting, especially projectile vomiting without preceding nausea, are classic signs of elevated ICP.</li><li><b>Pharmacology:</b> Antiemetic drugs target the various receptors in the vomiting pathways, including dopamine (D2), serotonin (5-HT3), histamine (H1), acetylcholine (M1), and neurokinin (NK1) receptors.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Nausea and vomiting associated with a headache that is worse in the morning or awakens the patient from sleep is a red flag for a brain tumor or other cause of increased ICP.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Nausea</b> is a centrally mediated sensation orchestrated by the brainstem's vomiting center, which integrates a wide array of inputs from the blood, gut, and brain itself to signal potential harm and trigger the urge to vomit.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_symptom_of",
