    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Nerve fibers</b> are the axons of neurons, classified based on their diameter, myelination status, and conduction velocity, which determines their specific sensory or motor function.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>AŒ± fibers:</b> Large diameter, heavily myelinated. The fastest conducting fibers. Function: proprioception (from muscle spindles, Golgi tendon organs) and somatic motor (alpha motor neurons).</li><li><b>AŒ≤ fibers:</b> Medium diameter, myelinated. Function: touch, pressure, vibration.</li><li><b>AŒ¥ fibers:</b> Small diameter, thinly myelinated. Function: transmit <mark>fast, sharp, well-localized pain</mark> and cold temperature.</li><li><b>C fibers:</b> Smallest diameter, <mark>unmyelinated</mark>. The slowest conducting fibers. Function: transmit <mark>slow, dull, poorly-localized pain</mark> and warmth. Also include postganglionic autonomic fibers.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> Local anesthetics preferentially block small, myelinated fibers first, which is why pain sensation (AŒ¥ and C fibers) is lost before touch (AŒ≤ fibers).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the two types of pain fibers: AŒ¥ for the initial 'ouch' and C fibers for the subsequent 'ache'.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The structure of a <b>nerve fiber</b> dictates its function; large, myelinated fibers are built for speed to transmit motor commands and discriminative touch, while small, unmyelinated fibers are designed for the slower, more persistent signaling of dull pain and temperature.</p>",
