    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Motion sickness</b> is a condition characterized by nausea, vomiting, and dizziness, caused by a mismatch between visually perceived movement and the vestibular system's sense of movement.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Occurs due to a conflict between the vestibular, visual, and proprioceptive systems. The brain receives contradictory information about the body's state of motion, which activates the [[74b651ab|vomiting center]] in the brainstem.</li><li><b>Key Neurotransmitters:</b> The pathways involved in motion sickness heavily rely on <mark>histaminic (H1)</mark> and <mark>muscarinic cholinergic (M1)</mark> signaling.</li><li><b>Treatment (Antimuscarinics):</b> <mark>Scopolamine</mark>, an antimuscarinic agent, is highly effective for prevention. It is often used as a transdermal patch.</li><li><b>Treatment (Antihistamines):</b> First-generation antihistamines with anticholinergic properties, such as diphenhydramine, dimenhydrinate, and meclizine, are also effective.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The primary pharmacological targets for preventing motion sickness are H1 and M1 receptors in the brainstem. Scopolamine (antimuscarinic) and first-generation antihistamines are the mainstays of therapy.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Motion sickness</b> is a sensory conflict disorder where the brain's confusion about movement triggers the vomiting reflex; treatment is aimed at blocking the histaminic and cholinergic pathways that mediate this distressing response.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
