    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Motor Cortex</b> is the region of the cerebral cortex involved in the planning, control, and execution of voluntary movements. It is located in the posterior part of the frontal lobe.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Primary Motor Cortex (M1):</b> Located in the precentral gyrus. It is responsible for the execution of voluntary movements.</li><li><b>Topographic Representation (Homunculus):</b> The primary motor cortex has a somatotopic organization, where different body parts are represented by distinct areas. The face and hands have disproportionately large representations. The legs and feet are represented on the medial surface of the hemisphere.</li><li><b>Blood Supply:</b> The lateral portion (face, arm) is supplied by the [[143bb23d|Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)]]. The medial portion (leg) is supplied by the [[830c856c|Anterior Cerebral Artery (ACA)]].</li><li><b>Thalamic Relay:</b> Receives major input from the <mark>ventral lateral (VL) nucleus</mark> of the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]], which relays signals from the basal ganglia and cerebellum.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The vascular supply of the motor homunculus is a high-yield topic for localizing strokes. An ACA stroke causes contralateral leg weakness, while an MCA stroke causes contralateral face and arm weakness.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Motor Cortex</b> is the final common pathway for the execution of voluntary movement, with its somatotopic map (homunculus) directly reflecting the fine motor control required for different body parts, a map whose vascular territories are critical for stroke localization.</p>",
