  "81355372": {
    "title": "Motor Neuron Signs",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Motor Deficits"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Motor neuron signs</b> are the clinical findings that result from damage to the motor nervous system, which are categorized into upper motor neuron (UMN) signs and lower motor neuron (LMN) signs, allowing for the localization of neurological lesions.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Upper Motor Neuron (UMN) Signs:</b> Result from lesions of the corticospinal tracts. Include <mark>spastic paralysis</mark>, hyperreflexia, increased muscle tone, and a positive Babinski sign. No significant muscle atrophy initially.</li><li><b>Lower Motor Neuron (LMN) Signs:</b> Result from lesions of the anterior horn cells, spinal roots, or peripheral nerves. Include <mark>flaccid paralysis</mark>, significant muscle atrophy, fasciculations, hyporeflexia, and decreased muscle tone.</li><li><b>Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS):</b> A classic example of a disease that presents with a combination of both UMN and LMN signs.</li><li><b>Anterior Spinal Artery Occlusion:</b> Causes damage to the anterior horns (LMN signs at the level of the lesion) and corticospinal tracts (UMN signs below the level of the lesion).</li><li><b>Brown-S√©quard Syndrome:</b> Causes ipsilateral UMN signs below the level of the hemisection.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The presence of both UMN and LMN signs in the same patient is a strong clue for [[4ed629f9|ALS]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The distinction between <b>upper and lower motor neuron signs</b> is fundamental to clinical neurology; UMN signs reflect a loss of central inhibition leading to hyperreflexia and spasticity, while LMN signs reflect a loss of direct muscle innervation leading to flaccidity and atrophy.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
