  "d3c4ac8c": {
    "title": "Movement Disorders",
    "primaryType": "concept",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Movement Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Movement disorders</b> are a group of neurological conditions characterized by abnormalities in the quality and quantity of voluntary and involuntary movements, typically resulting from dysfunction of the [[ed462927|basal ganglia]] or cerebellum.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Hypokinetic Disorders:</b> Characterized by a poverty of movement (akinesia/bradykinesia), rigidity, and tremor. The classic example is [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]].</li><li><b>Hyperkinetic Disorders:</b> Characterized by excessive, abnormal, involuntary movements. Examples include:<br> - <b>Chorea:</b> Rapid, jerky, purposeless movements (e.g., [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]]).<br> - <b>Athetosis:</b> Slow, writhing movements (e.g., [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]]).<br> - <b>Dystonia:</b> Sustained muscle contractions causing twisting movements or abnormal postures.<br> - <b>[[004e0bd6|Hemiballismus]]:</b> Wild, flinging movements of one side of the body.</li><li><b>Neurodegenerative Causes:</b> Many movement disorders are manifestations of underlying [[41ca6981|neurodegenerative disorders]], such as [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]] and [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]].</li><li><b>Abnormal Posturing:</b> [[c0b7a1ca|Decorticate and decerebrate posturing]] are specific types of abnormal movements seen in comatose patients with severe brain injury.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Movement disorders</b> represent a spectrum of dysfunction in the brain's motor control circuits, ranging from the 'too little' movement of Parkinsonism to the 'too much' movement of chorea and ballismus, all pointing to pathology within the basal ganglia and its connections.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
