  "45dd6d19": {
    "title": "Multiple Sclerosis (MS)",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Immunology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Demyelinating Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Multiple Sclerosis (MS)</b> is a chronic, autoimmune, inflammatory disease of the central nervous system characterized by the demyelination of axons, leading to a wide range of neurological deficits that are disseminated in <u>space and time</u>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Autoreactive T-cells cross the blood-brain barrier and attack the myelin sheath produced by [[a24f9747|oligodendrocytes]], leading to inflammation, demyelination, and axonal damage.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Symptoms vary widely depending on the location of the demyelinating plaques. Common presentations include [[98a63a59|optic neuritis]], transverse myelitis, [[58c684bd|internuclear ophthalmoplegia (INO)]], and sensory or motor deficits. Symptoms often worsen with heat (Uhthoff's phenomenon).</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> MRI is the gold standard, showing characteristic <mark>periventricular plaques</mark> (Dawson's fingers). CSF analysis reveals <mark>oligoclonal bands</mark> of IgG and an elevated IgG index.</li><li><b>Classic Triad (Charcot):</b> A historical triad of <b>S</b>canning speech, <b>I</b>ntention tremor, and <b>N</b>ystagmus (<b>SIN</b>).</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Acute flares are treated with high-dose corticosteroids. Long-term management involves disease-modifying therapies like [[00e48ea3|interferon-Œ≤]], glatiramer acetate, and [[ae20a0ce|natalizumab]]. Symptomatic treatment for spasticity ([[1ddc3f08|baclofen]]), neuropathic pain, and bladder dysfunction is also important.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A young woman with relapsing and remitting neurological symptoms affecting different parts of the CNS (e.g., an episode of optic neuritis followed months later by leg weakness) is the classic vignette for MS.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Multiple Sclerosis</b> is defined by its pathological hallmark of CNS demyelination disseminated in space and time, leading to a highly variable clinical course of relapsing and remitting neurological deficits that reflect the multifocal nature of the autoimmune attack.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Autoimmune Attack] --> B(Destruction of Oligodendrocytes); B --> C(CNS Demyelination); C --> D(Plaque Formation); D --> E(Neurological Deficits);"
    },
