  "9607467b": {
    "title": "Muscarinic Antagonists",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Autonomic",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Autonomic Drugs"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Muscarinic antagonists</b>, also known as anticholinergics, are drugs that competitively block the action of [[6a005559|acetylcholine]] at muscarinic receptors, thereby inhibiting the effects of the parasympathetic nervous system.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Examples:</b> Atropine, scopolamine, ipratropium, tiotropium, oxybutynin, tolterodine, [[383f6fbe|benztropine]], trihexyphenidyl.</li><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Competitively inhibit ACh at muscarinic receptors in the CNS and periphery.</li><li><b>Effects:</b> Mydriasis, cycloplegia, tachycardia, bronchodilation, decreased GI motility, decreased secretions (salivary, gastric, bronchial), and urinary retention. Mnemonic for anticholinergic effects: \"Hot as a hare, dry as a bone, blind as a bat, red as a beet, mad as a hatter.\"</li><li><b>Neurological Use (Parkinson's):</b> Centrally acting agents like [[383f6fbe|benztropine]] and trihexyphenidyl are used to treat tremor and rigidity in [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]] by correcting the relative cholinergic excess.</li><li><b>Neurological Use (MS):</b> Drugs like oxybutynin are used to treat spastic (hyperreflexic) bladder and urge incontinence in [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Be aware of the contraindications, especially in the elderly (risk of delirium, constipation, urinary retention) and in patients with [[9c80344d|angle-closure glaucoma]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Muscarinic antagonists</b> act as a system-wide 'off switch' for the parasympathetic nervous system, producing a predictable constellation of anticholinergic effects that are therapeutically useful in conditions ranging from COPD to Parkinson's disease, but also responsible for their significant side effect profile.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "antagonizes",
