  "d2b72dd8": {
    "title": "Muscarinic Receptors",
    "primaryType": "molecule",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Physiology",
      "Autonomic",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Receptors"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Muscarinic receptors</b> are a type of G-protein coupled acetylcholine receptor that are the primary end-organ receptors for the parasympathetic nervous system. They are also found in the CNS and at sympathetic postganglionic synapses to sweat glands.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Ligand:</b> [[6a005559|Acetylcholine (ACh)]].</li><li><b>Subtypes & Signaling:</b><br> - <b>M1 (G<sub>q</sub>):</b> CNS, enteric nervous system.<br> - <b>M2 (G<sub>i</sub>):</b> Heart (decreases heart rate and contractility).<br> - <b>M3 (G<sub>q</sub>):</b> Smooth muscle (contraction, e.g., bronchoconstriction, bladder contraction), glands (secretion), and endothelium (vasodilation via NO).</li><li><b>Vomiting Center Input:</b> M1 receptors are present in the vestibular nuclei and nucleus tractus solitarius, and their blockade (e.g., by scopolamine) is effective for [[511db4d8|motion sickness]].</li><li><b>Pharmacology:</b> Agonists (e.g., pilocarpine, bethanechol) mimic parasympathetic effects. Antagonists (e.g., atropine, ipratropium) block parasympathetic effects.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the G-protein coupling mnemonic: \"<b>QISS QIQ SIQ SQS</b>\" (Kiss kick six six). For muscarinic receptors: M1 (<b>Q</b>), M2 (<b>I</b>), M3 (<b>Q</b>).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Muscarinic receptors</b> are the workhorses of the parasympathetic nervous system, translating the signal of acetylcholine into diverse physiological effects‚Äîfrom slowing the heart (M2) to increasing secretions and smooth muscle contraction (M3)‚Äîvia distinct G-protein signaling pathways.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
