  "46380156": {
    "title": "Loss of Muscle Atonia in REM Sleep",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Sleep Medicine",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Sleep Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Loss of muscle atonia in REM sleep</b> is the cardinal feature of <i>REM Sleep Behavior Disorder (RBD)</i>, a parasomnia where the normal paralysis that occurs during REM sleep is absent, leading patients to physically act out their dreams.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Normal REM Sleep:</b> Characterized by rapid eye movements, dreaming, and near-complete muscle paralysis (atonia), which prevents individuals from acting out their dreams.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology of RBD:</b> The loss of atonia is thought to be due to dysfunction in the brainstem nuclei (e.g., subcoeruleus nucleus) that normally inhibit motor neurons during REM sleep.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients (often older men) exhibit dream-enacting behaviors, which can be violent and result in injury to themselves or their bed partners. They can often recall the dream content that corresponds to their actions.</li><li><b>Strong Association with Neurodegeneration:</b> RBD is a very strong predictor of future development of an <mark>Œ±-synucleinopathy</mark>, such as [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]], [[db2f16e5|Lewy body dementia]], or multiple system atrophy. It can precede the motor symptoms of these disorders by years or even decades.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> An older male patient who reports punching or kicking his spouse in his sleep while having vivid dreams is the classic presentation for REM Sleep Behavior Disorder. This finding should raise high suspicion for an underlying or future neurodegenerative disease like Parkinson's.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>loss of muscle atonia during REM sleep</b> is not just a sleep disturbance but a significant prodromal marker for Œ±-synuclein neurodegenerative diseases, representing one of the earliest clinical manifestations of these devastating conditions.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
