  "7cbe4382": {
    "title": "Muscle Spasm Treatment",
    "primaryType": "concept",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neurology",
      "Musculoskeletal",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Spasmolytics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Muscle spasm treatment</b> involves the use of pharmacologic agents known as spasmolytics or muscle relaxants, which act either centrally in the CNS or peripherally at the muscle to reduce involuntary muscle contractions, tone, and spasticity.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Spasticity vs. Spasms:</b> Spasticity is velocity-dependent increased muscle tone from a UMN lesion. Spasms are involuntary contractions from musculoskeletal injury. Different drugs are used for each.</li><li><b>Agents for Spasticity (UMN lesions):</b><br> - <b>[[1ddc3f08|Baclofen]]:</b> A GABA<sub>B</sub> receptor agonist that acts in the spinal cord.<br> - <b>Tizanidine:</b> A central Œ±<sub>2</sub>-adrenergic agonist.<br> - <b>Diazepam:</b> A benzodiazepine that facilitates GABA<sub>A</sub> action.</li><li><b>Agents for Acute Muscle Spasms:</b><br> - <b>Cyclobenzaprine:</b> A centrally acting agent structurally related to TCAs.</li><li><b>Agent Acting Directly on Muscle:</b><br> - <b>Dantrolene:</b> Blocks Ca<sup>2+</sup> release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum. Used for malignant hyperthermia and neuroleptic malignant syndrome, as well as chronic spasticity.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Know the site of action. Baclofen and Tizanidine are central (spinal cord/brainstem). Cyclobenzaprine is central. Dantrolene is peripheral (directly on the muscle).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The pharmacological treatment of <b>muscle spasms and spasticity</b> relies on either dampening CNS excitatory signals (e.g., with baclofen or tizanidine) or directly interfering with the muscle contraction machinery (e.g., with dantrolene), with the choice of agent depending on the underlying cause of the muscle hyperactivity.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "includes",
