  "a0c1b959": {
    "title": "Muscles of Mastication",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Anatomy",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Cranial Nerves"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>muscles of mastication</b> are four pairs of muscles responsible for the movements of the mandible at the temporomandibular joint, primarily for chewing. They are all innervated by the mandibular division of the <i>trigeminal nerve (CN V<sub>3</sub>)</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Muscles that Close the Jaw (Elevation):</b><br> - <b>M</b>asseter<br> - <b>T</b>emporalis<br> - <b>M</b>edial pterygoid<br> Mnemonic: <b>M</b>'s <b>M</b>unch.</li><li><b>Muscle that Opens the Jaw (Depression):</b><br> - <b>L</b>ateral pterygoid. Mnemonic: <b>L</b>ateral <b>L</b>owers.</li><li><b>Innervation:</b> All four muscles are innervated by the motor branch of the <mark>mandibular nerve (CN V<sub>3</sub>)</mark>.</li><li><b>Embryology:</b> Derived from the first pharyngeal arch.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> A lesion of the motor root of CN V or the V<sub>3</sub> branch will cause weakness of the muscles of mastication. On jaw protrusion, the jaw will deviate <mark>toward the side of the lesion</mark> due to the unopposed action of the contralateral lateral pterygoid muscle.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that all muscles of mastication are innervated by V<sub>3</sub>. Jaw deviation toward the lesion is a key sign of a V<sub>3</sub> motor deficit.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The four <b>muscles of mastication</b> are a functional group defined by their shared innervation from CN V<sub>3</sub> and their origin from the first pharyngeal arch, working in concert to elevate, depress, and move the mandible from side to side during chewing.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "are_innervated_by",
