  "7b57eee7": {
    "title": "Mydriasis",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Neurology",
      "Pharmacology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Physical Findings"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Mydriasis</b> is the dilation of the pupil, which can be a physiological response to dim light or a pathological or pharmacological sign.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Physiology:</b> Mediated by the <mark>sympathetic nervous system</mark>. Postganglionic sympathetic fibers release norepinephrine, which acts on Œ±<sub>1</sub>-adrenergic receptors on the dilator pupillae muscle, causing it to contract.</li><li><b>Pharmacological Causes:</b> Can be induced by sympathomimetic agents (e.g., epinephrine, phenylephrine) or <mark>anticholinergic/antimuscarinic agents</mark> (e.g., atropine, tropicamide), which block the parasympathetic constriction of the pupil.</li><li><b>Pathological Causes:</b> A fixed, dilated (\"blown\") pupil is a classic sign of a compressive [[68c66997|oculomotor nerve (CN III) palsy]], as seen with an uncal herniation or a [[a1647fb2|posterior communicating artery aneurysm]].</li><li><b>Meperidine Exception:</b> Unlike most opioids which cause miosis, meperidine can cause mydriasis due to its anticholinergic properties.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A unilaterally dilated and nonreactive pupil is a neurological emergency. It is a key sign of uncal herniation compressing CN III.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Mydriasis</b> results from either sympathetic activation (contraction of the dilator muscle) or parasympathetic blockade (relaxation of the sphincter muscle); its presence, especially when unilateral and fixed, is a critical sign of potential oculomotor nerve compression.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_mediated_by",
        "to": "sympathetic_nervous_system"
      },
