  "c8030560": {
    "title": "Myelencephalon",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Embryology",
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Embryology",
      "Brain Development"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Myelencephalon</b> is the most caudal of the five secondary brain vesicles that arise from the embryonic neural tube. It develops from the posterior part of the hindbrain (rhombencephalon) and gives rise to the medulla oblongata.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Embryonic Origin:</b> Arises from the posterior portion of the rhombencephalon (hindbrain).</li><li><b>Adult Derivative:</b> Differentiates into the <mark>medulla oblongata</mark>, the lowest part of the brainstem.</li><li><b>Associated Cavity:</b> The cavity of the myelencephalon becomes the lower part of the <mark>fourth ventricle</mark>.</li><li><b>Cranial Nerves:</b> The nuclei for cranial nerves IX, X, XI, and XII are located in the medulla, and thus originate from the myelencephalon.</li><li><b>Mnemonic for Vesicles:</b> The five secondary vesicles in rostral to caudal order are Telencephalon, Diencephalon, Mesencephalon, Metencephalon, and Myelencephalon.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Myelencephalon</b> is the final segment of the developing brain, forming the medulla oblongata, which serves as the critical connection between the higher brain centers and the spinal cord and contains the nuclei for vital autonomic functions.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Rhombencephalon (Hindbrain)] --> B(Metencephalon); A --> C(Myelencephalon); C --> D(Medulla Oblongata); C --> E(Lower Fourth Ventricle);"
