    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>myelomeningocele</b> is the most severe form of spina bifida, an open neural tube defect where both the <i>meninges and the spinal cord</i> herniate through a defect in the vertebral column, forming a cystic sac on the infant's back.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Results from the failure of the caudal neuropore of the [[a87cbede|neural tube]] to close during the 4th week of embryonic development.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> A visible sac-like protrusion on the back, typically in the lumbosacral region. It is associated with neurological deficits below the level of the lesion, including lower extremity paralysis and bowel/bladder incontinence.</li><li><b>Associated Condition:</b> Almost always associated with a <mark>Chiari II malformation</mark>, which can lead to obstructive [[0bc2f200|hydrocephalus]].</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> Can be diagnosed prenatally by ultrasound and elevated maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) and amniotic fluid acetylcholinesterase (AChE).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from a meningocele, where only the meninges herniate and the spinal cord remains in the canal. Myelomeningocele involves herniation of the 'myelo' (spinal cord) itself, leading to severe neurological deficits.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>myelomeningocele</b> represents a catastrophic failure of neurulation, where the spinal cord itself is exposed and herniated, leading to inevitable and permanent neurological damage below the lesion and a near-universal association with Chiari II malformation and hydrocephalus.</p>",
