    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Myeloschisis</b> (or rachischisis) is the most severe form of spina bifida, an open neural tube defect where the neural folds fail to fuse, resulting in a flattened, plate-like mass of nervous tissue that is directly exposed to the environment without any overlying meningeal or skin covering.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Represents a complete failure of primary neurulation in the affected region. The neural plate is open and exposed on the surface of the back.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> A raw, exposed plaque of neural tissue is visible on the infant's back. This leads to profound and complete neurological deficits below the level of the lesion.</li><li><b>Comparison to Myelomeningocele:</b> It is more severe than a [[e9cd6754|myelomeningocele]], in which the herniated neural tissue is at least covered by meninges.</li><li><b>Prognosis:</b> Carries a very poor prognosis due to the severe neurological impairment and high risk of infection.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> This is the most severe form of neural tube defect. The key feature is the exposed, non-fused neural plate on the back.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Myeloschisis</b> represents the most fundamental failure of neural tube formation, where the neural folds do not even begin to fuse, leaving the primordial spinal cord exposed to the outside world and resulting in the most devastating neurological outcomes.</p>",
