  "b7808532": {
    "title": "Methemoglobinemia",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Hematology",
      "Toxicology",
      "Pharmacology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Hematology and Oncology",
      "Pathology",
      "Red Blood Cell Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Methemoglobinemia</b> is a condition characterized by the presence of an abnormally high level of methemoglobin (MetHb) in the blood. Methemoglobin is a form of hemoglobin in which the iron in the heme group is in the ferric (Fe<sup>3+</sup>) state, rather than the ferrous (Fe<sup>2+</sup>) state, making it unable to bind oxygen.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The Fe<sup>3+</sup> state not only prevents oxygen binding to that heme group but also causes a left shift in the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve for the remaining normal hemoglobin, impairing oxygen release to tissues. This results in a functional anemia and tissue hypoxia.</li><li><b>Causes:</b> Can be congenital (e.g., cytochrome b5 reductase deficiency) or acquired. Acquired causes include exposure to oxidizing agents such as <mark>dapsone</mark>, nitrites (found in some well water and as preservatives), and topical/local anesthetics like <mark>benzocaine</mark> and prilocaine.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients present with cyanosis that is unresponsive to supplemental oxygen, and blood that is classically described as <mark>\"chocolate-brown\"</mark> in color. Pulse oximetry is unreliable and often reads around 85%.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> Confirmed by co-oximetry of an arterial blood gas sample.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> The antidote is <mark>methylene blue</mark>, which acts as an electron donor to reduce Fe<sup>3+</sup> back to Fe<sup>2+</sup> via the NADPH-MetHb reductase pathway.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient who develops cyanosis and shortness of breath after a dental procedure or endoscopy (where benzocaine spray is used) with chocolate-brown blood is a classic vignette for acquired methemoglobinemia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Methemoglobinemia</b> is a state of 'iron rust' within hemoglobin, where oxidizing drugs convert functional Fe<sup>2+</sup> to non-functional Fe<sup>3+</sup>, leading to a profound tissue hypoxia that is uniquely treated with the reducing agent methylene blue.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
