    "title": "Meyer's Loop",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Visual Pathway"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Meyer's loop</b> is the inferior portion of the optic radiation, a bundle of nerve fibers that curves from the lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN) of the thalamus, sweeps anteriorly into the <i>temporal lobe</i>, and then projects posteriorly to the lower bank of the calcarine sulcus in the occipital lobe.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathway:</b> Carries visual information from the <mark>inferior retina</mark> (which corresponds to the superior visual field).</li><li><b>Location:</b> Travels through the temporal lobe, looping around the inferior horn of the lateral ventricle.</li><li><b>Lesion Effect:</b> A lesion of Meyer's loop results in a contralateral <mark>superior quadrantanopia</mark> (loss of the upper quadrant of the visual field on the opposite side). This is often referred to as a \"pie in the sky\" defect.</li><li><b>Causes of Lesions:</b> Can be damaged by strokes involving the [[143bb23d|Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)]], temporal lobe tumors, or temporal lobectomy surgery.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the mnemonic <b>L-M-N-O-P</b>: <b>L</b>ateral geniculate nucleus to <b>M</b>eyer's loop (<b>N</b>o, that's wrong). Better mnemonic: <b>T</b>emporal lobe lesion = <b>T</b>op-quadrant defect (\"<b>T</b>ea in the <b>T</b>reetops\"). Contrast with the dorsal optic radiation in the <b>P</b>arietal lobe, which causes a \"<b>P</b>ie on the <b>F</b>loor\" (inferior quadrantanopia).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Meyer's loop</b> takes a detour through the temporal lobe to carry information from the inferior retina; therefore, a lesion in this specific location predictably causes a contralateral \"pie in the sky\" visual field defect, a key localizing sign in neuro-ophthalmology.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Inferior Retina] --> B(LGN); B --> C(Meyer's Loop in Temporal Lobe); C --> D(Lower Visual Cortex); A --Represents--> E(Superior Visual Field);"
    },
