    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Microglia</b> are the resident immune cells of the central nervous system (CNS), acting as the primary phagocytic scavengers and mediators of the innate immune response within the brain and spinal cord.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Embryonic Origin:</b> Unlike other glial cells (which are neuroectodermal), microglia are derived from the <mark>mesoderm</mark> (yolk sac myeloid progenitors) and migrate into the CNS during development.</li><li><b>Function:</b> In the resting state, they constantly survey their microenvironment with motile processes. Upon activation by injury, infection, or inflammation, they transform into an amoeboid shape, become phagocytic, and release inflammatory mediators (e.g., cytokines, nitric oxide).</li><li><b>Role in Pathology:</b> They are activated in response to any CNS injury, including stroke, trauma, and infection. They phagocytose cellular debris and dead neurons.</li><li><b>HIV-Associated Dementia:</b> In HIV infection, microglia can become infected and fuse to form <mark>multinucleated giant cells</mark>, which is a pathognomonic finding in HIV-associated dementia.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the unique mesodermal origin of microglia, distinguishing them from all other CNS cells which are of ectodermal origin. Mnemonic: <b>M</b>icroglia = <b>M</b>acrophages of the CNS, from <b>M</b>esoderm.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Microglia</b> are the dedicated immune defenders of the CNS, originating from the mesoderm and acting as the brain's resident macrophages; their activation is a double-edged sword, essential for clearing debris but also capable of contributing to neuroinflammation.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
