    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Midazolam</b> is a short-acting <i>benzodiazepine</i> with potent anxiolytic, amnestic, sedative, and anticonvulsant properties, commonly used for procedural sedation and as an induction agent for general anesthesia.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Facilitates the action of [[5aa5cb91|GABA]] at the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor, increasing the <mark>frequency</mark> of Cl<sup>-</sup> channel opening, which leads to CNS depression.</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Has a <mark>rapid onset</mark> and <mark>short duration</mark> of action, making it ideal for procedural use. It is one of the benzodiazepines with minimal first-pass metabolism.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used for sedation before medical procedures (e.g., endoscopy, surgery), as an anxiolytic, and for the treatment of status epilepticus.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Can cause significant respiratory depression, especially when combined with other CNS depressants like opioids. Also causes hypotension and anterograde amnesia.</li><li><b>Reversal:</b> The effects of midazolam can be reversed by the competitive antagonist <mark>flumazenil</mark>.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Midazolam is a go-to drug for procedural sedation because of its rapid onset, short duration, and potent amnestic effects. Remember that its respiratory depressant effects are additive with opioids.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Midazolam</b> is a fast-acting, short-duration benzodiazepine prized for its ability to induce sedation and amnesia for uncomfortable procedures, but its potent CNS depressant effects necessitate careful monitoring of respiratory status.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
