    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Midbrain</b> (or mesencephalon) is the most superior part of the brainstem, connecting the pons and cerebellum with the forebrain. It is a crucial center for motor control, auditory and visual processing, and consciousness.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Embryology:</b> Arises from the mesencephalon, one of the three primary brain vesicles.</li><li><b>Cranial Nerve Nuclei:</b> Contains the nuclei for the [[68c66997|oculomotor nerve (CN III)]] and the [[bba6093a|trochlear nerve (CN IV)]].</li><li><b>Key Structures:</b><br> - <b>Tectum (Dorsal):</b> Contains the superior colliculi (visual reflexes) and inferior colliculi (auditory reflexes).<br> - <b>Tegmentum (Ventral):</b> Contains the red nucleus (motor coordination) and substantia nigra (motor control, dopamine production).<br> - <b>Cerebral Peduncles:</b> Large bundles of descending motor fibers (corticospinal and corticobulbar tracts).</li><li><b>Vascular Supply:</b> Primarily supplied by branches of the [[b6a2cc31|Posterior Cerebral Artery (PCA)]].</li><li><b>Clinical Syndromes:</b> Lesions can cause specific syndromes like Weber syndrome (CN III palsy + contralateral hemiplegia) and Parinaud syndrome (dorsal midbrain compression).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Midbrain</b> is a compact but vital relay and processing center, housing the origins of the nerves that move the eyes and containing the substantia nigra, whose degeneration is the cause of Parkinson's disease.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
