  "143bb23d": {
    "title": "Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "Vascular",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Cerebrovascular System"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)</b> is the largest cerebral artery and a terminal branch of the internal carotid artery. It supplies a significant portion of the lateral cerebral hemispheres, and its occlusion is the most common cause of ischemic stroke.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Territory:</b> Supplies the lateral surface of the frontal, parietal, and temporal lobes. This includes the primary motor and somatosensory cortices for the <mark>face and upper limb</mark>, as well as the language centers (Broca's and Wernicke's areas) in the dominant hemisphere.</li><li><b>Stroke Effects:</b> An MCA stroke classically causes <mark>contralateral hemiparesis and sensory loss</mark>, predominantly affecting the face and arm more than the leg.</li><li><b>Dominant Hemisphere (usually Left) Stroke:</b> Can cause [[6bc9a567|aphasia]] (Broca's, Wernicke's, or global).</li><li><b>Non-dominant Hemisphere (usually Right) Stroke:</b> Can cause [[134828d8|hemineglect syndrome]].</li><li><b>Deep Branches (Lenticulostriate Arteries):</b> Supply the basal ganglia and internal capsule. Occlusion of these small vessels causes lacunar strokes, such as a [[8aefcafe|pure motor stroke]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Contralateral face and arm weakness/sensory loss is the hallmark of an MCA stroke. If speech is affected, the lesion is in the dominant hemisphere. If neglect is present, the lesion is in the non-dominant hemisphere.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Middle Cerebral Artery</b> supplies the eloquent lateral aspects of the brain, including motor and sensory areas for the face and arm, and the language centers. Consequently, an MCA stroke produces some of the most devastating and classic neurological deficits.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
