  "45568c28": {
    "title": "Middle Ear",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Otology",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Otology",
      "Anatomy"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Middle Ear</b> is an air-filled cavity within the temporal bone, located between the tympanic membrane and the inner ear. It contains the auditory ossicles and is connected to the nasopharynx by the eustachian tube.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Components:</b> The middle ear cavity contains the three [[3aea8cac|auditory ossicles]] (malleus, incus, stapes).</li><li><b>Function:</b> Transmits and amplifies sound vibrations from the tympanic membrane (eardrum) to the oval window of the inner ear.</li><li><b>Eustachian Tube:</b> Connects the middle ear to the nasopharynx, allowing for pressure equalization between the middle ear and the atmosphere. Dysfunction is a key factor in [[a03641af|otitis media]].</li><li><b>Muscles:</b> Contains the tensor tympani (innervated by CN V<sub>3</sub>) and stapedius (innervated by CN VII) muscles, which dampen loud sounds.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> The most common pathology is [[a03641af|acute otitis media]], an infection of the middle ear space, especially common in children. Other conditions include [[03ef3134|cholesteatoma]] and otosclerosis.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Middle Ear</b> functions as a mechanical impedance-matching system, using the lever action of the ossicles to efficiently transfer sound energy from the low-impedance air of the external world to the high-impedance fluid of the inner ear.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
