  "f3073d4b": {
    "title": "Middle Meningeal Artery",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "Neurosurgery",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Cerebrovascular System"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Middle Meningeal Artery</b> is the largest of the three arteries that supply the meninges. Its rupture, typically due to head trauma, is the classic cause of an <i>epidural hematoma</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Origin:</b> It is a branch of the maxillary artery, which in turn is a branch of the external carotid artery.</li><li><b>Course:</b> Enters the skull through the <mark>foramen spinosum</mark> and runs in a groove on the inner surface of the temporal bone, between the dura mater and the skull.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> Laceration of this artery, often associated with a fracture of the <mark>temporal bone at the pterion</mark> (the thinnest part of the skull), leads to an <mark>epidural hematoma</mark>.</li><li><b>Epidural Hematoma:</b> An arterial bleed that accumulates rapidly in the potential space between the dura and the skull, creating a lens-shaped (biconvex) hematoma on CT scan.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Trauma to the side of the head (pterion) leading to a brief loss of consciousness, a 'lucid interval,' and then rapid neurological decline is the classic presentation for an epidural hematoma from a middle meningeal artery tear.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Middle Meningeal Artery's</b> vulnerable course in a groove on the inner surface of the thin temporal bone makes it the primary culprit in epidural hematomas following lateral head trauma, leading to a rapidly expanding, life-threatening arterial bleed.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
