  "c8833bae": {
    "title": "Migraine Headaches",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pain Management",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Headaches"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Migraine</b> is a primary headache disorder characterized by recurrent, moderate to severe headaches that are typically unilateral and pulsating, and are often associated with nausea, photophobia, and phonophobia. Some attacks are preceded by a sensory warning sign or aura.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Involves irritation of the [[0eb45a0a|trigeminal nerve (CN V)]], meninges, or blood vessels, leading to the release of vasoactive neuropeptides like <mark>calcitonin gene-related peptide (CGRP)</mark> and substance P.</li><li><b>Clinical Features (POUND mnemonic):</b> <b>P</b>ulsatile, <b>O</b>ne-day duration (4-72 hrs), <b>U</b>nilateral, <b>N</b>ausea, <b>D</b>isabling.</li><li><b>Aura:</b> A transient visual, sensory, or motor disturbance that precedes or accompanies the headache. The most common is a visual aura (e.g., scintillating scotoma).</li><li><b>Abortive Treatment:</b> For acute attacks, treatments include NSAIDs, <mark>triptans</mark> (5-HT<sub>1B/1D</sub> agonists like sumatriptan), and dihydroergotamine.</li><li><b>Prophylactic Treatment:</b> For frequent migraines, options include beta-blockers (e.g., propranolol), TCAs (e.g., amitriptyline), anticonvulsants (e.g., topiramate, valproate), and anti-CGRP monoclonal antibodies.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Triptans are contraindicated in patients with coronary artery disease or Prinzmetal angina due to their vasoconstrictive effects.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Migraine</b> is a complex neurovascular disorder, not just a simple headache. Its pathophysiology involves trigeminal nerve activation and CGRP release, making CGRP antagonists and 5-HT agonists (triptans) specific and effective treatments.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
