  "e55deaa2": {
    "title": "Miosis",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Neurology",
      "Pharmacology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Physical Findings"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Miosis</b> is the constriction of the pupil, which can be a physiological response to bright light or a pathological or pharmacological sign.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Physiology:</b> Mediated by the <mark>parasympathetic nervous system</mark>. Preganglionic fibers from the Edinger-Westphal nucleus travel with the [[68c66997|oculomotor nerve (CN III)]] to the ciliary ganglion. Postganglionic fibers release ACh, which acts on M3 muscarinic receptors on the <mark>sphincter pupillae muscle</mark>, causing it to contract.</li><li><b>Pharmacological Causes:</b> Can be induced by cholinomimetics (e.g., [[f54d873a|pilocarpine]]) or acetylcholinesterase inhibitors. <mark>Opioids</mark> (e.g., morphine, heroin) characteristically cause pinpoint pupils by stimulating the Edinger-Westphal nucleus.</li><li><b>Pathological Causes:</b> A key feature of [[c19010a3|Horner syndrome]], which results from disruption of the sympathetic pathway to the eye, leading to unopposed parasympathetic tone.</li><li><b>Pupillary Control Pathway:</b> The pupillary light reflex pathway involves CN II (afferent) and CN III (efferent), resulting in miosis.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The triad of coma, respiratory depression, and miosis is classic for opioid overdose. Remember that tolerance does not develop to the miotic effects of opioids.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Miosis</b> results from parasympathetic activation causing contraction of the pupillary sphincter muscle. Its presence can be a key diagnostic clue, pointing to conditions ranging from opioid overdose to Horner syndrome.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
