    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Moraxella catarrhalis</b> is a gram-negative diplococcus that is a common commensal of the upper respiratory tract and a frequent cause of otitis media, sinusitis, and exacerbations of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Microbiology:</b> Aerobic, non-motile, gram-negative diplococcus. It is oxidase-positive.</li><li><b>Clinical Infections:</b><br> - <b>[[a03641af|Otitis Media]]:</b> One of the top three bacterial causes in children, along with <i>S. pneumoniae</i> and non-typeable <i>H. influenzae</i>.<br> - <b>Sinusitis:</b> A common cause of acute bacterial sinusitis in both children and adults.<br> - <b>COPD Exacerbations:</b> A significant cause of bacterial exacerbations of chronic bronchitis and COPD.</li><li><b>Virulence:</b> Produces beta-lactamase, making it resistant to penicillins like amoxicillin.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Often treated with amoxicillin-clavulanate, cephalosporins, or macrolides to cover for beta-lactamase production.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> When considering the causes of [[a03641af|otitis media]] or a COPD exacerbation, always include <i>M. catarrhalis</i> in the differential, and remember that it is typically beta-lactamase positive.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Moraxella catarrhalis</b> is a common respiratory pathogen that, along with <i>S. pneumoniae</i> and <i>H. influenzae</i>, forms the classic triad of bacteria responsible for otitis media and sinusitis, with its frequent production of beta-lactamase influencing antibiotic choice.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
