  "666cc8e9": {
    "title": "Moro Reflex",
    "primaryType": "physiology",
    "tags": [
      "Pediatrics",
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Reflexes"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Moro reflex</b>, also known as the startle reflex, is a primitive, involuntary reflex present in infants in response to a sudden loss of support or a loud noise, characterized by the spreading out and then pulling in of the arms.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Elicitation:</b> Elicited by allowing the infant's head to suddenly but gently fall backward.</li><li><b>Response:</b> The infant responds by symmetrically abducting and extending the arms, followed by adduction and flexion of the arms. The infant may also cry.</li><li><b>Developmental Timeline:</b> Present at birth and should disappear by <mark>4-6 months of age</mark>.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> Its presence at birth indicates a normal, intact central nervous system. <br> - <b>Absence:</b> A symmetric absence may indicate severe CNS damage. <br> - <b>Asymmetry:</b> An asymmetric response suggests a focal peripheral lesion, such as a brachial plexus injury (e.g., Erb's palsy) or a fractured clavicle on the non-responsive side.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The persistence of the Moro reflex beyond 6 months of age is abnormal and suggests underlying neurological disease. An asymmetric Moro reflex is a key sign of a birth injury like a brachial plexus palsy.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Moro reflex</b> is a critical component of the newborn neurological exam; its symmetric presence is a reassuring sign of CNS integrity, while its asymmetry or absence can be the first clue to a significant central or peripheral nervous system injury.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
