    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Morphine</b> is a potent opiate analgesic drug that is the prototypical <i>Œº-opioid receptor agonist</i>, used for the management of severe pain.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Acts as a full agonist at Œº-opioid receptors in the CNS, leading to hyperpolarization of neurons and inhibition of pain signal transmission.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Management of severe acute and chronic pain (e.g., postoperative pain, cancer pain). Also used for [[d268ace0|acute cardiogenic pulmonary edema]] due to its anxiolytic and venodilating (preload reducing) effects.</li><li><b>Metabolism:</b> Undergoes extensive first-pass metabolism in the liver to form active metabolites, including morphine-6-glucuronide (more potent analgesic) and morphine-3-glucuronide (associated with neuroexcitatory effects). These metabolites are renally cleared, so caution is needed in renal failure.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Respiratory depression, sedation, constipation, miosis, nausea, vomiting, hypotension, and potential for tolerance and dependence.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Morphine and its active metabolites accumulate in renal failure, increasing the risk of toxicity. Remember its use in pulmonary edema is for both analgesia/anxiolysis and preload reduction.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Morphine</b> is the gold standard opioid analgesic, providing powerful pain relief by activating Œº-opioid receptors, but its utility is tempered by a significant side effect profile, most notably life-threatening respiratory depression.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
