    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Memantine</b> is a non-competitive <i>NMDA receptor antagonist</i> used for the symptomatic treatment of moderate to severe [[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Blocks the NMDA (N-methyl-D-aspartate) receptor, a glutamate receptor. In [[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]], excessive glutamate activity is thought to cause excitotoxicity and neuronal death. Memantine blocks this pathological activation while allowing for normal physiological synaptic transmission.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used to treat moderate to severe dementia in [[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]]. It may provide modest benefits in cognition, daily function, and behavior.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Generally well-tolerated. Side effects can include dizziness, confusion, and hallucinations.</li><li><b>Combination Therapy:</b> Often used in combination with an acetylcholinesterase inhibitor (e.g., [[47d0372e|donepezil]]) for a dual-mechanism approach to treating Alzheimer's symptoms.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> While acetylcholinesterase inhibitors are first-line for mild-to-moderate Alzheimer's, memantine is added for moderate-to-severe disease. Remember its mechanism is to prevent glutamate-induced excitotoxicity.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Memantine</b> works by protecting neurons from the chronic, low-level excitotoxicity caused by excessive glutamate in [[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]], acting as a 'noise filter' for the NMDA receptor to improve cognitive function without blocking normal learning and memory processes.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Excess Glutamate] --> B(Overstimulation of NMDA Receptor); B --> C(Excitotoxicity); C --> D(Neuronal Death in Alzheimer's); E[Memantine] --|Blocks|--> B;"
