    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Memory</b> is a complex cognitive function involving multiple neural structures, primarily within the [[73ace357|limbic system]] and temporal lobes, responsible for encoding, storing, and retrieving information.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Hippocampus:</b> A critical structure located in the medial temporal lobe. It is essential for the formation of new declarative (explicit) memories (facts and events). Bilateral damage to the hippocampus results in profound <mark>anterograde amnesia</mark>.</li><li><b>Amygdala:</b> Located adjacent to the hippocampus, the amygdala is crucial for processing the emotional significance of memories, particularly fear-related memories.</li><li><b>Mammillary Bodies:</b> Part of the [[73ace357|limbic system]] that receives input from the hippocampus via the fornix. Damage to the mammillary bodies, as seen in <mark>Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome</mark>, leads to severe memory deficits and confabulation.</li><li><b>Cerebral Cortex:</b> Long-term memories are thought to be stored in a distributed fashion across the cerebral cortex, in the same areas that were involved in the initial perception and processing of the information.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Bilateral hippocampal damage causes anterograde amnesia (can't make new memories), while bilateral mammillary body damage (Wernicke-Korsakoff) also causes anterograde amnesia plus confabulation.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The formation of new long-term memories is a process critically dependent on the integrity of the medial temporal lobe, especially the hippocampus, which acts as a temporary storage and consolidation hub before memories are distributed to the cortex for permanent storage.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
