    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>Meningioma</b> is a typically benign, slow-growing tumor that arises from the meningothelial (arachnoid cap) cells of the [[805d0677|meninges]]. It is the second most common primary brain tumor in adults.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Epidemiology:</b> More common in females. Risk factors include prior radiation to the head and Neurofibromatosis type 2.</li><li><b>Location:</b> Occurs along any dural surface, often on the convexities of the cerebral hemispheres, parasagittal region, or skull base. It is an <mark>extra-axial</mark> tumor, meaning it is external to the brain parenchyma.</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> Appears as a well-circumscribed, dural-based mass that enhances brightly and uniformly with contrast. A characteristic <mark>\"dural tail\"</mark> of enhancing dura may be seen.</li><li><b>Histology:</b> Characterized by spindle cells arranged in a <mark>whorled pattern</mark> and the presence of <mark>psammoma bodies</mark> (laminated calcifications).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Often asymptomatic and found incidentally. If symptomatic, it causes focal neurological deficits or seizures due to compression of the underlying brain.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A well-demarcated, dural-based tumor with a dural tail on MRI, and psammoma bodies on histology, is pathognomonic for a meningioma.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>Meningioma</b> is a classic 'outside-in' brain tumor, arising from the protective meningeal layers and causing symptoms by compressing, rather than invading, the adjacent brain parenchyma, which is reflected in its well-circumscribed appearance on imaging.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
