    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>meningocele</b> is a type of spina bifida, a neural tube defect, where the <i>meninges</i> herniate through a defect in the vertebral column, forming a fluid-filled sac on the infant's back, but the spinal cord itself remains within the spinal canal.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Results from the failure of the caudal neuropore of the [[a87cbede|neural tube]] to close, with a subsequent defect in the overlying vertebral arches.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> A visible, membrane-covered sac protruding from the back, typically in the lumbosacral region.</li><li><b>Neurological Function:</b> Because the spinal cord is not displaced into the sac, neurological function is often <mark>normal or only mildly affected</mark>.</li><li><b>Distinction from Myelomeningocele:</b> This is the key distinction. In a [[e9cd6754|myelomeningocele]], both the meninges and the spinal cord herniate into the sac, resulting in severe neurological deficits.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The key difference between a meningocele and a myelomeningocele is the contents of the sac. If the spinal cord is not in the sac, it's a meningocele, and the prognosis is much better.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>meningocele</b> is a 'best-case scenario' for an open neural tube defect, as the herniation is limited to the meninges and CSF, sparing the spinal cord itself from displacement and severe damage.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
