    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Meperidine</b> is a synthetic <i>opioid analgesic</i> that acts as a Œº-opioid receptor agonist, used for short-term management of moderate to severe pain. Its use is limited due to its toxic metabolite and drug interactions.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Agonist at Œº-opioid receptors. It also has significant antimuscarinic (anticholinergic) effects.</li><li><b>Metabolism:</b> Metabolized in the liver to <mark>normeperidine</mark>, a neurotoxic metabolite. Normeperidine accumulation can cause CNS excitation, tremors, and seizures.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Use is generally discouraged due to its toxic metabolite. It was historically used for pain in pancreatitis (thought to cause less sphincter of Oddi spasm than morphine, though this is debated) and to treat rigors/shivering.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> In addition to standard opioid side effects, it can cause <mark>seizures</mark> due to normeperidine accumulation, especially in patients with renal failure or those on high doses. Unlike other opioids, it can cause <mark>mydriasis</mark> (pupil dilation) due to its anticholinergic effects.</li><li><b>Contraindication:</b> <u>Absolutely contraindicated</u> with <mark>MAO inhibitors</mark>, as the combination can precipitate life-threatening [[serotonin_syndrome|serotonin syndrome]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the two unique features of meperidine compared to other opioids: it can cause seizures (via normeperidine) and mydriasis (anticholinergic effect), and it is contraindicated with MAOIs.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Meperidine</b> is an opioid with a dangerous secret: its neurotoxic metabolite, normeperidine, which accumulates in renal failure and can cause seizures, making it a poor choice for long-term or high-dose pain management.</p>",
