    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Mepivacaine</b> is an intermediate-acting <i>local anesthetic</i> of the amide class, used for local or regional anesthesia via infiltration, nerve block, or epidural techniques.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Class:</b> Amide local anesthetic. Mnemonic: Amides have two 'i's in their name (mep<b>i</b>vaca<b>i</b>ne).</li><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Blocks voltage-gated <mark>Na<sup>+</sup> channels</mark> on the inner portion of the nerve cell membrane, preventing the propagation of [[832463e6|action potentials]] and thus blocking nerve conduction.</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Has an intermediate duration of action. It is not effective as a topical anesthetic.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Systemic toxicity can occur with accidental intravascular injection or overdose, leading to CNS excitation (seizures) followed by depression (coma, respiratory arrest), and cardiovascular toxicity (hypotension, arrhythmias, bradycardia).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Know how to differentiate amide from ester local anesthetics. Allergic reactions are much more common with esters (due to PABA metabolite) than with amides.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Mepivacaine</b> is a workhorse amide local anesthetic that provides reliable nerve blockade by blocking sodium channels, with a safety profile typical of its class, where systemic toxicity is the primary concern.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
