    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Merkel discs</b> (or Merkel cell-neurite complexes) are specialized mechanoreceptors in the skin responsible for sensing fine, discriminative touch, such as pressure, shape, and texture.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Structure:</b> Consist of a Merkel cell (a specialized epithelial cell) in close apposition with an enlarged nerve terminal.</li><li><b>Location:</b> Found in the basal layer of the epidermis, particularly abundant in fingertips, lips, and other highly sensitive areas.</li><li><b>Function:</b> They are <mark>slowly adapting</mark> mechanoreceptors, meaning they fire continuously as long as a stimulus is present. This property makes them ideal for encoding static features like sustained <mark>pressure</mark> and the shape/texture of objects.</li><li><b>Nerve Fibers:</b> Transmitted by large, myelinated AŒ≤ fibers.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Signals travel via the [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Associate slowly adapting receptors with static qualities. Merkel discs = sustained pressure/shape. Ruffini corpuscles = sustained stretch. Rapidly adapting receptors (Meissner's, Pacinian) detect changes and vibration.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Merkel discs</b> are the high-fidelity touch receptors of the skin, providing the brain with a continuous stream of information about the precise shape and texture of objects being touched, a function enabled by their slowly adapting nature.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
