    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Mesencephalon</b>, also known as the midbrain, is the middle of the three primary brain vesicles that form during early embryonic development. It persists as a distinct structure in the adult brain, forming the most superior part of the brainstem.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Embryonic Origin:</b> One of the three primary brain vesicles, situated between the prosencephalon (forebrain) and rhombencephalon (hindbrain). It does not subdivide into secondary vesicles.</li><li><b>Adult Derivative:</b> Differentiates into the <mark>midbrain</mark>.</li><li><b>Associated Cavity:</b> The cavity of the mesencephalon narrows to form the <mark>cerebral aqueduct</mark>, which connects the third and fourth ventricles.</li><li><b>Cranial Nerves:</b> The nuclei for the [[68c66997|oculomotor nerve (CN III)]] and the [[bba6093a|trochlear nerve (CN IV)]] are located in the midbrain.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the developmental pathway: Mesencephalon (primary vesicle) ‚Üí Mesencephalon (secondary vesicle) ‚Üí Midbrain (adult structure).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Mesencephalon</b> is the developmental precursor to the midbrain, a critical brainstem region that retains its name from embryology into adulthood and houses the vital conduit for CSF flow, the cerebral aqueduct.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Primary Vesicles] --> B(Mesencephalon); B --> C[Secondary Vesicles]; C --> D(Mesencephalon); D --> E[Adult Structures]; E --> F(Midbrain); E --> G(Cerebral Aqueduct);"
