    "title": "Mesocortical Pathway",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Psychiatry",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Dopaminergic Pathways"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Mesocortical Pathway</b> is a dopaminergic tract that projects from the <i>ventral tegmental area (VTA)</i> in the midbrain to the <i>prefrontal cortex</i>. It is critically involved in cognitive functions, motivation, and emotion.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Origin:</b> Ventral Tegmental Area (VTA) in the midbrain.</li><li><b>Termination:</b> Prefrontal cortex (especially the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex).</li><li><b>Neurotransmitter:</b> [[90adc821|Dopamine]].</li><li><b>Function:</b> Plays a key role in executive functions, such as working memory, planning, and attention, as well as motivation and emotional regulation.</li><li><b>Pathology (Schizophrenia):</b> Hypoactivity (decreased dopamine) in the mesocortical pathway is thought to be responsible for the <mark>negative symptoms</mark> of schizophrenia (e.g., apathy, flat affect, cognitive deficits).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the two key VTA pathways in schizophrenia: the <b>mesocortical</b> pathway is underactive (negative symptoms), while the [[f4381654|mesolimbic]] pathway is overactive (positive symptoms).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Mesocortical Pathway</b> is the dopaminergic connection to the brain's 'CEO,' the prefrontal cortex. Its underperformance is a leading hypothesis for the debilitating negative and cognitive symptoms of schizophrenia.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Ventral Tegmental Area VTA] --Dopamine--> B(Prefrontal Cortex); B --> C(Executive Function & Motivation);"
