    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Metamorphopsia</b> is a type of visual distortion in which straight lines appear wavy or bent. It is a key symptom of macular disease.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Caused by disruption of the normal arrangement of photoreceptors in the macula, the central part of the retina responsible for high-acuity vision.</li><li><b>Classic Association:</b> It is a hallmark symptom of <mark>wet (exudative) age-related macular degeneration (AMD)</mark>. The leakage of fluid and blood from choroidal neovascularization beneath the macula elevates and distorts the retinal layers.</li><li><b>Other Causes:</b> Can also be seen in other macular pathologies, such as epiretinal membrane, macular pucker, and central serous chorioretinopathy.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> Can be subjectively tested by the patient at home using an <mark>Amsler grid</mark>. The patient looks at the grid, and if the lines appear wavy, distorted, or have blank spots, it suggests macular pathology.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient, especially an elderly one, who complains that straight lines (like on a door frame or telephone pole) suddenly appear wavy has metamorphopsia and should be evaluated urgently for wet AMD.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Metamorphopsia</b> is a specific visual distortion that acts as a sensitive alarm bell for macular pathology, particularly the neovascularization of wet AMD, signaling a disruption in the precise architecture of the central retina.</p>",
