    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Metencephalon</b> is one of the five secondary brain vesicles, arising from the anterior part of the embryonic hindbrain (rhombencephalon). It develops into the pons and the cerebellum.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Embryonic Origin:</b> Arises from the rostral (anterior) portion of the rhombencephalon (hindbrain).</li><li><b>Adult Derivatives:</b> Differentiates into the <mark>pons</mark> and the <mark>cerebellum</mark>.</li><li><b>Associated Cavity:</b> The cavity of the metencephalon becomes the upper part of the <mark>fourth ventricle</mark>.</li><li><b>Mnemonic for Vesicles:</b> The five secondary vesicles in rostral to caudal order are Telencephalon, Diencephalon, Mesencephalon, <b>Metencephalon</b>, and Myelencephalon.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that the two components of the hindbrain (rhombencephalon) are the metencephalon (pons and cerebellum) and the myelencephalon (medulla).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Metencephalon</b> is the developmental precursor to the pons and cerebellum, two structures that are anatomically and functionally linked to form a critical hub for motor control and sensory relay in the adult brainstem.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Rhombencephalon (Hindbrain)] --> B(Metencephalon); A --> C(Myelencephalon); B --> D(Pons); B --> E(Cerebellum); B --> F(Upper Fourth Ventricle);"
