    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Methadone</b> is a long-acting, synthetic <i>Œº-opioid receptor agonist</i> used for the management of chronic pain and, most notably, as a maintenance therapy for opioid use disorder.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> A potent, long-acting full agonist at Œº-opioid receptors. It also has antagonist activity at the NMDA receptor, which may contribute to its efficacy in neuropathic pain.</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Has a long and variable half-life (typically 24-36 hours), which allows for once-daily dosing and prevents the rapid peaks and troughs associated with short-acting opioids like heroin, thereby reducing cravings and withdrawal symptoms.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b><br> - <b>Opioid Maintenance Therapy:</b> The primary use. Reduces illicit opioid use, mortality, and criminal activity.<br> - <b>Chronic Pain:</b> Effective for chronic pain, including neuropathic pain.<br> - <b>[[b95e97eb|Neonatal Abstinence Syndrome]]:</b> Used to treat withdrawal in newborns exposed to opioids in utero.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Similar to other opioids (respiratory depression, constipation, sedation). A major unique risk is <mark>QT interval prolongation</mark> and torsades de pointes.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Methadone's long half-life is its key feature for maintenance therapy. The risk of QT prolongation is a high-yield adverse effect to remember.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Methadone</b> treats opioid addiction by substituting a long-acting, orally administered opioid for a short-acting, often injected one. This stabilizes the patient by preventing withdrawal and reducing cravings, allowing them to disengage from the cycle of illicit drug use, but it carries its own risks, including QT prolongation.</p>",
