      "definition": "<p><b>Malignant (necrotizing) otitis externa</b> is a severe, invasive, and potentially life-threatening infection of the external auditory canal and skull base, typically caused by <i>Pseudomonas aeruginosa</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The infection begins in the external ear canal and aggressively spreads, causing osteomyelitis of the temporal bone and skull base.</li><li><b>Risk Factors:</b> Almost exclusively seen in <mark>elderly patients with diabetes mellitus</mark> and other immunocompromised individuals.</li><li><b>Causative Organism:</b> The most common pathogen is <mark>Pseudomonas aeruginosa</mark>.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Presents with exquisite, severe otalgia (ear pain) that is often worse at night, purulent otorrhea, and the presence of <mark>granulation tissue</mark> at the floor of the ear canal at the bone-cartilage junction.</li><li><b>Complications:</b> Can progress to involve cranial nerves, most commonly the [[dea9755f|facial nerve (CN VII)]] as it exits the stylomastoid foramen, leading to facial paralysis. Further spread can cause meningitis or brain abscess.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> An elderly diabetic patient with severe ear pain, drainage, and granulation tissue in the ear canal is the classic vignette for malignant otitis externa.</li></ul>",
