      "definition": "<p><b>Malignant hyperthermia (MH)</b> is a rare, life-threatening, hypermetabolic state of skeletal muscle triggered by exposure to volatile inhaled anesthetics (e.g., halothane, sevoflurane) or the depolarizing neuromuscular blocker <i>succinylcholine</i> in genetically susceptible individuals.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Genetics:</b> Most commonly an autosomal dominant condition with variable penetrance, associated with mutations in the <mark>ryanodine receptor (RYR1)</mark> gene.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The triggering agent causes a defect in the RYR1 receptor on the sarcoplasmic reticulum, leading to a massive, uncontrolled release of Ca<sup>2+</sup> into the cytoplasm of skeletal muscle cells.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Occurs during or shortly after anesthesia. Signs include tachycardia, tachypnea, muscle rigidity (especially masseter muscle spasm), hyperthermia (a late sign), and hypercapnia.</li><li><b>Lab Findings:</b> Rhabdomyolysis leads to hyperkalemia, myoglobinuria, and a profound metabolic acidosis.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Immediate cessation of the triggering agent and administration of <mark>dantrolene</mark>, a muscle relaxant that blocks Ca<sup>2+</sup> release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum by acting on the RYR1 receptor.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient developing fever, muscle rigidity, and tachycardia shortly after receiving general anesthesia is the classic scenario. The immediate treatment is dantrolene.</li></ul>",
