      "definition": "<p><b>Mannitol</b> is an <i>osmotic diuretic</i> administered intravenously to reduce acutely raised intracranial pressure (ICP) and intraocular pressure by drawing water out of tissues and into the bloodstream.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> As an osmotically active agent, mannitol increases the osmolarity of the blood and renal tubular fluid. In the brain, it creates an osmotic gradient that pulls water from the brain parenchyma across the [[dd47b9cc|blood-brain barrier]] into the vasculature, thereby reducing cerebral edema and ICP.</li><li><b>Clinical Use (Neurology):</b> Used in emergencies to treat <mark>cerebral edema</mark> and acutely elevated ICP (e.g., from head trauma, tumors, or stroke).</li><li><b>Clinical Use (Ophthalmology):</b> Used to rapidly lower intraocular pressure in acute angle-closure glaucoma.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Can cause pulmonary edema, especially in patients with heart failure, due to the initial expansion of extracellular fluid volume. Other effects include dehydration, hypernatremia, and hyponatremia.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Mannitol is the go-to drug for emergency reduction of intracranial pressure. Its main contraindication is anuria and heart failure, as the initial volume expansion can be dangerous.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Mannitol</b> acts as a potent osmotic agent, effectively dehydrating the brain by pulling water out of the parenchyma and across the blood-brain barrier, providing a rapid but temporary solution to life-threatening increases in intracranial pressure.</p>",
