    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Mean Arterial Pressure (MAP)</b> is the average arterial pressure during a single cardiac cycle, and it is the primary driving force for blood flow to the body's organs, including the brain. Cerebral perfusion is dependent on the gradient between MAP and intracranial pressure (ICP).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Formula:</b> Cerebral Perfusion Pressure (CPP) = MAP - ICP.</li><li><b>Autoregulation:</b> Cerebral blood flow is kept relatively constant over a wide range of MAP (approx. 60-140 mmHg) through the process of autoregulation, where cerebral arterioles constrict or dilate in response to changes in blood pressure.</li><li><b>Effect of Low MAP:</b> If MAP falls below the lower limit of autoregulation (~60 mmHg), cerebral blood flow becomes pressure-dependent and decreases, leading to ischemia.</li><li><b>Effect of High MAP:</b> If MAP rises above the upper limit of autoregulation (~140 mmHg), the autoregulatory system can be overwhelmed, leading to forced vasodilation, disruption of the blood-brain barrier, and vasogenic edema.</li><li><b>Cushing Reflex:</b> In the setting of severely elevated ICP, the body attempts to maintain CPP by drastically increasing MAP, leading to the triad of hypertension, bradycardia, and irregular respirations.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The brain maintains a stable blood flow despite fluctuations in systemic blood pressure through a robust autoregulatory mechanism; however, this system fails at the extremes of <b>mean arterial pressure</b>, making both severe hypotension and hypertension dangerous to cerebral perfusion.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
