    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Medial Lemniscus</b> is a major ascending sensory pathway in the brainstem that carries information about fine touch, vibration, and conscious proprioception from the contralateral side of the body to the thalamus.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Origin:</b> Formed by the axons of second-order neurons originating in the nucleus gracilis and nucleus cuneatus of the medulla.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> After originating in the medulla, these fibers <mark>decussate</mark> (cross the midline) as the internal arcuate fibers and then ascend through the brainstem as the medial lemniscus. It terminates in the ventral posterolateral (VPL) nucleus of the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]].</li><li><b>Function:</b> It is the brainstem component of the [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway]].</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> A lesion of the medial lemniscus in the brainstem (e.g., in [[4af9a67d|medial medullary syndrome]]) causes contralateral loss of vibration and proprioception.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the location of decussation. The dorsal column pathway decussates in the medulla to form the medial lemniscus. The spinothalamic pathway decussates in the spinal cord.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Medial Lemniscus</b> is the critical ascending tract that carries contralateral discriminative sensory information through the brainstem, representing the second-order neuron of the dorsal column pathway after its decussation in the medulla.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Nucleus Gracilis/Cuneatus] --Internal Arcuate Fibers (Decussation)--> B(Medial Lemniscus); B --Ascends through Brainstem--> C(VPL of Thalamus);"
    },
