  "59ad6172": {
    "title": "Medial Longitudinal Fasciculus (MLF)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Brainstem"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Medial Longitudinal Fasciculus (MLF)</b> is a pair of heavily myelinated nerve tracts in the brainstem that connects the cranial nerve nuclei responsible for eye movements (CN III, IV, and VI), allowing for the coordination of conjugate horizontal gaze.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> The primary role of the MLF is to coordinate horizontal eye movements by connecting the [[dd11dde6|abducens nucleus (CN VI)]] on one side with the contralateral [[68c66997|oculomotor nucleus (CN III)]].</li><li><b>Pathway for Gaze:</b> When looking to the right, the right abducens nucleus fires, causing the right lateral rectus to contract. Simultaneously, it sends a signal via the left MLF to the left oculomotor nucleus to contract the left medial rectus.</li><li><b>Lesion Effects:</b> A lesion in the MLF causes <mark>Internuclear Ophthalmoplegia (INO)</mark>.</li><li><b>Internuclear Ophthalmoplegia (INO):</b> Characterized by impaired adduction of the ipsilateral eye and nystagmus of the abducting contralateral eye. Convergence is typically preserved.</li><li><b>Etiology:</b> In a young patient, bilateral INO is highly suggestive of <mark>[[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]]</mark>, as the MLF is heavily myelinated and a common site for demyelinating plaques. In an older patient, a unilateral INO is often due to a brainstem stroke.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Bilateral INO in a young woman is pathognomonic for MS. Remember <b>INO</b> = <b>I</b>psilateral adduction failure, <b>N</b>ystagmus <b>O</b>pposite.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Medial Longitudinal Fasciculus</b> is the critical communication link that yokes the eyes together for horizontal movements; its disruption in INO uncouples the eyes, providing a precise localizing sign for a lesion in the dorsal brainstem.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
