  "4af9a67d": {
    "title": "Medial Medullary Syndrome",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Vascular",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brainstem Syndromes"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Medial Medullary Syndrome</b> (also known as Dejerine syndrome) is a brainstem stroke syndrome caused by an occlusion of the paramedian branches of the <i>anterior spinal artery</i> or the vertebral arteries, affecting the medial portion of the medulla.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Vascular Supply:</b> Caused by infarction in the territory of the <mark>anterior spinal artery (ASA)</mark>.</li><li><b>Affected Structures:</b> The lesion damages three key medial structures:<br>1. <b>Corticospinal Tract (Pyramid):</b> Causes <mark>contralateral hemiparesis</mark> (UMN signs).<br>2. <b>Medial Lemniscus:</b> Causes <mark>contralateral loss of proprioception and vibration</mark>.<br>3. <b>Hypoglossal Nucleus/Nerve (CN XII):</b> Causes <mark>ipsilateral tongue deviation</mark> (tongue deviates toward the lesion).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> A patient presents with contralateral weakness and loss of vibration/proprioception, with the tongue deviating toward the side of weakness when protruded.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of contralateral motor/sensory loss with ipsilateral tongue deviation is pathognomonic for a medial medullary lesion. The tongue 'licks the wound' (deviates toward the side of the lesion).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Medial Medullary Syndrome</b> is a classic crossed brainstem syndrome where damage to the pyramids and medial lemniscus causes contralateral deficits, while damage to the exiting hypoglossal nerve causes an ipsilateral deficit, precisely localizing the lesion to the medial medulla.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Anterior Spinal Artery Occlusion] --> B(Medial Medullary Infarct); B --> C(Corticospinal Tract Damage -> Contralateral Hemiparesis); B --> D(Medial Lemniscus Damage -> Contralateral Proprioception/Vibration Loss); B --> E(CN XII Damage -> Ipsilateral Tongue Deviation);"
    },
    "connections": [
