  "07f6ec2a": {
    "title": "Medulla Oblongata",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Brainstem"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Medulla Oblongata</b> is the most caudal part of the brainstem, connecting the pons to the spinal cord. It contains vital autonomic centers for respiration and cardiovascular function, as well as nuclei for several cranial nerves.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Embryology:</b> Arises from the [[c8030560|myelencephalon]].</li><li><b>Cranial Nerve Nuclei:</b> Contains nuclei for cranial nerves <b>IX (Glossopharyngeal)</b>, <b>X (Vagus)</b>, <b>XI (Accessory)</b>, and <b>XII (Hypoglossal)</b>.</li><li><b>Key Structures:</b><br> - <b>Pyramids:</b> Ventral bundles containing the corticospinal tracts, which decussate at the pyramidal decussation.<br> - <b>Medial Lemniscus:</b> Ascending tract for contralateral proprioception/vibration.<br> - <b>Inferior Olivary Nucleus:</b> Relays information to the cerebellum.<br> - <b>Nucleus Tractus Solitarius & Nucleus Ambiguus:</b> Key sensory and motor nuclei for CN IX and X.</li><li><b>Autonomic Centers:</b> Contains the respiratory, cardiac, and vasomotor centers.</li><li><b>Stroke Syndromes:</b> [[4af9a67d|Medial Medullary Syndrome]] (ASA occlusion) and Lateral Medullary (Wallenberg) Syndrome (PICA occlusion).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Medulla Oblongata</b> is the critical life-support center of the brainstem, housing the autonomic nuclei that control breathing and heart rate, and serving as the major conduit for motor and sensory tracts between the brain and spinal cord.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
