  "16d613bb": {
    "title": "Medulloblastoma",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Oncology",
      "Pediatrics",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brain Tumors"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>Medulloblastoma</b> is a highly malignant primary brain tumor that arises in the cerebellum and is the most common malignant brain tumor in childhood.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Exclusively occurs in the cerebellum. In children, it typically arises in the cerebellar <mark>vermis</mark> (midline).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> A midline location leads to <mark>truncal ataxia</mark> (unsteady gait). The tumor can compress the fourth ventricle, causing obstructive [[0bc2f200|hydrocephalus]] with symptoms of increased ICP (headache, vomiting, [[4ae219da|papilledema]]).</li><li><b>Metastasis:</b> These tumors are known to spread through the cerebrospinal fluid, causing <mark>\"drop metastases\"</mark> to the spinal cord, which can present as back pain or radiculopathy.</li><li><b>Histology:</b> A type of primitive neuroectodermal tumor (PNET), it is composed of small, round, blue cells. A characteristic finding is the formation of <mark>Homer-Wright rosettes</mark>, where tumor cells arrange themselves in a circle around a central space filled with neuropil. It is synaptophysin-positive.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A child with truncal ataxia and signs of hydrocephalus should make you think of a medulloblastoma. The presence of Homer-Wright rosettes on histology is pathognomonic.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Medulloblastoma</b> is an aggressive pediatric cerebellar tumor whose midline location leads to truncal ataxia and obstructive hydrocephalus, and its propensity to seed the CSF can lead to 'drop metastases' along the spinal cord.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
