    "title": "Meissner's Corpuscles",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Dermatology",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Sensory System"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Meissner's corpuscles</b> are encapsulated sensory receptors located in the dermal papillae of the skin that are specialized to detect light, discriminative touch and low-frequency vibration.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Structure:</b> Small, encapsulated nerve endings located in the dermal papillae, just beneath the epidermis.</li><li><b>Function:</b> They are <mark>rapidly adapting</mark> mechanoreceptors, meaning they respond to changes in stimuli (e.g., initial contact with an object, movement of textures across the skin) rather than sustained pressure. This makes them crucial for discriminative touch, such as reading Braille or detecting slip.</li><li><b>Location:</b> Abundant in glabrous (hairless) skin, such as the fingertips, palms, soles, and lips.</li><li><b>Nerve Fibers:</b> Transmitted by large, myelinated AŒ≤ fibers.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Signals travel via the [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Associate rapidly adapting receptors with dynamic qualities. Meissner's corpuscles = light touch/texture changes. Pacinian corpuscles = high-frequency vibration.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Meissner's corpuscles</b> are the skin's fine-tuned motion detectors, rapidly adapting to provide the brain with detailed information about the texture and movement of objects across the skin, essential for tasks requiring fine tactile discrimination.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
