      "definition": "<p><b>Liquefactive necrosis</b> is a type of necrosis in which the dead tissue is transformed into a liquid, viscous mass. It is characteristic of focal bacterial or fungal infections and hypoxic death of cells within the central nervous system.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Occurs in tissues with high lipid content and few connective tissue fibers, or in the context of infections with pyogenic bacteria. Enzymatic digestion of the dead cells by hydrolytic enzymes from neutrophils (in abscesses) or by the cells' own lysosomes (in CNS ischemia) predominates over protein denaturation.</li><li><b>Central Nervous System:</b> This is the characteristic type of necrosis seen in the brain following an <mark>ischemic stroke</mark>. Microglial cells (the CNS macrophages) release hydrolytic enzymes that digest the necrotic tissue, eventually forming a fluid-filled cystic space.</li><li><b>Bacterial Infections:</b> Also characteristic of abscess formation, where neutrophils release enzymes that liquefy the tissue, forming pus.</li><li><b>Gross Appearance:</b> The affected area becomes soft, liquid, and creamy yellow (due to dead leukocytes in pus) or a fluid-filled cavity.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> For the brain, the answer to 'what type of necrosis occurs after an ischemic event?' is <u>always</u> liquefactive necrosis. For most other organs (e.g., heart, kidney), the answer is coagulative necrosis.</li></ul>",
