      "definition": "<p><b>Lorazepam</b> is an intermediate-acting <i>benzodiazepine</i> with potent anxiolytic, sedative, and anticonvulsant properties, commonly used for anxiety, insomnia, and status epilepticus.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Facilitates the action of [[5aa5cb91|GABA]] at the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor, increasing the <mark>frequency</mark> of Cl<sup>-</sup> channel opening and causing CNS depression.</li><li><b>Metabolism:</b> Undergoes direct glucuronidation in the liver, making its metabolism less dependent on the cytochrome P450 system.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> First-line treatment for <mark>status epilepticus</mark>. Also used for anxiety disorders, sedation in the ICU, and management of alcohol withdrawal.</li><li><b>Safe in Liver Disease:</b> Along with Oxazepam and Temazepam, Lorazepam is a preferred benzodiazepine in patients with severe liver disease. Mnemonic: <b>O</b>utside <b>T</b>he <b>L</b>iver (<b>O</b>xazepam, <b>T</b>emazepam, <b>L</b>orazepam).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Lorazepam is the IV benzodiazepine of choice for terminating an active seizure in status epilepticus due to its rapid onset and relatively long duration of action in the CNS.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Lorazepam</b> is a versatile benzodiazepine that is a first-line agent for the emergency treatment of status epilepticus and is also a safer choice in patients with liver failure due to its direct glucuronidation metabolism.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
