    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>Lower Motor Neuron (LMN)</b> is a motor neuron whose cell body is located in the anterior horn of the spinal cord or in a brainstem cranial nerve nucleus, and whose axon directly innervates skeletal muscle fibers.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Serves as the final common pathway for all motor output from the CNS to the muscles.</li><li><b>LMN Lesion Signs:</b> Damage to LMNs results in a characteristic set of signs in the affected muscles. Mnemonic: Everything is <b>L</b>owered. <br> - <mark>Flaccid paralysis</mark> or weakness (paresis).<br> - Significant <mark>muscle atrophy</mark>.<br> - <mark>Fasciculations</mark> (involuntary muscle twitches).<br> - <mark>Hyporeflexia</mark> or areflexia (decreased or absent deep tendon reflexes).<br> - Decreased muscle tone (hypotonia).</li><li><b>Causes of LMN Lesions:</b> [[75f2b918|Poliomyelitis]], [[e6820b7f|spinal muscular atrophy]], [[4ed629f9|amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS)]], trauma to peripheral nerves, and [[ed52e40b|Guillain-Barr√© syndrome]].</li><li><b>Facial Nerve Lesion:</b> An LMN lesion of CN VII (e.g., Bell's palsy) causes ipsilateral paralysis of the <u>entire</u> half of the face, including the forehead.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The presence of fasciculations and significant atrophy are strong indicators of an LMN lesion.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>Lower Motor Neuron</b> is the direct and final link between the central nervous system and a muscle fiber; its destruction severs this link, leading to a complete loss of voluntary and reflex activity in the muscle, resulting in flaccid paralysis and profound atrophy.</p>",
