    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>lumbar puncture (LP)</b>, or spinal tap, is a diagnostic and sometimes therapeutic procedure used to collect a sample of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) for analysis by inserting a needle into the subarachnoid space of the lumbar spine.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Indications:</b> Primarily used to diagnose infections of the CNS (e.g., meningitis, encephalitis), [[63f8b05f|subarachnoid hemorrhage]], inflammatory conditions (e.g., [[45dd6d19|MS]]), and to measure intracranial pressure.</li><li><b>Anatomical Landmark:</b> The needle is inserted between the L3/L4 or L4/L5 vertebral interspaces to avoid injuring the spinal cord, which typically ends at the L1/L2 level in adults. A line drawn between the iliac crests approximates the L4 vertebral body.</li><li><b>Layers Pierced:</b> Skin ‚Üí Supraspinous ligament ‚Üí Interspinous ligament ‚Üí Ligamentum flavum ‚Üí Epidural space ‚Üí Dura mater ‚Üí Arachnoid mater ‚Üí Subarachnoid space. The pia mater is <u>not</u> pierced.</li><li><b>Opening Pressure:</b> Measurement of CSF pressure at the start of the procedure. It is elevated in conditions like bacterial/fungal meningitis and [[7c59030e|normal pressure hydrocephalus]] (intermittently).</li><li><b>Contraindications:</b> A major contraindication is evidence of significantly increased ICP with mass effect (e.g., brain tumor, large abscess) due to the risk of cerebral herniation. A head CT is often performed prior to LP if there are focal neurological signs or papilledema.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>lumbar puncture</b> is a fundamental neurological procedure that provides direct access to the cerebrospinal fluid, offering invaluable diagnostic information about infectious, inflammatory, and hemorrhagic conditions affecting the central nervous system.</p>",
