    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Age-related macular degeneration (AMD)</b> is a progressive neurodegenerative disease of the macula, the central part of the retina, leading to the loss of central, high-acuity vision. It is a leading cause of irreversible blindness in older adults.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Dry (Atrophic) AMD:</b> Most common form (~80%). Characterized by the slow, progressive atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) and photoreceptors. The hallmark finding is the presence of <mark>drusen</mark>, which are yellow extracellular deposits between Bruch's membrane and the RPE.</li><li><b>Wet (Exudative) AMD:</b> Less common but more severe. Characterized by the growth of abnormal new blood vessels from the choroid (choroidal neovascularization) that break through Bruch's membrane. These vessels leak fluid and blood, causing rapid and severe central vision loss.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients experience gradual (dry) or rapid (wet) loss of central vision (central scotoma). A key symptom of wet AMD is <mark>metamorphopsia</mark> (straight lines appear wavy).</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Dry AMD is managed with antioxidant vitamins and zinc (AREDS formula) to slow progression. Wet AMD is treated with intravitreal injections of <mark>anti-VEGF</mark> agents (e.g., ranibizumab, bevacizumab) to inhibit neovascularization.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate the two types: Dry AMD = Drusen and gradual vision loss. Wet AMD = Neovascularization, hemorrhage, and rapid vision loss.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Age-related macular degeneration</b> is a disease of the central retina where the 'dry' form involves the slow accumulation of metabolic debris (drusen), while the 'wet' form involves an aggressive, sight-threatening invasion of leaky new blood vessels, which can be targeted with anti-VEGF therapy.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
