    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>Antenatal administration of <b>magnesium sulfate</b> to mothers at high risk for preterm delivery before 32 weeks' gestation is a neuroprotective strategy shown to reduce the risk and severity of <i>cerebral palsy</i> in surviving infants.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Indication:</b> Administered to pregnant women at risk of imminent preterm birth, typically between 24 and 32 weeks of gestation.</li><li><b>Mechanism of Neuroprotection:</b> The exact mechanism is not fully understood but is thought to involve several pathways: <br> - Reduction of inflammatory cytokines.<br> - Blockade of NMDA receptors, reducing excitotoxic injury.<br> - Increased cerebral blood flow and antioxidant effects.</li><li><b>Primary Outcome:</b> Reduces the risk of moderate to severe [[171ca00b|cerebral palsy]] in the offspring. It does not prevent preterm birth itself.</li><li><b>Other Obstetric Uses:</b> Magnesium sulfate is also the first-line treatment for seizure prophylaxis in preeclampsia and eclampsia, and as a tocolytic to temporarily suppress preterm labor.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the dual neuroprotective roles of magnesium sulfate in obstetrics: preventing seizures in the mother (preeclampsia) and reducing the risk of cerebral palsy in the preterm infant.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Magnesium sulfate</b> serves as a powerful neuroprotectant for the vulnerable preterm brain; when given to the mother before an early delivery, it stabilizes the fetal brain's vasculature and neuronal environment, significantly lowering the odds of the child developing cerebral palsy.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
