    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Magnetic gait</b> is a type of gait apraxia characterized by the appearance of the feet being 'stuck to the floor.' It is one of the cardinal features of <i>Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus (NPH)</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Description:</b> Patients have difficulty initiating walking despite having normal motor strength. They take slow, short, shuffling steps with a wide base. The feet appear to be 'glued' or 'magnetized' to the floor.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Believed to be caused by the stretching of the corona radiata fibers (specifically the sacral motor fibers that innervate the legs) by the enlarged lateral ventricles in [[7c59030e|Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus]].</li><li><b>Associated Condition:</b> It is the 'wobbly' component of the classic NPH triad: \"<b>W</b>et, <b>W</b>obbly, and <b>W</b>acky\" (urinary incontinence, gait apraxia, and cognitive dysfunction).</li><li><b>Distinction from Parkinsonian Gait:</b> While both are shuffling, the magnetic gait of NPH is typically wide-based, and patients have difficulty lifting their feet. Parkinsonian gait is often narrow-based with festination (involuntary acceleration).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A wide-based, shuffling gait where the patient's feet seem stuck to the floor, in the context of dementia and incontinence, is highly specific for NPH.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Magnetic gait</b> is a form of frontal gait apraxia that visually represents the difficulty in initiating movement seen in NPH; it is not a problem of strength or coordination but a failure of the cortical motor programming for walking, caused by ventricular enlargement.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
