      "definition": "<p>The <b>Lateral Rectus Muscle</b> is one of the six extraocular muscles responsible for eye movement. Its sole function is to <u>abduct</u> the eye, moving it laterally away from the nose.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Action:</b> Abduction (lateral movement) of the eyeball.</li><li><b>Innervation:</b> It is exclusively innervated by the <mark>abducens nerve (CN VI)</mark>.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> Paralysis of the lateral rectus muscle due to a [[dd11dde6|CN VI palsy]] results in an inability to abduct the eye. This leads to an unopposed pull by the medial rectus, causing an esotropia (inward deviation of the eye) and horizontal [[9914d433|diplopia]].</li><li><b>Mnemonic:</b> Remember the innervation of the extraocular muscles with the formula <b>LR<sub>6</sub>SO<sub>4</sub>R<sub>3</sub></b> (<b>L</b>ateral <b>R</b>ectus by CN <b>6</b>, <b>S</b>uperior <b>O</b>blique by CN <b>4</b>, <b>R</b>est by CN <b>3</b>).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> An isolated inability to abduct the eye points directly to a lesion of either the lateral rectus muscle itself or, more commonly, the abducens nerve (CN VI).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Lateral Rectus muscle</b> has a singular, straightforward function‚Äîeye abduction‚Äîand a dedicated nerve supply from CN VI, making its paralysis a highly specific localizing sign for abducens nerve pathology.</p>",
