    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Lateral Ventricles</b> are the two largest, C-shaped cavities of the ventricular system of the brain, located within the cerebral hemispheres. They contain cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), which is produced by their choroid plexuses.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> One in each cerebral hemisphere. Each lateral ventricle has an anterior (frontal) horn, a body (parietal), a posterior (occipital) horn, and an inferior (temporal) horn.</li><li><b>CSF Flow:</b> CSF flows from each lateral ventricle into the third ventricle via the paired <mark>interventricular foramina of Monro</mark>.</li><li><b>Embryology:</b> The cavities of the lateral ventricles are derived from the lumen of the embryonic telencephalon.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Enlargement of the lateral ventricles is a key sign of [[0bc2f200|hydrocephalus]]. In <mark>obstructive hydrocephalus</mark>, blockage of the foramen of Monro or the cerebral aqueduct will cause dilation of the lateral ventricles. In [[7c59030e|normal pressure hydrocephalus]], all ventricles are enlarged.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Symmetrical enlargement of the lateral ventricles on a CT or MRI is a classic finding in hydrocephalus.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Lateral Ventricles</b> are the primary sites of CSF production and form the starting point of the CSF circulatory pathway; their enlargement is a sensitive indicator of pathologies that either obstruct CSF flow or impair its absorption.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Lateral Ventricles] --Foramen of Monro--> B(Third Ventricle); B --Cerebral Aqueduct--> C(Fourth Ventricle);"
    },
