  "b1466841": {
    "title": "Left-Right Disorientation",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Cognitive Deficit",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brain Lesions"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Left-right disorientation</b> is a neurological deficit characterized by the inability to distinguish between the left and right sides of one's own body or in extrapersonal space. It is a component of <i>Gerstmann syndrome</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Localization:</b> This deficit is a specific sign of a lesion in the <mark>dominant (usually left) parietal lobe</mark>, specifically the angular gyrus.</li><li><b>Associated Syndrome:</b> It is one of the four classic components of [[38f3ed1f|Gerstmann syndrome]].</li><li><b>Gerstmann Syndrome Tetrad:</b> The full syndrome includes <b>Left-Right Disorientation</b>, <b>Agraphia</b> (inability to write), <b>[[8558c64b|Acalculia]]</b> (inability to perform calculations), and <b>Finger Agnosia</b> (inability to distinguish fingers).</li><li><b>Vascular Territory:</b> These symptoms often result from a stroke in the territory of the [[143bb23d|Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)]] that supplies the dominant parietal lobe.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of left-right confusion with difficulty in writing, calculating, or identifying fingers is pathognomonic for Gerstmann syndrome and points to a lesion in the dominant angular gyrus.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Left-right disorientation</b> is a highly specific cognitive deficit that, when present, strongly localizes a lesion to the dominant parietal lobe, often as part of the unique constellation of symptoms known as Gerstmann syndrome.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
