  "516b9ff4": {
    "title": "Lens Dislocation (Ectopia Lentis)",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Genetics",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Pathology"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Lens dislocation</b>, or <b>ectopia lentis</b>, is the displacement of the crystalline lens of the eye from its normal position. While most commonly caused by trauma, it can be a hallmark of several systemic genetic disorders.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Caused by weakness or disruption of the zonular fibers that hold the lens in place.</li><li><b>Marfan Syndrome:</b> An autosomal dominant connective tissue disorder caused by a mutation in the fibrillin-1 (<i>FBN1</i>) gene. Characterized by a classic <mark>upward and outward (superotemporal)</mark> dislocation of the lens.</li><li><b>Homocystinuria:</b> An autosomal recessive disorder of methionine metabolism. Characterized by a <mark>downward and inward (inferonasal)</mark> dislocation of the lens.</li><li><b>Other Associations:</b> Can also be seen in Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, sulfite oxidase deficiency, and Weil-Marchesani syndrome.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Can cause blurred vision, diplopia, and may lead to glaucoma or retinal detachment.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The direction of lens dislocation is a key feature for differentiating Marfan syndrome from homocystinuria on exams. Mnemonic: Mar<b>fan</b>'s fans the lens <b>up</b>.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Ectopia lentis</b> is a significant physical finding that should prompt consideration of an underlying systemic connective tissue or metabolic disorder, with the direction of dislocation providing a crucial clue to distinguish between Marfan syndrome and homocystinuria.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
