  "dcd6b576": {
    "title": "Lenticulostriate Artery Stroke",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Vascular",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Cerebrovascular Disease"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>lenticulostriate artery stroke</b> is a type of <i>lacunar stroke</i> caused by the occlusion of one of the small, deep penetrating arteries that branch from the [[143bb23d|Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)]]. These strokes result in small infarcts in the deep brain structures.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Vascular Anatomy:</b> The lenticulostriate arteries arise from the M1 segment of the MCA and supply deep structures such as the basal ganglia (putamen, globus pallidus, caudate), and the posterior limb of the internal capsule.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Occlusion is typically due to <mark>lipohyalinosis</mark> or microatheroma, processes strongly associated with chronic [[hypertension]].</li><li><b>Clinical Syndromes:</b> Because these arteries supply densely packed white matter tracts and deep nuclei, small infarcts can cause significant deficits. The most common syndrome is a <mark>pure motor stroke</mark>.</li><li><b>Pure Motor Stroke:</b> Caused by an infarct in the contralateral posterior limb of the internal capsule. Presents with unilateral weakness of the face, arm, and leg without any sensory, visual, or cognitive deficits.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient with a history of hypertension presenting with a pure motor hemiparesis (face, arm, and leg equally affected) has a lacunar stroke in the lenticulostriate artery territory until proven otherwise.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Strokes involving the <b>lenticulostriate arteries</b> are the archetypal lacunar infarcts, where chronic hypertension damages these tiny end-arteries, leading to small, deep brain infarcts that produce 'pure' motor or sensory syndromes by selectively damaging critical white matter tracts.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
