  "eec6247a": {
    "title": "Lentiform Nucleus",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Basal Ganglia"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Lentiform Nucleus</b> is a large, lens-shaped mass of gray matter located in the deep cerebral hemispheres. It is a major component of the [[ed462927|basal ganglia]] and is composed of two parts: the putamen and the globus pallidus.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Components:</b><br> - <b>Putamen:</b> The larger, more lateral part.<br> - <b>Globus Pallidus:</b> The smaller, more medial part, which is further subdivided into an external (GPe) and internal (GPi) segment.</li><li><b>Anatomical Relations:</b> The lentiform nucleus is separated from the caudate nucleus and thalamus by the internal capsule.</li><li><b>Function:</b> As part of the basal ganglia, it is involved in the regulation of voluntary movement. The putamen is a major input nucleus of the basal ganglia (along with the caudate), while the globus pallidus internus is a major output nucleus.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> Lesions of the lentiform nucleus can cause various movement disorders. It is a common site for hypertensive intraparenchymal hemorrhages due to its supply by the vulnerable lenticulostriate arteries.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the anatomical groupings: Striatum = Caudate + Putamen. Lentiform Nucleus = Putamen + Globus Pallidus.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Lentiform Nucleus</b>, comprising the putamen and globus pallidus, forms the core of the basal ganglia's motor circuit, playing a pivotal role in processing cortical signals to modulate and refine voluntary movements.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
