  "c8515469": {
    "title": "Leptin",
    "primaryType": "molecule",
    "tags": [
      "Endocrinology",
      "Physiology",
      "Biochemistry",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Endocrine",
      "Physiology",
      "Hormones"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Leptin</b> is a peptide hormone produced primarily by adipose tissue that acts on the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]] to regulate appetite and energy balance. It functions as a long-term satiety signal, informing the brain about the body's fat stores.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Source:</b> Secreted by adipocytes (fat cells) in proportion to the amount of stored fat.</li><li><b>Target:</b> Acts on receptors in the arcuate nucleus of the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]].</li><li><b>Function:</b> Suppresses appetite and increases energy expenditure. It inhibits orexigenic (appetite-stimulating) neurons and stimulates anorexigenic (appetite-suppressing) neurons.</li><li><b>Leptin Resistance:</b> In obesity, plasma leptin levels are high, but the brain becomes resistant to its anorexigenic effects, contributing to the maintenance of a high body weight.</li><li><b>Congenital Leptin Deficiency:</b> A rare genetic disorder causing severe early-onset obesity and hyperphagia. These individuals can be treated effectively with leptin injections.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Think of leptin as the 'satiety hormone' from fat. High fat stores -> high leptin -> decreased appetite. In obesity, this feedback loop is broken due to leptin resistance.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Leptin</b> is the hormonal messenger from fat tissue to the brain, signaling energy sufficiency and suppressing hunger; however, in the common state of obesity, the brain becomes deaf to this signal, leading to a state of perceived starvation despite excess energy stores.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Adipose Tissue] --Secretes--> B(Leptin); B --> C(Hypothalamus); C --> D(Decreased Appetite); C --> E(Increased Energy Expenditure);"
    },
    "connections": [
