    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Levetiracetam</b> is a newer-generation, broad-spectrum <i>anticonvulsant</i> medication with a unique mechanism of action, widely used for the treatment of both focal and generalized seizures.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> The exact mechanism is not fully understood, but it is known to bind to the <mark>synaptic vesicle protein 2A (SV2A)</mark>. This is thought to modulate neurotransmitter release, although how this prevents seizures is unclear.</li><li><b>Spectrum of Activity:</b> It is a <mark>broad-spectrum</mark> agent, effective against focal seizures, generalized tonic-clonic seizures, and myoclonic seizures.</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Has favorable pharmacokinetics with minimal hepatic metabolism (not dependent on CYP450) and few drug-drug interactions.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Generally well-tolerated. The most common side effects are somnolence, dizziness, and fatigue. A significant potential side effect is <mark>neuropsychiatric symptoms</mark>, including irritability, agitation, depression, and psychosis.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Levetiracetam's unique SV2A mechanism and its broad spectrum of activity with a favorable side effect profile make it a popular choice. Be aware of the potential for behavioral and psychiatric side effects.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Levetiracetam</b> is a widely used anticonvulsant due to its broad efficacy and favorable safety profile, which works through a novel mechanism of binding to the synaptic vesicle protein SV2A to modulate neurotransmitter release.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
