  "db2f16e5": {
    "title": "Lewy Body Dementia (LBD)",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Geriatrics",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Neurodegenerative Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Lewy Body Dementia (LBD)</b> is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder characterized by the presence of Lewy bodies (abnormal aggregates of alpha-synuclein) in the cerebral cortex, leading to a clinical syndrome of dementia, parkinsonism, and visual hallucinations.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathology:</b> An Œ±-synucleinopathy, characterized by the formation of intracellular <mark>Lewy bodies</mark> in cortical and subcortical neurons.</li><li><b>Core Clinical Features:</b><br>1. <b>Dementia:</b> Cognitive decline, particularly in executive function and visuospatial ability.<br>2. <b>Fluctuating Cognition:</b> Pronounced variations in attention and alertness.<br>3. <b>Visual Hallucinations:</b> Well-formed, recurrent visual hallucinations are a hallmark feature.<br>4. <b>Parkinsonism:</b> Spontaneous motor features of parkinsonism (bradykinesia, rigidity, tremor).</li><li><b>Supportive Feature:</b> <mark>REM sleep behavior disorder (RBD)</mark>, where patients physically act out their dreams, is very common and often precedes other symptoms.</li><li><b>Distinction from Parkinson's Disease:</b> The timing of symptoms is key. In LBD, dementia develops <mark>before or concurrently with (within 1 year of)</mark> the onset of parkinsonism. If dementia develops >1 year after the onset of well-established Parkinson's, it is termed Parkinson disease dementia.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient with dementia, vivid visual hallucinations, and parkinsonian features has Lewy Body Dementia. Remember the 'one-year rule' to distinguish it from Parkinson disease dementia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Lewy Body Dementia</b> is a disease at the crossroads of Alzheimer's and Parkinson's, sharing cognitive decline with the former and motor symptoms with the latter, but distinguished by its unique core features of fluctuating cognition and vivid visual hallucinations, all driven by the cortical accumulation of Œ±-synuclein.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
