  "7a52c5ee": {
    "title": "Light-Near Dissociation",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Physical Findings"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Light-near dissociation</b> is a clinical sign where the pupillary constriction response to a near stimulus (the [[81b5f5fe|accommodation]] reflex) is intact, but the pupillary light reflex is absent or greatly reduced.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Classic Association:</b> The most famous cause is the <mark>Argyll Robertson pupil</mark>, which is pathognomonic for tertiary (neuro)syphilis. The pupils are typically small, bilateral, and irregular. Mnemonic: \"Prostitute's pupil\" - accommodates but does not react.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology (Argyll Robertson):</b> The lesion is thought to be in the pretectal area of the dorsal midbrain, which interrupts the afferent fibers for the light reflex before they reach the Edinger-Westphal nucleus, while sparing the more ventral pathways for accommodation.</li><li><b>Parinaud Syndrome:</b> Also known as dorsal midbrain syndrome, it is another cause of light-near dissociation (pseudo-Argyll Robertson pupils). It is caused by compression of the dorsal midbrain, often by a pineal gland tumor.</li><li><b>Adie's Tonic Pupil:</b> A benign condition caused by damage to the ciliary ganglion, resulting in a dilated pupil with minimal reaction to light but a slow, tonic constriction to a near stimulus.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> If you see 'pupils accommodate but do not react,' your first thought should be neurosyphilis (Argyll Robertson pupil).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Light-near dissociation</b> is a specific form of pupillary dysfunction that points to a lesion in the dorsal midbrain, disrupting the pupillary light reflex pathway while sparing the separate, more complex pathway for the accommodation reflex.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
