    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Lightheadedness</b> is a common, non-specific symptom described as a feeling of being about to faint or lose consciousness (presyncope). It is distinct from vertigo, which is a sensation of spinning.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Typically caused by a transient decrease in cerebral perfusion (blood flow to the brain).</li><li><b>Cardiovascular Causes:</b> The most common causes are cardiovascular. These include orthostatic hypotension, arrhythmias (bradycardia or tachycardia), vasovagal syncope, and structural heart disease (e.g., aortic stenosis, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy).</li><li><b>Neurological Causes:</b> While less common, neurological causes can include vertebrobasilar insufficiency or autonomic dysfunction.</li><li><b>Distinction from Vertigo:</b> It is crucial to differentiate lightheadedness from [[5603962d|vertigo]]. Lightheadedness is a feeling of faintness, while vertigo is a sensation of movement or spinning. Asking the patient \"Do you feel like you are going to pass out, or is the room spinning?\" is a key diagnostic question.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> When a patient complains of 'dizziness,' the first step is to clarify what they mean. If they describe a feeling of faintness, think about causes of decreased cerebral perfusion, starting with cardiovascular etiologies.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Lightheadedness</b> is a symptom of impending syncope, signaling a temporary reduction in blood flow to the brain. Its evaluation should primarily focus on cardiovascular causes, as it is fundamentally a perfusion problem, not a vestibular one like vertigo.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
