    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Limb ataxia</b> is a form of ataxia characterized by a lack of voluntary coordination of muscle movements in the extremities, resulting from dysfunction of the <i>cerebellar hemispheres</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Caused by a lesion in the lateral parts of the [[bebe58d4|cerebellum]] (the cerebellar hemispheres), which are responsible for motor planning and coordination of the distal limbs.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Manifests as clumsy, uncoordinated movements of the arms and legs. It is typically <mark>ipsilateral</mark> to the side of the cerebellar lesion.</li><li><b>Physical Exam Findings:</b><br> - <b>Dysmetria:</b> Inability to judge distance or range of movement (e.g., overshooting or undershooting a target in the finger-to-nose test).<br> - <b>Dysdiadochokinesia:</b> Inability to perform rapid, alternating movements.<br> - <b>Intention Tremor:</b> A tremor that worsens as the limb approaches its target.</li><li><b>Distinction from Truncal Ataxia:</b> Truncal ataxia (unsteady gait, difficulty sitting or standing unsupported) is caused by a lesion of the cerebellar vermis (midline cerebellum).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the lateral-to-medial organization of the cerebellum. Lateral lesions (hemispheres) cause limb ataxia. Medial lesions (vermis) cause truncal ataxia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Limb ataxia</b> is a direct consequence of a lesion in the ipsilateral cerebellar hemisphere, leading to a breakdown in the smooth, coordinated execution of limb movements and resulting in the classic findings of dysmetria, dysdiadochokinesia, and intention tremor.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
