      "Sensory System"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Joint position sense</b>, or <b>proprioception</b>, is the sense of the relative position of one's own parts of the body and strength of effort being employed in movement. It is a key component of somatosensation, transmitted via the dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Sensory Receptors:</b> Mediated by mechanoreceptors in muscles (muscle spindles), tendons (Golgi tendon organs), and <mark>joints</mark> (Ruffini corpuscles, Pacinian corpuscles).</li><li><b>Nerve Fibers:</b> Transmitted by large, heavily myelinated, and fast-conducting AŒ± and AŒ≤ fibers.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Signals travel up the ipsilateral [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal columns]] to the medulla, synapse, decussate, and ascend via the [[f19bc454|medial lemniscus]] to the VPL nucleus of the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]], and finally to the somatosensory cortex.</li><li><b>Clinical Testing:</b> Assessed by moving a patient's joint (e.g., the great toe) up or down with their eyes closed and asking them to identify the direction of movement. The [[47a0f3d1|Romberg test]] also assesses proprioception.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Loss of proprioception and vibration sense is a hallmark of [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal column]] pathology, seen in conditions like [[71daebd6|tabes dorsalis]] and [[6f5bea90|subacute combined degeneration]] (vitamin B12 deficiency).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Proprioception</b> is the body's 'sixth sense,' providing the brain with a constant, unconscious awareness of limb position and movement, which is essential for coordinated motor control and balance. Its reliance on large, myelinated fibers makes it vulnerable in specific neurological disorders.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
