    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Kl√ºver-Bucy syndrome</b> is a rare behavioral syndrome resulting from bilateral damage to the medial temporal lobes, particularly the <i>amygdala</i>. It is characterized by a constellation of symptoms including hyperorality, hypersexuality, and placidity.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Caused by lesions that destroy the [[d220fc3f|amygdala]] bilaterally. The most common cause is <mark>Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV-1) encephalitis</mark>, which has a predilection for the temporal lobes. Other causes include trauma, stroke, and Pick disease.</li><li><b>Clinical Features:</b><br> - <b>Hyperphagia:</b> Excessive eating and weight gain.<br> - <b>Hypersexuality:</b> Inappropriate and indiscriminate sexual behavior.<br> - <b>Hypermetamorphosis:</b> Compulsive desire to explore every object in sight.<br> - <b>Hyperorality:</b> Tendency to examine objects by mouth.<br> - <b>Placidity:</b> Diminished fear response, appearing tame or emotionally blunted.<br> - <b>Visual Agnosia:</b> Inability to recognize familiar objects or faces.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient who survives HSV encephalitis and subsequently develops bizarre behaviors like putting inedible objects in their mouth, inappropriate sexual advances, and a flattened emotional response is the classic presentation of Kl√ºver-Bucy syndrome.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Kl√ºver-Bucy syndrome</b> is a dramatic demonstration of the amygdala's role in processing emotion and driving behavior; its bilateral destruction unmasks primitive oral and sexual tendencies and extinguishes the normal fear response.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
