    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Krabbe disease</b>, also known as globoid cell leukodystrophy, is a rare, fatal, autosomal recessive <i>lysosomal storage disease</i> caused by a deficiency of the enzyme galactocerebrosidase, leading to the accumulation of galactocerebroside and psychosine, which destroys myelin-producing cells.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Genetics:</b> Autosomal recessive inheritance.</li><li><b>Enzyme Deficiency:</b> Deficiency of <mark>galactocerebrosidase</mark>.</li><li><b>Accumulated Substrate:</b> Galactocerebroside and, more importantly, the cytotoxic metabolite <mark>psychosine (galactosylsphingosine)</mark>.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Psychosine accumulation is toxic to [[a24f9747|oligodendrocytes]] (in the CNS) and [[c65a8909|Schwann cells]] (in the PNS), leading to widespread and severe demyelination.</li><li><b>Histology:</b> The pathognomonic finding is the presence of <mark>globoid cells</mark>‚Äîlarge, multinucleated macrophages filled with undigested galactocerebroside‚Äîclustered around blood vessels in the white matter.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> The classic form is infantile-onset, presenting at 3-6 months with extreme irritability, developmental delay/regression, spasticity, and peripheral neuropathy. It is rapidly progressive and fatal within about two years.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> For lysosomal storage diseases, link the disease, enzyme, and substrate. Krabbe = Galactocerebrosidase deficiency = Psychosine accumulation. The key histological finding is the globoid cell.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Krabbe disease</b> is a devastating leukodystrophy where the deficiency of galactocerebrosidase leads to the buildup of the highly toxic lipid psychosine, which selectively kills off the body's myelin-producing cells, resulting in rapid and global demyelination.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Galactocerebroside] --Galactocerebrosidase--> B(Degradation); C[Enzyme Deficiency] --x B; A --> D(Accumulation of Psychosine); D --> E(Destruction of Oligodendrocytes & Schwann Cells); E --> F(Globoid Cells & Demyelination);"
