    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Kyphoscoliosis</b> is a spinal deformity characterized by an abnormal curvature of the spine in both the coronal (scoliosis) and sagittal (kyphosis) planes, resulting in a 'hunchback' and lateral curve.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Description:</b> A combination of kyphosis (anteroposterior rounding of the back) and scoliosis (lateral curvature of the spine).</li><li><b>Neuromuscular Causes:</b> It is a common feature of several neuromuscular diseases due to muscle weakness and imbalance affecting the paraspinal muscles.</li><li><b>Friedreich Ataxia:</b> Kyphoscoliosis is a classic skeletal deformity seen in [[39bc1763|Friedreich Ataxia]], along with pes cavus and hammer toes.</li><li><b>Cerebral Palsy:</b> Common in children with [[171ca00b|cerebral palsy]], particularly those with spastic quadriplegia.</li><li><b>Complications:</b> Severe kyphoscoliosis can restrict lung expansion, leading to a <mark>restrictive lung disease</mark> pattern on pulmonary function tests and eventual respiratory failure.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The presence of kyphoscoliosis in a patient with neurological symptoms should prompt consideration of underlying neuromuscular disorders like [[39bc1763|Friedreich Ataxia]] or muscular dystrophies.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Kyphoscoliosis</b> in the context of a neurological disorder is a physical manifestation of chronic muscle imbalance acting on the growing spine, and its progression can lead to severe, life-threatening restrictive lung disease.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
