  "b56349b2": {
    "title": "Lacunar Infarcts",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Vascular",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Cerebrovascular Disease"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Lacunar infarcts</b> are small (&lt;1.5 cm) ischemic strokes that occur in the deep, subcortical areas of the brain, resulting from the occlusion of a single, small penetrating artery. They are strongly associated with chronic hypertension.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Chronic hypertension leads to <mark>lipohyalinosis</mark> and microatheroma of small penetrating arteries (e.g., lenticulostriate, thalamoperforate arteries), making them prone to occlusion.</li><li><b>Location:</b> Commonly occur in the basal ganglia (especially the putamen), internal capsule, thalamus, and pons.</li><li><b>Clinical Syndromes:</b> Because they affect small, functionally specific areas, they produce classic 'lacunar syndromes' that lack cortical signs (e.g., aphasia, neglect, visual field cuts).<br> - <b>[[8aefcafe|Pure Motor Stroke]]:</b> Most common. Lesion in the posterior limb of the internal capsule. Contralateral hemiparesis.<br> - <b>Pure Sensory Stroke:</b> Lesion in the thalamus (VPL/VPM). Contralateral hemisensory loss.</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> May be too small to be seen on initial non-contrast CT. MRI (especially diffusion-weighted imaging) is more sensitive.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The absence of cortical signs is the key to identifying a lacunar stroke. A patient with hypertension who develops pure motor or pure sensory deficits has a lacunar infarct.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Lacunar infarcts</b> are the small-vessel disease of the brain, where the long-term damage of hypertension leads to occlusion of tiny penetrating arteries, causing discrete subcortical strokes that manifest as 'pure' motor or sensory syndromes.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Chronic Hypertension] --> B(Lipohyalinosis of Penetrating Arteries); B --> C(Arterial Occlusion); C --> D(Lacunar Infarct); D --> E(Pure Motor or Sensory Syndromes);"
    },
    "connections": [
