    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Dermatome landmarks</b> are specific areas of skin innervated by a single spinal nerve root, which are used in the neurological examination to localize the level of a spinal cord or nerve root lesion.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>T4:</b> Level of the nipples. Mnemonic: T<b>4</b> at the teat <b>pore</b>.</li><li><b>T7:</b> Level of the xiphoid process.</li><li><b>T10:</b> Level of the umbilicus (belly bu<b>tt</b>on). Site of referred pain in early appendicitis.</li><li><b>L1:</b> Inguinal ligament region.</li><li><b>L4:</b> Includes the kneecaps. Mnemonic: Down on a<b>L</b>l <b>4</b>'s.</li><li><b>S2, S3, S4:</b> Sensation of the perineum. Mnemonic: <b>S2</b>, <b>3</b>, <b>4</b> keep the penis off the floor.</li><li><b>C6:</b> Includes the thumb.</li><li><b>C7:</b> Includes the middle finger.</li><li><b>C8:</b> Includes the little finger.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Knowledge of key <b>dermatome landmarks</b> allows a clinician to translate a patient's subjective sensory complaints into an objective anatomical location within the spinal cord, forming a crucial step in localizing neurological lesions.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
