  "4d8b1ee2": {
    "title": "Lateral Corticospinal Tract",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Spinal Cord"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Lateral Corticospinal Tract</b> is the largest descending motor pathway in the spinal cord, responsible for the voluntary control of contralateral limb and fine motor movements.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Controls voluntary, skilled movements of the distal extremities.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Composed of upper motor neuron axons that originate in the primary motor cortex. They descend through the internal capsule and cerebral peduncles, <mark>decussate (cross over) at the pyramidal decussation</mark> in the caudal medulla, and then descend in the lateral funiculus of the contralateral spinal cord to synapse on lower motor neurons in the anterior horn.</li><li><b>Somatotopy:</b> Within the tract, fibers are somatotopically organized, with cervical fibers located most medially and sacral fibers most laterally.</li><li><b>Lesion Effects:</b> Damage to the lateral corticospinal tract results in <mark>ipsilateral upper motor neuron (UMN) signs</mark> below the level of the lesion (because the fibers have already crossed). These signs include spastic paralysis, hyperreflexia, and a positive Babinski sign.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A lesion in the brain or brainstem above the pyramidal decussation causes contralateral UMN signs. A lesion in the spinal cord below the decussation causes ipsilateral UMN signs. This is a key principle for localizing lesions.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Lateral Corticospinal Tract</b> is the primary highway for voluntary motor commands to the limbs, and its decussation in the medulla is the crucial anatomical reason why one side of the brain controls the opposite side of the body.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Motor Cortex] --> B(Internal Capsule); B --> C(Cerebral Peduncle); C --> D(Pyramidal Decussation in Medulla); D --> E(Lateral Corticospinal Tract in Spinal Cord); E --> F(Synapse on LMN in Anterior Horn);"
    },
