      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Thalamus"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Lateral Geniculate Nucleus (LGN)</b>, also known as the lateral geniculate body, is a key nucleus in the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]] that serves as the primary thalamic relay station for <i>visual information</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Relays visual signals from the optic tract to the primary visual cortex in the occipital lobe.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Receives input from retinal ganglion cells via the optic tract. The LGN then projects via the optic radiation (which includes [[8423676f|Meyer's loop]] and the dorsal optic radiation) to the primary visual cortex (Brodmann area 17) in the calcarine sulcus.</li><li><b>Mnemonic:</b> <b>L</b>ateral geniculate nucleus for <b>L</b>ight (vision). Contrast with the <b>M</b>edial geniculate nucleus for <b>M</b>usic (hearing).</li><li><b>Laminar Structure:</b> It has a layered structure that keeps information from the ipsilateral and contralateral eyes separate.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the thalamic sensory relays: LGN for visual, MGN for auditory, VPL for body sensation, and VPM for face sensation. A lesion in the LGN causes a contralateral homonymous hemianopia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Lateral Geniculate Nucleus</b> is the brain's crucial gateway for vision, acting as the final processing and relay point in the thalamus before visual information is sent to the cortex for conscious perception.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Optic Tract] --> B(Lateral Geniculate Nucleus); B --> C(Optic Radiation); C --> D(Primary Visual Cortex);"
    },
