  "07656b4a": {
    "title": "Lateral Medullary Syndrome (Wallenberg Syndrome)",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Vascular",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brainstem Syndromes"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Lateral Medullary Syndrome</b>, also known as <b>Wallenberg syndrome</b>, is a brainstem stroke syndrome caused by an occlusion of the <i>posterior inferior cerebellar artery (PICA)</i> or the vertebral artery, affecting the lateral portion of the medulla.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Vascular Supply:</b> Caused by infarction in the territory of the <mark>Posterior Inferior Cerebellar Artery (PICA)</mark>. Mnemonic: Don't <b>PICA</b> (pick a) horse that can't eat (hoarseness and dysphagia).</li><li><b>Affected Structures & Symptoms:</b><br> - <b>Vestibular nuclei:</b> Nystagmus, vertigo, nausea/vomiting.<br> - <b>Inferior cerebellar peduncle:</b> Ipsilateral ataxia, dysmetria.<br> - <b>Spinothalamic tract:</b> <mark>Contralateral</mark> loss of pain and temperature from the body.<br> - <b>Spinal trigeminal nucleus:</b> <mark>Ipsilateral</mark> loss of pain and temperature from the face.<br> - <b>Nucleus ambiguus (CN IX, X):</b> <mark>Ipsilateral</mark> dysphagia, hoarseness, and decreased gag reflex.<br> - <b>Sympathetic fibers:</b> Ipsilateral Horner syndrome (ptosis, miosis, anhidrosis).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> This is a classic 'crossed' syndrome. The key is the combination of contralateral body sensory loss with ipsilateral face sensory loss and ipsilateral bulbar/cerebellar signs. Hoarseness and dysphagia are highly specific for this syndrome.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Wallenberg syndrome</b> is a constellation of deficits that perfectly maps to the anatomy of the lateral medulla; the crossed sensory findings (ipsilateral face, contralateral body) combined with ipsilateral ataxia and bulbar palsy are pathognomonic for a PICA occlusion.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[PICA Occlusion] --> B(Lateral Medullary Infarct); B --> C(Crossed Sensory Loss); B --> D(Ipsilateral Horner Syndrome); B --> E(Ipsilateral Ataxia); B --> F(Dysphagia/Hoarseness);"
    },
