      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Endocrine",
      "Anatomy",
      "Hypothalamus"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Lateral Nucleus</b> of the hypothalamus is a region of the hypothalamus that is considered the primary center for regulating <i>hunger</i> and food intake.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Regulates hunger. Stimulation of the lateral nucleus induces hunger and eating behavior.</li><li><b>Lesion Effect:</b> A lesion in the lateral nucleus causes <mark>anorexia</mark> and weight loss. Mnemonic: A lesion to the <b>L</b>ateral nucleus makes you <b>L</b>ean.</li><li><b>Neurotransmitters:</b> It is stimulated by ghrelin (a hunger hormone from the stomach) and inhibited by leptin (a satiety hormone from fat cells). It produces orexigenic (appetite-stimulating) neuropeptides like orexin.</li><li><b>Contrast with Ventromedial Nucleus:</b> The lateral nucleus is functionally opposed by the ventromedial nucleus (VMN), which is the satiety center. A lesion in the VMN causes hyperphagia and obesity.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the opposing functions: <b>L</b>ateral nucleus = <b>H</b>unger. <b>V</b>entro<b>m</b>edial nucleus = <b>S</b>atiety. (<b>L</b>ateral <b>H</b>unger, <b>V</b>ery <b>M</b>uch <b>S</b>atisfied).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Lateral Nucleus</b> of the hypothalamus acts as the body's 'on switch' for hunger; its destruction leads to a profound lack of appetite, highlighting its critical role in driving the fundamental behavior of seeking food.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
