    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Internal Jugular Vein (IJV)</b> is a major paired vein in the neck that collects blood from the brain, superficial face, and neck, and is the primary drainage point for the dural venous sinuses.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Course:</b> Originates at the jugular foramen at the base of the skull as a continuation of the sigmoid sinus. It descends in the neck within the carotid sheath, lateral to the common carotid artery.</li><li><b>Drainage:</b> The dural venous sinuses (e.g., superior sagittal sinus, cavernous sinus) ultimately drain into the sigmoid sinus, which then becomes the IJV.</li><li><b>Tributaries:</b> Receives blood from the facial, lingual, pharyngeal, and thyroid veins.</li><li><b>Termination:</b> Joins the subclavian vein to form the brachiocephalic vein.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> The IJV is used for central venous access (central line placement). The pulsations of the right IJV can be observed to estimate central venous pressure.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The jugular foramen is a key anatomical landmark through which the IJV exits the skull, along with cranial nerves IX, X, and XI.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Internal Jugular Vein</b> is the principal venous conduit draining the cranial cavity, serving as the final exit for blood from the dural venous sinus system before it returns to the heart.</p>",
