    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Internuclear Ophthalmoplegia (INO)</b> is a specific gaze palsy characterized by impaired horizontal eye movement, caused by a lesion in the <i>medial longitudinal fasciculus (MLF)</i> in the brainstem.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> A lesion in the [[59ad6172|MLF]] disrupts the signal from the contralateral [[dd11dde6|abducens (CN VI) nucleus]] to the ipsilateral [[68c66997|oculomotor (CN III) nucleus]].</li><li><b>Clinical Signs:</b> When the patient attempts to look away from the side of the lesion, the ipsilateral (adducting) eye fails to move medially past the midline. The contralateral (abducting) eye exhibits nystagmus. Convergence is typically preserved.</li><li><b>Mnemonic:</b> <b>INO</b> = <b>I</b>psilateral adduction failure, <b>N</b>ystagmus <b>O</b>pposite.</li><li><b>Etiology:</b> In a young adult, <mark>bilateral INO</mark> is pathognomonic for [[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]]. In an older adult, a <mark>unilateral INO</mark> is most often caused by a brainstem stroke.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A young woman with [[45dd6d19|MS]] who develops double vision and is found to have impaired adduction in one eye on lateral gaze has INO.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Internuclear Ophthalmoplegia</b> is a highly specific neurological sign that uncouples the normally yoked horizontal movements of the eyes, precisely localizing a lesion to the MLF and strongly suggesting either multiple sclerosis or a brainstem stroke depending on the patient's age and laterality.</p>",
