    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Intracranial Pressure (ICP)</b> is the pressure exerted by the contents of the cranium‚Äîbrain tissue, cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), and blood‚Äîwithin the rigid, non-expandable skull. Normal ICP is typically <15 mmHg in adults.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Monro-Kellie Doctrine:</b> States that the sum of the volumes of brain, CSF, and intracranial blood is constant. An increase in one component must be compensated by a decrease in another, or ICP will rise.</li><li><b>Cerebral Perfusion Pressure (CPP):</b> CPP = MAP - ICP. Maintaining adequate CPP is crucial for brain viability. As ICP rises, CPP falls, potentially leading to cerebral ischemia.</li><li><b>Regulation of ICP:</b> Can be influenced by factors that alter cerebral blood volume (e.g., PaCO<sub>2</sub>), CSF volume (e.g., [[0bc2f200|hydrocephalus]]), or brain tissue volume (e.g., edema).</li><li><b>Ex Vacuo Ventriculomegaly:</b> This is ventricular enlargement due to brain atrophy, not increased CSF pressure. In this case, ICP is normal.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Therapeutic hyperventilation (lowering PaCO<sub>2</sub>) causes cerebral vasoconstriction, which reduces cerebral blood volume and can temporarily lower ICP in an emergency.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Intracranial pressure</b> is a delicate balance of brain, blood, and CSF volumes within the fixed skull. The Monro-Kellie doctrine dictates that when this balance is disrupted by a pathological process, ICP rises, threatening cerebral perfusion and brain function.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
