    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Intraocular Pressure (IOP)</b> is the fluid pressure inside the eye, maintained by a balance between the production and drainage of aqueous humor. Elevated IOP is the primary risk factor for the development and progression of glaucoma.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Normal Range:</b> Typically between 10 and 21 mmHg.</li><li><b>Determinants:</b> Determined by the rate of aqueous humor production by the ciliary body and the resistance to its outflow through the trabecular meshwork and uveoscleral pathway.</li><li><b>Aqueous Humor Production:</b> Secreted by the ciliary epithelium, a process that can be decreased by beta-blockers and carbonic anhydrase inhibitors.</li><li><b>Aqueous Humor Outflow:</b> Drains primarily via the trabecular meshwork (conventional pathway) and secondarily via the uveoscleral pathway. Prostaglandin analogs increase uveoscleral outflow, while cholinergic agonists increase trabecular outflow.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Elevated IOP (ocular hypertension) damages the optic nerve head, leading to the progressive optic neuropathy of [[3ce6c035|glaucoma]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The main goal of [[3ce6c035|glaucoma]] treatment is to lower IOP, either by decreasing aqueous humor production or by increasing its outflow.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Intraocular pressure</b> is the 'blood pressure' of the eye, a dynamic equilibrium of aqueous humor production and drainage. When this equilibrium is disrupted and pressure rises, it exerts a damaging force on the optic nerve, leading to the irreversible vision loss of glaucoma.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
