    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Intraparenchymal hemorrhage</b>, also known as intracerebral hemorrhage, is a type of hemorrhagic stroke characterized by bleeding directly into the brain parenchyma. It is most commonly caused by chronic hypertension.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology (Hypertensive):</b> Chronic hypertension leads to the formation of <mark>Charcot-Bouchard microaneurysms</mark> in small, penetrating arteries. Rupture of these microaneurysms is the most common cause.</li><li><b>Common Locations:</b> Hypertensive hemorrhages typically occur in deep brain structures, most commonly the <mark>basal ganglia (putamen)</mark>, followed by the thalamus, pons, and cerebellum.</li><li><b>Etiology (Other):</b> Other causes include cerebral amyloid angiopathy (lobar hemorrhages in the elderly), vascular malformations, tumors, and reperfusion injury after an ischemic stroke.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Sudden onset of focal neurological deficits that progress over minutes to hours. Symptoms depend on the location of the bleed and are often accompanied by headache, nausea/vomiting, and altered consciousness.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> An elderly patient with a history of poorly controlled hypertension who presents with a sudden focal deficit and signs of increased ICP has likely suffered a hypertensive intraparenchymal hemorrhage, most probably in the basal ganglia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Intraparenchymal hemorrhage</b> is a devastating stroke subtype where chronic hypertension weakens small, deep arteries to the point of rupture (Charcot-Bouchard microaneurysms), causing a bleed directly into critical brain structures like the basal ganglia.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
