      "Anesthetics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Intravenous anesthetics</b> are a group of drugs administered intravenously to induce or maintain general anesthesia. They are typically rapid-acting and lipid-soluble, allowing them to quickly cross the blood-brain barrier.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Propofol:</b> The most commonly used IV agent for induction and maintenance of anesthesia. Potentiates GABA<sub>A</sub> receptors. Causes hypotension and respiratory depression.</li><li><b>Etomidate:</b> Potentiates GABA<sub>A</sub> receptors. It is <mark>hemodynamically neutral</mark>, making it ideal for induction in trauma or cardiac patients. Can cause adrenal insufficiency.</li><li><b>Ketamine:</b> An NMDA receptor antagonist. It is a dissociative anesthetic that provides analgesia and amnesia. It is a sympathomimetic, causing increased heart rate and blood pressure. Can cause emergence reactions (hallucinations).</li><li><b>Barbiturates (Thiopental):</b> Potentiate GABA<sub>A</sub> by increasing the duration of Cl<sup>-</sup> channel opening. Rapid onset due to high lipid solubility, but has a short duration of action due to rapid redistribution to skeletal muscle and fat.</li><li><b>Benzodiazepines (Midazolam):</b> Potentiate GABA<sub>A</sub> by increasing the frequency of Cl<sup>-</sup> channel opening. Used for sedation and anxiolysis.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Know the key distinguishing features: Propofol = most common, hypotension. Etomidate = hemodynamically stable. Ketamine = sympathomimetic, dissociative.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Intravenous anesthetics</b> induce unconsciousness by enhancing inhibitory neurotransmission (GABA) or blocking excitatory neurotransmission (glutamate), with each agent possessing a unique hemodynamic and side effect profile that dictates its specific clinical application.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
