    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Neonatal Intraventricular Hemorrhage (IVH)</b> is bleeding into the brain's ventricular system, a common and serious complication of prematurity, originating from the fragile germinal matrix.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Risk Factors:</b> The single most important risk factor is <mark>prematurity</mark>, especially in infants born before 32 weeks' gestation or with very low birth weight (<1500g).</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The hemorrhage originates from the <mark>germinal matrix</mark>, a highly vascularized region in the subventricular zone that is prominent in premature infants. The immature vessels in this region are prone to rupture with fluctuations in cerebral blood flow.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Can be asymptomatic or present with signs of neurological distress, such as altered consciousness, bulging fontanelle, hypotension, seizures, or coma.</li><li><b>Complications:</b> Can lead to post-hemorrhagic [[0bc2f200|hydrocephalus]] (due to blockage of CSF pathways by blood clots or scarring of arachnoid granulations) and long-term neurodevelopmental impairment, including [[171ca00b|cerebral palsy]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A premature infant who suddenly develops a bulging fontanelle, decreased activity, and a drop in hematocrit should be evaluated for IVH with a cranial ultrasound.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Neonatal Intraventricular Hemorrhage</b> is a disease of prematurity, where the fragile, underdeveloped blood vessels of the germinal matrix rupture, leading to bleeding into the ventricles and the potential for lifelong neurological disability.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
