    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Iritis</b> is inflammation of the iris, the colored part of the eye. It is the most common form of anterior uveitis.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Presents with a red, painful eye, photophobia, and blurred vision. On exam, there is often ciliary flush (a ring of redness around the cornea) and may be a constricted or irregular pupil.</li><li><b>Slit-Lamp Exam:</b> The hallmark finding is the presence of inflammatory cells and flare (protein) in the anterior chamber. Keratic precipitates (inflammatory cells on the corneal endothelium) may also be seen.</li><li><b>Systemic Associations:</b> While it can be idiopathic, iritis is strongly associated with systemic inflammatory and autoimmune diseases, particularly the <mark>HLA-B27-associated spondyloarthropathies</mark> (ankylosing spondylitis, reactive arthritis, psoriatic arthritis, IBD-associated arthritis). It is also seen in sarcoidosis and juvenile idiopathic arthritis.</li><li><b>Complications:</b> Can lead to posterior synechiae (adhesions between the iris and lens), glaucoma, and cataracts if not treated appropriately.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient with a seronegative spondyloarthropathy (e.g., ankylosing spondylitis) who presents with a painful red eye likely has anterior uveitis/iritis.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Iritis</b> is an intraocular inflammation that often serves as an ocular marker for systemic autoimmune disease, particularly the HLA-B27 spondyloarthropathies, making a thorough systemic review essential in any patient with a painful, red eye.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
