    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Iron deficiency</b> is a major secondary cause and risk factor for <i>Restless Legs Syndrome (RLS)</i>, a neurological disorder characterized by an irresistible urge to move the legs, typically accompanied by unpleasant sensations.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Restless Legs Syndrome (RLS):</b> An urge to move the legs, usually worse at rest and in the evening, and temporarily relieved by movement.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The link is not fully understood, but iron is a crucial cofactor for <mark>tyrosine hydroxylase</mark>, the rate-limiting enzyme in dopamine synthesis. It is hypothesized that low brain iron levels lead to dysfunctional dopaminergic transmission in the CNS, contributing to RLS symptoms.</li><li><b>Clinical Evaluation:</b> All patients with RLS should be screened for iron deficiency by checking their serum <mark>ferritin</mark> levels.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> If iron deficiency is present (typically defined as ferritin < 50-75 ng/mL), iron supplementation is a first-line treatment and can significantly improve or resolve RLS symptoms.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> In a patient presenting with symptoms of RLS, the first step in management is to check their serum ferritin level to rule out iron deficiency as a treatable underlying cause.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The connection between low <b>iron</b> stores and <b>Restless Legs Syndrome</b> highlights the importance of iron in CNS dopamine synthesis; repleting iron in deficient patients can correct the underlying neurochemical imbalance and alleviate the distressing symptoms of RLS.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
