      "Cerebrovascular Disease"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>An <b>ischemic stroke</b> is a neurological deficit of sudden onset resulting from focal cerebral ischemia due to an interruption of blood supply to a part of the brain. It is the most common type of stroke, accounting for approximately 80% of cases.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Types:</b><br> - <b>Thrombotic:</b> Caused by a thrombus forming on a ruptured atherosclerotic plaque within a cerebral artery.<br> - <b>Embolic:</b> Caused by an embolus (e.g., from the heart in atrial fibrillation or from a carotid artery plaque) lodging in a cerebral artery.<br> - <b>Hypoxic:</b> Caused by systemic hypoperfusion (e.g., in shock), typically affecting watershed areas.</li><li><b>Pathology Time Course:</b> The brain tissue undergoes <mark>liquefactive necrosis</mark>. Histological changes include 'red neurons' (12-24 hrs), neutrophil infiltration (24-72 hrs), macrophage/microglial infiltration (3-5 days), reactive gliosis (1-2 weeks), and finally a glial scar ( >2 weeks).</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> A non-contrast CT is the crucial first step to rule out hemorrhage. It may be normal in the first 6-24 hours. Diffusion-weighted MRI is the most sensitive test and can detect ischemia within minutes.</li><li><b>Acute Treatment:</b> Intravenous thrombolysis with tPA (alteplase) if within the 3-4.5 hour window and no contraindications. Mechanical thrombectomy may be an option for large vessel occlusions.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The primary goal of the initial head CT in a suspected stroke is not to diagnose the ischemic stroke itself, but to exclude hemorrhage so that thrombolytic therapy can be safely administered.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>An <b>ischemic stroke</b> is a 'brain attack' where a blocked artery leads to neuronal death and liquefactive necrosis. The clinical presentation is dictated by the vascular territory affected, and the immediate management hinges on rapidly distinguishing it from a hemorrhagic stroke to allow for time-sensitive reperfusion therapy.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
