    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Isoflurane</b> is a volatile <i>inhaled general anesthetic</i> used for the induction and, more commonly, the maintenance of general anesthesia.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Has a medium blood:gas partition coefficient, resulting in a slower onset and recovery compared to newer agents like desflurane and sevoflurane, but faster than halothane.</li><li><b>Potency:</b> Has a low MAC (Minimum Alveolar Concentration) of ~1.2%, indicating high anesthetic potency.</li><li><b>Systemic Effects:</b><br> - <b>Cardiovascular:</b> Causes dose-dependent decrease in mean arterial pressure, primarily through a decrease in systemic vascular resistance (vasodilation). Cardiac output is generally maintained.<br> - <b>Respiratory:</b> A potent respiratory depressant, decreasing tidal volume and minute ventilation.<br> - <b>Cerebral:</b> Increases cerebral blood flow (due to vasodilation), which can increase intracranial pressure. It also decreases cerebral metabolic rate.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Pungent odor can cause airway irritation, coughing, and laryngospasm, making it less ideal for inhalation induction. It is a potential trigger for [[429af8bd|malignant hyperthermia]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Know the relative properties of inhaled anesthetics. Isoflurane has higher potency (lower MAC) and slower onset (higher blood:gas coefficient) than desflurane and sevoflurane.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Isoflurane</b> is a potent but relatively slow-acting inhaled anesthetic whose main hemodynamic effect is vasodilation, leading to a drop in blood pressure, and like other volatile anesthetics, it carries the risk of triggering malignant hyperthermia.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
