      "Cranial Nerves"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Jaw Jerk Reflex</b> is a monosynaptic stretch reflex that involves the muscles of mastication, used to test the integrity of the <i>trigeminal nerve (CN V)</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Elicitation:</b> The patient's mouth is held slightly open and relaxed. The examiner places a finger on the chin and taps it with a reflex hammer.</li><li><b>Normal Response:</b> A minimal or absent jerk (slight closure of the jaw).</li><li><b>Abnormal Response (Hyperreflexia):</b> A brisk, exaggerated closure of the jaw is an abnormal finding and indicates an <mark>upper motor neuron (UMN) lesion</mark> above the level of the trigeminal motor nucleus in the pons.</li><li><b>Reflex Arc:</b><br> - <b>Afferent Limb:</b> Proprioceptive fibers from the masseter muscle travel via the mandibular division of the <mark>trigeminal nerve (CN V<sub>3</sub>)</mark> to the mesencephalic nucleus of CN V.<br> - <b>Efferent Limb:</b> Motor fibers from the motor nucleus of CN V travel via the <mark>trigeminal nerve (CN V<sub>3</sub>)</mark> to cause contraction of the masseter muscle.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The jaw jerk is unique because both its afferent and efferent limbs are carried by the same cranial nerve (CN V). A hyperactive jaw jerk is a sign of a bilateral UMN lesion, as seen in conditions like [[4ed629f9|amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS)]] or pseudobulbar palsy.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Jaw Jerk Reflex</b> is a cranial nerve equivalent of a deep tendon reflex, specifically testing the integrity of the trigeminal nerve. An exaggerated response is a key sign of upper motor neuron disease affecting the corticobulbar tracts.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Tap on Chin] --> B(Stretch Masseter); B --> C(Afferent via CN V3); C --> D(Mesencephalic & Motor Nuclei of CN V); D --> E(Efferent via CN V3); E --> F(Masseter Contraction);"
