      "Immunology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Infections"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>JC virus (John Cunningham virus)</b> is a common human polyomavirus that is typically asymptomatic in immunocompetent individuals but can reactivate in the setting of severe immunosuppression, causing the fatal demyelinating disease <i>Progressive Multifocal Leukoencephalopathy (PML)</i>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Microbiology:</b> A member of the Polyomaviridae family; a small, non-enveloped, double-stranded DNA virus.</li><li><b>Latency:</b> After primary infection (usually in childhood), the virus establishes a lifelong latent infection in the kidneys and lymphoid tissue.</li><li><b>Reactivation:</b> Reactivation occurs in states of severe cell-mediated immunodeficiency, such as advanced <mark>HIV/AIDS</mark> (CD4 count < 200), hematologic malignancies, or in patients on immunosuppressive therapies like [[ae20a0ce|natalizumab]].</li><li><b>Pathogenesis of PML:</b> The reactivated virus spreads to the brain and infects and destroys <mark>oligodendrocytes</mark>, the myelin-producing cells of the CNS.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation of PML:</b> Rapidly progressive, multifocal neurological deficits, including cognitive decline, motor weakness, and visual changes. It is usually fatal.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The triad of an immunocompromised patient (especially AIDS or on natalizumab), rapidly progressive neurological symptoms, and multifocal non-enhancing white matter lesions on MRI is classic for PML caused by JC virus.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>JC virus</b> is a ubiquitous and harmless passenger in most of the population, but in an immunocompromised host, it can transform into a destructive pathogen that specifically targets and lyses oligodendrocytes, leading to the devastating demyelinating disease PML.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
