    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Hypothalamus</b> is a small but vital region of the diencephalon located below the thalamus, which serves as the primary link between the nervous system and the endocrine system via the pituitary gland. It is the main control center for the autonomic nervous system and regulates homeostasis.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Main Functions (TAN HATS):</b> <b>T</b>hirst and water balance, <b>A</b>denohypophysis control, <b>N</b>eurohypophysis hormone production, <b>H</b>unger, <b>A</b>utonomic regulation, <b>T</b>emperature regulation, <b>S</b>exual urges.</li><li><b>Key Nuclei:</b><br> - <b>Lateral Nucleus:</b> Hunger center. Lesion ‚Üí anorexia. <br> - <b>Ventromedial Nucleus:</b> Satiety center. Lesion ‚Üí hyperphagia. <br> - <b>Anterior Nucleus:</b> Cooling, parasympathetic. Lesion ‚Üí hyperthermia.<br> - <b>Posterior Nucleus:</b> Heating, sympathetic. Lesion ‚Üí inability to thermoregulate.<br> - <b>Suprachiasmatic Nucleus (SCN):</b> Circadian rhythm.<br> - <b>Supraoptic & Paraventricular Nuclei:</b> Synthesize ADH and oxytocin.</li><li><b>Endocrine Control:</b> Produces releasing and inhibiting hormones (e.g., GnRH, CRH, TRH, somatostatin, dopamine) that travel via the hypophyseal portal system to control the [[76ba7f2e|anterior pituitary]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the functions of the lateral and ventromedial nuclei with the mnemonic: A lesion to the <b>L</b>ateral nucleus makes you <b>L</b>ean. A lesion to the <b>V</b>entro<b>m</b>edial nucleus makes you <b>V</b>ery <b>M</b>assive.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Hypothalamus</b> is the master regulator of homeostasis, constantly monitoring the body's internal state and orchestrating a wide range of autonomic, endocrine, and behavioral responses to maintain a stable internal environment.</p>",
