    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>hypoxic stroke</b>, also known as hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy (HIE) in a global context, is brain damage caused by a systemic reduction in oxygen delivery, resulting from either hypoxemia (low blood oxygen content) or ischemia (low blood flow).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Caused by conditions leading to global cerebral hypoperfusion, such as cardiac arrest, profound hypotension (shock), or asphyxiation.</li><li><b>Vulnerable Areas:</b> Certain brain regions are particularly susceptible to hypoxic-ischemic injury due to their high metabolic demand. These include:<br> - Pyramidal cells of the <mark>hippocampus</mark> (specifically CA1 region).<br> - <mark>Purkinje cells</mark> of the cerebellum.<br> - Pyramidal cells of the neocortex (leading to laminar necrosis).</li><li><b>Watershed Infarcts:</b> Hypoxic strokes characteristically affect <mark>watershed areas</mark>‚Äîthe border zones between territories supplied by major cerebral arteries (e.g., between ACA and MCA territories). These areas are the most vulnerable to a systemic drop in blood pressure.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Can range from mild confusion to coma or brain death, depending on the severity and duration of the insult. Diffuse neurological deficits are common.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient who suffers a cardiac arrest and subsequently develops neurological deficits likely has hypoxic-ischemic brain injury. Look for damage in watershed zones or the highly vulnerable hippocampal and cerebellar cells.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>hypoxic stroke</b> is a global brain injury resulting from a systemic lack of oxygen or blood flow, which selectively damages the most metabolically active neurons and the most tenuously perfused watershed territories.</p>",
