    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension (IIH)</b>, also known as pseudotumor cerebri, is a condition of increased intracranial pressure with no evident cause on neuroimaging, classically affecting young, obese women.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Epidemiology:</b> Most common in <mark>women of childbearing age who are obese</mark>.</li><li><b>Associated Factors:</b> Associated with certain medications, including tetracyclines, oral contraceptives, and excess vitamin A.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Presents with symptoms of increased ICP: <mark>headache</mark> (often pulsatile, worse with straining), pulsatile tinnitus, and visual disturbances.</li><li><b>Ophthalmologic Findings:</b> <mark>Papilledema</mark> (swelling of the optic disc) is a key finding. Patients may also have a [[dd11dde6|CN VI palsy]], leading to horizontal diplopia. Untreated, it can lead to permanent vision loss.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> Based on clinical findings, papilledema, normal neuroimaging (to rule out a mass or hydrocephalus), and an <mark>elevated opening pressure</mark> (>250 mmH<sub>2</sub>O) on lumbar puncture with normal CSF composition.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Weight loss is the cornerstone of long-term management. <mark>Acetazolamide</mark> (a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor) is used to decrease CSF production.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The classic vignette is an obese young woman with a daily headache, pulsatile tinnitus, and papilledema.</li></ul>",
