    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Increased Intracranial Pressure (ICP)</b> is a pathological elevation of pressure within the rigid cranial vault. It is a neurological emergency that can lead to decreased cerebral perfusion and brain herniation.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Causes:</b> Can be caused by an increase in the volume of any of the intracranial components: brain parenchyma (e.g., tumor, edema), blood (e.g., hemorrhage, [[067666cd|venous sinus thrombosis]]), or cerebrospinal fluid (e.g., [[0bc2f200|hydrocephalus]]).</li><li><b>Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension (IIH):</b> A specific syndrome of increased ICP with no evident cause on imaging, typically affecting young, obese women.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Headache (often worse in the morning or with Valsalva), nausea/vomiting, [[4ae219da|papilledema]], and visual disturbances. [[dd11dde6|CN VI palsy]] is a common finding.</li><li><b>Cushing's Triad:</b> A late and ominous sign of severely elevated ICP, consisting of hypertension, bradycardia, and irregular respirations.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Papilledema is the cardinal sign of increased ICP on physical exam. A CN VI palsy in the setting of headache is often a 'false localizing sign' pointing to generalized increased ICP.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Increased Intracranial Pressure</b> occurs when the volume of the brain's contents exceeds the compensatory capacity of the skull, leading to a dangerous rise in pressure that can compress vital brain structures and compromise cerebral blood flow.</p>",
