    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Indirect Pathway</b> is a neuronal circuit within the [[ed462927|basal ganglia]] that has a net <i>inhibitory</i> effect on the thalamus, thereby suppressing unwanted or competing movements.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> To inhibit movement by increasing the tonic inhibition of the thalamus.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Cortical excitation of the striatum leads to inhibition of the globus pallidus externus (GPe). This disinhibits the subthalamic nucleus (STN), allowing the STN to excite the globus pallidus internus (GPi). The now-excited GPi increases its inhibition of the thalamus, which in turn reduces excitation of the motor cortex.</li><li><b>Dopamine's Role:</b> [[90adc821|Dopamine]] from the substantia nigra pars compacta <mark>inhibits</mark> the indirect pathway by acting on D2 receptors in the striatum.</li><li><b>Pathology (Parkinson's):</b> In [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]], the loss of dopamine leads to overactivity of the indirect pathway, contributing to the profound inhibition of movement (bradykinesia).</li><li><b>Pathology (Huntington's):</b> In early [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]], degeneration of the indirect pathway neurons in the striatum leads to disinhibition of the thalamus and hyperkinetic movements (chorea).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that the indirect pathway is inhibitory to movement. Dopamine inhibits this pathway. Therefore, loss of dopamine (Parkinson's) leads to less movement, while damage to the pathway itself (Huntington's) leads to more movement.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Indirect Pathway</b> acts as the 'brake' of the basal ganglia motor circuit; its complex, multi-step process ultimately amplifies the inhibition of the thalamus to suppress unwanted movements, and its dysregulation is a key factor in both hypokinetic and hyperkinetic disorders.</p>",
