    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Cerebral infarcts</b> are areas of necrotic brain tissue resulting from ischemia, most commonly caused by the occlusion of a cerebral artery. The location and extent of the infarct determine the clinical neurological deficits.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Types:</b><br> - <b>Thrombotic:</b> Due to local clot formation, often over an atherosclerotic plaque.<br> - <b>Embolic:</b> Due to a clot traveling from a distant source (e.g., heart, carotid arteries).<br> - <b>Lacunar:</b> Small infarcts in deep brain structures from occlusion of small penetrating arteries.</li><li><b>Cortical Areas:</b> Infarcts in the territories of the major cerebral arteries ([[830c856c|ACA]], [[143bb23d|MCA]], [[b6a2cc31|PCA]]) produce characteristic patterns of motor, sensory, and cognitive deficits known as 'cortical signs' (e.g., aphasia, neglect).</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> The brain undergoes <mark>liquefactive necrosis</mark> following an ischemic event.</li><li><b>Watershed Infarcts:</b> Occur in the border zones between major arterial territories and are associated with systemic hypoperfusion.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The clinical syndrome presented in a stroke question is the key to identifying the affected artery and the location of the infarct.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Cerebral infarcts</b> are the pathological consequence of an ischemic stroke, where the specific neurological deficit serves as a precise map to the occluded blood vessel and the corresponding area of necrotic brain tissue.</p>",
