    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Infective dementia</b> refers to a progressive decline in cognitive function caused by a chronic or subacute infection of the central nervous system.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>HIV-Associated Dementia (HAD):</b> Occurs in patients with advanced HIV/AIDS (CD4 < 200). Caused by inflammatory activation of microglial cells, which form multinucleated giant cells. Presents with subcortical dementia (e.g., slowed movements and cognitive processing).</li><li><b>Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD):</b> A rapidly progressive dementia caused by prions. Characterized by myoclonus and ataxia.</li><li><b>Neurosyphilis:</b> Tertiary syphilis can cause a progressive dementia known as general paresis.</li><li><b>Progressive Multifocal Leukoencephalopathy (PML):</b> Caused by reactivation of the [[30b75088|JC virus]] in immunocompromised individuals. A demyelinating disease that leads to rapidly progressive neurological deficits and dementia.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> When a patient with dementia presents with an atypical, rapid course or has risk factors for specific infections (e.g., HIV, history of syphilis), consider an infective etiology.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>While most dementias are neurodegenerative, a subset is caused by chronic CNS infections. These <b>infective dementias</b> are important to recognize as some, like neurosyphilis, may be treatable, and others, like CJD, have important public health implications.</p>",
