      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Actions:</b> Primary: Extorsion (outward rotation). Secondary: Elevation and Abduction.</li><li><b>Innervation:</b> Innervated by the inferior division of the <mark>oculomotor nerve (CN III)</mark>.</li><li><b>Testing:</b> The elevating action of the inferior oblique is best isolated when the eye is adducted (looking toward the nose) and the patient is asked to look up. Mnemonic: <b>I</b>nferior oblique tested looking <b>I</b>n and up.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> Paralysis of the inferior oblique (as part of a [[68c66997|CN III palsy]]) contributes to the 'down and out' position of the eye and causes vertical diplopia.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the mnemonic <b>LR<sub>6</sub>SO<sub>4</sub>R<sub>3</sub></b>. The inferior oblique is part of the 'Rest' innervated by CN III.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Inferior Oblique</b> muscle is unique in its primary action of extorsion, but its clinically tested function is elevation of the adducted eye, a key movement for diagnosing oculomotor nerve palsies.</p>",
