    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Inferior Rectus</b> is one of the six extraocular muscles. Its primary action is depression of the eyeball, with secondary actions of adduction and extorsion.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Actions:</b> Primary: Depression (downward movement). Secondary: Adduction and Extorsion.</li><li><b>Innervation:</b> Innervated by the inferior division of the <mark>oculomotor nerve (CN III)</mark>.</li><li><b>Testing:</b> The depressing action of the inferior rectus is best isolated when the eye is abducted (looking away from the nose) and the patient is asked to look down.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> Paralysis of the inferior rectus (as part of a [[68c66997|CN III palsy]]) contributes to the 'down and out' position of the eye and causes vertical diplopia. In an orbital floor 'blowout' fracture, the inferior rectus can become entrapped, restricting upward gaze.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the mnemonic <b>LR<sub>6</sub>SO<sub>4</sub>R<sub>3</sub></b>. The inferior rectus is part of the 'Rest' innervated by CN III.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Inferior Rectus</b> muscle is the primary depressor of the eye, and its function is best tested by having the patient look down and out; its entrapment in an orbital floor fracture is a classic cause of restricted upgaze.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
