    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Inhaled anesthetics</b> are volatile liquids or gases that are administered via inhalation to induce and maintain general anesthesia. Their effects are dose-dependent and reversible.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Examples:</b> Halothane (historical), [[70509ee9|isoflurane]], sevoflurane, desflurane, and [[9c56fa3c|nitrous oxide (N<sub>2</sub>O)]].</li><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> The exact mechanism is unknown, but they are thought to enhance the activity of inhibitory neurotransmitter receptors (e.g., GABA<sub>A</sub>, glycine) and inhibit excitatory receptors (e.g., NMDA).</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b><br> - <b>Onset/Recovery:</b> Determined by blood solubility (blood:gas partition coefficient). Low solubility (e.g., N<sub>2</sub>O, desflurane) = rapid onset and recovery. High solubility = slow onset/recovery.<br> - <b>Potency:</b> Determined by lipid solubility (oil:gas partition coefficient) and measured by the <mark>Minimum Alveolar Concentration (MAC)</mark>. High lipid solubility = low MAC = high potency.</li><li><b>Systemic Effects:</b> Cause myocardial depression, hypotension (vasodilation), respiratory depression, and increased cerebral blood flow.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> All volatile anesthetics (not N<sub>2</sub>O) can trigger <mark>malignant hyperthermia</mark> in susceptible individuals. Halothane is associated with severe hepatotoxicity.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The clinical properties of <b>inhaled anesthetics</b> are governed by their physical solubilities: low blood solubility allows for rapid control of anesthetic depth, while high lipid solubility confers high potency, allowing for effective anesthesia at low concentrations.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
