    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Inner Ear</b> is the innermost part of the ear, housed within the petrous part of the temporal bone. It contains the sensory organs for hearing (the cochlea) and balance (the vestibular system).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Components:</b> Consists of the bony labyrinth, a system of bony canals, which contains the membranous labyrinth, a system of fluid-filled sacs and ducts.</li><li><b>Cochlea:</b> The spiral-shaped, fluid-filled structure responsible for hearing. It contains the [[2e814378|organ of Corti]], which transduces sound vibrations into nerve impulses.</li><li><b>Vestibular System:</b> Responsible for balance and spatial orientation. It includes the three semicircular canals (which detect rotational movements) and the otolith organs (utricle and saccule, which detect linear acceleration and gravity).</li><li><b>Fluids:</b> The membranous labyrinth is filled with endolymph (high in K<sup>+</sup>), while the space between the bony and membranous labyrinths is filled with perilymph (high in Na<sup>+</sup>).</li><li><b>Innervation:</b> The [[6fded3e7|vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII)]] carries auditory information from the cochlea and vestibular information from the vestibular system to the brainstem.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Pathologies of the inner ear cause sensorineural hearing loss and/or vertigo. [[6f2228c1|M√©ni√®re disease]] is a classic disorder of the inner ear caused by an excess of endolymph.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Inner Ear</b> is a sophisticated transducer that converts mechanical energy‚Äîsound vibrations and head movements‚Äîinto the electrical language of the nervous system, subserving the distinct but related senses of hearing and balance.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
