      "Sedative-Hypnotics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Insomnia therapy</b> involves pharmacological and non-pharmacological approaches to manage the inability to fall asleep, stay asleep, or get restorative sleep. Pharmacological agents primarily include benzodiazepines, nonbenzodiazepine hypnotics, and melatonin receptor agonists.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Benzodiazepines:</b> (e.g., temazepam, triazolam) Increase the frequency of GABA<sub>A</sub> channel opening. Effective but can alter sleep architecture, cause dependence, and have next-day sedation.</li><li><b>Nonbenzodiazepine Hypnotics (\"Z-drugs\"):</b> (e.g., zolpidem, zaleplon, eszopiclone) Act selectively on the BZ1 subtype of the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor. Less disruption of sleep architecture and lower dependence risk than benzodiazepines. Effects are reversed by flumazenil.</li><li><b>Melatonin Receptor Agonists:</b> (e.g., [[bbf7e9ef|ramelteon]]) Agonist at melatonin receptors in the suprachiasmatic nucleus. Helps with sleep onset and is not a controlled substance, with no abuse potential.</li><li><b>Orexin Receptor Antagonists:</b> (e.g., suvorexant) Block orexin, a neuropeptide that promotes wakefulness.</li><li><b>Other Agents:</b> Sedating antidepressants (e.g., trazodone, mirtazapine) and antihistamines (e.g., diphenhydramine) are also used.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Modern <b>insomnia therapy</b> has shifted from broad CNS depressants like benzodiazepines towards more targeted agents, such as the Z-drugs that selectively act on GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor subtypes or ramelteon that targets the body's natural sleep-wake cycle via melatonin receptors.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
