    "title": "Intention Tremor",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "Movement Disorders",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Movement Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>An <b>intention tremor</b> is a type of action tremor characterized by a broad, coarse, low-frequency tremor that is absent at rest and worsens as the limb approaches a target during a voluntary, visually-guided movement. It is a cardinal sign of cerebellar dysfunction.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Results from a lesion in the [[bebe58d4|cerebellum]] or its connections (e.g., superior cerebellar peduncle). The cerebellum is responsible for coordinating and fine-tuning movements, and its dysfunction leads to an inability to smoothly correct for errors in movement trajectory.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> The tremor is absent when the limb is at rest. It appears and progressively worsens as the patient attempts a purposeful movement, such as reaching for an object or performing the finger-to-nose test.</li><li><b>Associated Conditions:</b> A classic sign of diseases affecting the cerebellum, such as <mark>[[45dd6d19|Multiple Sclerosis]]</mark>, stroke, tumors, or chronic alcoholism.</li><li><b>Distinction from Other Tremors:</b><br> - <b>Resting Tremor:</b> Occurs at rest and improves with movement (e.g., [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]]).<br> - <b>Essential Tremor:</b> A postural and action tremor that is typically faster and less coarse than an intention tremor.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A tremor that is worst at the end of a goal-directed movement (e.g., finger-to-nose test) is an intention tremor and points to a lesion in the ipsilateral cerebellum.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>An <b>intention tremor</b> is the physical manifestation of a failing cerebellar feedback loop; as the hand nears its target, the cerebellum's inability to make fine, real-time adjustments to the movement results in progressively larger oscillations.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
