      "definition": "<p><b>Hydrocephalus</b> is the abnormal accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) within the brain's ventricles, leading to ventricular dilation and, typically, increased intracranial pressure (ICP).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Communicating Hydrocephalus:</b> Caused by impaired CSF absorption by the arachnoid granulations (e.g., post-meningitis scarring). All ventricles are symmetrically dilated. [[7c59030e|Normal pressure hydrocephalus (NPH)]] is a subtype.</li><li><b>Non-communicating (Obstructive) Hydrocephalus:</b> Caused by a structural blockage of CSF flow within the ventricular system (e.g., aqueductal stenosis, tumor). Ventricles proximal to the obstruction are dilated. Common in [[7f8bdf0b|childhood brain tumors]] like [[16d613bb|medulloblastoma]].</li><li><b>Hydrocephalus ex Vacuo:</b> A mimic of hydrocephalus where there is ventricular enlargement due to brain atrophy and neuronal loss (e.g., in Alzheimer's disease). ICP is normal.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> In adults, symptoms of increased ICP (headache, papilledema, vomiting). In infants, macrocephaly (enlarging head circumference) and bulging fontanelles.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The key distinction is between communicating (absorption problem) and non-communicating (flow problem). Imaging helps differentiate them by showing either all ventricles enlarged or only those upstream of a blockage.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Hydrocephalus</b> is a condition of 'water on the brain' that results from an imbalance between CSF production and absorption. The clinical consequences stem from the mechanical pressure of the excess fluid, which can damage brain tissue and dangerously elevate intracranial pressure.</p>",
