      "definition": "<p>The administration of <b>succinylcholine</b>, a depolarizing neuromuscular blocker, can cause a transient but potentially life-threatening <i>hyperkalemia</i>, not hypercalcemia. This effect is exaggerated in patients with certain underlying conditions.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Hyperkalemia:</b> Succinylcholine is an acetylcholine receptor agonist. Its binding to nicotinic receptors on the motor endplate causes a sustained depolarization, which leads to an efflux of potassium (K<sup>+</sup>) from muscle cells.</li><li><b>Normal Response:</b> In healthy individuals, this results in a small, clinically insignificant rise in serum K<sup>+</sup> (approx. 0.5 mEq/L).</li><li><b>Exaggerated Response:</b> In patients with upregulation of acetylcholine receptors (e.g., burns, crush injuries, denervating injuries, myopathies), succinylcholine can cause a massive K<sup>+</sup> release, leading to severe, life-threatening <mark>hyperkalemia</mark> and cardiac arrest.</li><li><b>Hypercalcemia Note:</b> Succinylcholine is a trigger for [[429af8bd|malignant hyperthermia]], a condition involving massive release of <i>calcium</i> from the sarcoplasmic reticulum, but it does not directly cause serum hypercalcemia. The primary electrolyte concern with succinylcholine itself is hyperkalemia.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Succinylcholine is contraindicated in patients with major burns, crush injuries, or upper motor neuron disease due to the risk of severe hyperkalemia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Succinylcholine's depolarizing action at the neuromuscular junction invariably causes a potassium efflux from muscle cells; while normally benign, this effect becomes dangerously amplified in conditions with receptor upregulation, posing a significant risk of fatal hyperkalemia.</p>",
