      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Occurs when the eye is either too short (axial hyperopia) or the cornea/lens system has too little refractive power (refractive hyperopia).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients can see distant objects clearly but have difficulty with near-vision tasks like reading. Young patients may be able to compensate by accommodating, but this can lead to eye strain and headaches.</li><li><b>Correction:</b> Corrected with a <mark>convex (converging) lens</mark> (e.g., glasses or contact lenses with a positive diopter prescription). The converging lens adds refractive power, moving the focal point forward onto the retina.</li><li><b>Distinction from Presbyopia:</b> While both cause blurry near vision, hyperopia is a refractive error present from a young age, whereas [[767d985e|presbyopia]] is an age-related loss of accommodation.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the correction: <b>H</b>yperopia (farsightedness) is corrected with a con<b>vex</b> lens.</li></ul>",
