      "definition": "<p><b>Hyperprolactinemia</b> is a condition of elevated serum prolactin levels, which can be caused by physiological states, medications, or pathological conditions such as a prolactin-secreting pituitary adenoma (prolactinoma).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Physiology:</b> Prolactin secretion from the anterior pituitary is tonically inhibited by [[90adc821|dopamine]] from the hypothalamus (via the tuberoinfundibular pathway).</li><li><b>Prolactinoma:</b> The most common type of functional [[5f3188bd|pituitary adenoma]]. It autonomously secretes prolactin.</li><li><b>Drug-Induced:</b> Many drugs can cause hyperprolactinemia by blocking dopamine's inhibitory effect. These include most <mark>antipsychotics</mark> (dopamine D2 receptor antagonists) and metoclopramide.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation (Women):</b> Galactorrhea (milky nipple discharge), amenorrhea, and infertility (as high prolactin inhibits GnRH release).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation (Men):</b> Decreased libido, impotence, and gynecomastia.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> The first-line treatment for prolactinomas is a <mark>dopamine agonist</mark> (e.g., cabergoline, bromocriptine), which shrinks the tumor and normalizes prolactin levels.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Any drug that blocks dopamine receptors can cause hyperprolactinemia and its associated symptoms. This is a common side effect of antipsychotic medications.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Hyperprolactinemia</b> is most often a result of either a prolactin-secreting tumor or a disruption of the normal dopaminergic inhibition of the pituitary, leading to a classic triad of galactorrhea, amenorrhea, and infertility.</p>",
