      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Long-standing hypertension leads to degenerative changes in the walls of small, penetrating arteries and arterioles in the brain, a process called lipohyalinosis. This weakens the vessel walls, leading to the formation of <mark>Charcot-Bouchard microaneurysms</mark>.</li><li><b>Mechanism of Bleed:</b> Rupture of these microaneurysms is the primary cause of hypertensive intraparenchymal hemorrhage.</li><li><b>Common Locations:</b> The bleeds typically occur in deep brain structures supplied by these small penetrating arteries. The most common sites, in order of frequency, are the <mark>basal ganglia (putamen)</mark>, thalamus, pons, and cerebellum.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Sudden onset of focal neurological deficits that progress over minutes to hours, often accompanied by headache, vomiting, and signs of increased ICP.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> An elderly patient with a history of poorly controlled hypertension who presents with a sudden focal deficit and signs of increased ICP has likely suffered a hypertensive intraparenchymal hemorrhage, most probably in the basal ganglia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Chronic <b>hypertension</b> relentlessly damages the brain's small, deep arteries, leading to the formation of fragile Charcot-Bouchard microaneurysms that are prone to rupture, causing devastating intraparenchymal hemorrhages in characteristic locations like the basal ganglia.</p>",
