  "549b012e": {
    "title": "Hypertensive Retinopathy",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Cardiology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Pathology"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Hypertensive retinopathy</b> is retinal vascular damage caused by chronically elevated systemic blood pressure. The severity of the findings on funduscopic examination often correlates with the severity and duration of the hypertension.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Chronic hypertension causes progressive arteriosclerosis of the retinal vessels. This leads to vessel wall thickening, narrowing of the lumen, and breakdown of the blood-retinal barrier.</li><li><b>Funduscopic Findings (Mild to Moderate):</b><br> - Arteriolar narrowing (copper wiring, silver wiring).<br> - <mark>Arteriovenous (AV) nicking</mark>: Venules appear to be compressed or 'nicked' where they are crossed by sclerotic arterioles.<br> - Flame-shaped hemorrhages and cotton-wool spots.</li><li><b>Funduscopic Findings (Severe/Malignant Hypertension):</b><br> - Hard exudates, often arranged in a star pattern around the macula (<mark>macular star</mark>).<br> - <mark>Papilledema</mark> (optic disc swelling), which indicates hypertensive emergency.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> The presence of hypertensive retinopathy is a marker for systemic end-organ damage from hypertension and is associated with an increased risk of stroke, myocardial infarction, and death.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> AV nicking is a classic funduscopic finding of chronic hypertension. The presence of papilledema in a hypertensive patient is a sign of malignant hypertension and is a medical emergency.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Hypertensive retinopathy</b> provides a direct window into the systemic effects of high blood pressure; the changes seen in the retinal arterioles, from AV nicking to papilledema, mirror the vascular damage occurring in the kidneys, heart, and brain.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
