  "0df5b928": {
    "title": "Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy and Friedreich Ataxia",
    "primaryType": "concept",
    "tags": [
      "Cardiology",
      "Neurology",
      "Genetics",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Cardiovascular",
      "Pathology",
      "Cardiomyopathy"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM)</b> is the most common cardiac manifestation and the leading cause of death in patients with <i>Friedreich Ataxia</i>, a progressive neurodegenerative disorder.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Friedreich Ataxia:</b> An autosomal recessive trinucleotide repeat (GAA) disorder in the frataxin gene, leading to mitochondrial dysfunction.</li><li><b>Cardiac Involvement:</b> Occurs in over 90% of patients with Friedreich Ataxia. Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is the most common pattern, characterized by concentric left ventricular hypertrophy.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Frataxin deficiency leads to mitochondrial iron accumulation and oxidative stress, which damages cardiomyocytes, causing fibrosis and hypertrophy.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients may be asymptomatic or present with dyspnea, chest pain, palpitations, or syncope. It is a major cause of mortality, often due to heart failure or arrhythmias.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of neurological symptoms (ataxia, loss of reflexes) and hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a young patient is highly suggestive of Friedreich Ataxia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The development of <b>hypertrophic cardiomyopathy</b> is an integral and life-limiting component of Friedreich Ataxia, demonstrating that the mitochondrial dysfunction caused by frataxin deficiency is a multisystem disorder that severely impacts high-energy organs like the heart and brain.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
