  "b080137e": {
    "title": "Therapeutic Hyperventilation",
    "primaryType": "procedure",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Critical Care",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "ICP Management"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Therapeutic hyperventilation</b> is a temporary measure used to acutely lower increased intracranial pressure (ICP) by inducing respiratory alkalosis, which causes cerebral vasoconstriction.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Increased ventilation (hyperventilation) 'blows off' CO<sub>2</sub>, leading to a decrease in arterial PCO<sub>2</sub> (hypocapnia). Cerebral blood flow is highly sensitive to PCO<sub>2</sub>. Hypocapnia causes cerebral <mark>vasoconstriction</mark>.</li><li><b>Effect on ICP:</b> Cerebral vasoconstriction reduces cerebral blood volume, which, according to the Monro-Kellie doctrine, leads to a rapid decrease in intracranial pressure.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used as a temporizing, life-saving measure in patients with acutely elevated ICP and signs of impending brain herniation (e.g., from severe traumatic brain injury or large intracranial hemorrhage).</li><li><b>Limitations:</b> The effect is transient (lasts for hours). Prolonged or excessive hyperventilation can be harmful, as the severe vasoconstriction may lead to cerebral ischemia. It is a bridge to more definitive treatments (e.g., surgical decompression, osmotic therapy).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the relationship: ‚ÜìPCO<sub>2</sub> ‚Üí Vasoconstriction ‚Üí ‚ÜìCerebral Blood Flow ‚Üí ‚ÜìICP. This is a key physiological principle in neurocritical care.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Therapeutic hyperventilation</b> is a powerful but temporary tool to combat dangerously high intracranial pressure, working by manipulating the potent effect of CO<sub>2</sub> on cerebral blood vessel tone to rapidly reduce intracranial blood volume.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
