  "4caf22d3": {
    "title": "Hypoglossal Nerve (CN XII)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Cranial Nerves"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Hypoglossal Nerve (CN XII)</b> is a purely motor cranial nerve that provides motor innervation to all the intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue, except for the palatoglossus (which is innervated by the vagus nerve).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Controls tongue movement, which is essential for speech articulation, swallowing, and manipulating food.</li><li><b>Origin:</b> Arises from the hypoglossal nucleus in the medulla and exits the skull through the hypoglossal canal.</li><li><b>Lesion Effects (LMN):</b> A lower motor neuron lesion of CN XII (affecting the nerve itself or its nucleus) causes ipsilateral tongue paralysis. On protrusion, the tongue will <mark>deviate toward the side of the lesion</mark> due to the unopposed action of the contralateral genioglossus muscle. Fasciculations and atrophy of the ipsilateral tongue will also be present.</li><li><b>Lesion Effects (UMN):</b> An upper motor neuron lesion (e.g., from a stroke) causes contralateral tongue weakness. On protrusion, the tongue will deviate <mark>away from the side of the cortical lesion</mark>.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the tongue deviation rule: LMN lesions cause the tongue to 'lick the wound' (deviate toward the lesion). UMN lesions cause the tongue to deviate away from the lesion.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Hypoglossal Nerve</b> is the primary driver of tongue movement, and the direction of tongue deviation upon protrusion is a classic and reliable sign for differentiating between an ipsilateral lower motor neuron lesion and a contralateral upper motor neuron lesion.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
