      "definition": "<p><b>Brain herniation syndromes</b> are life-threatening conditions where increased intracranial pressure forces brain tissue from one compartment into another, across rigid dural structures like the falx cerebri or tentorium cerebelli, or through the foramen magnum.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Subfalcine Herniation:</b> The cingulate gyrus herniates under the falx cerebri. Can compress the anterior cerebral artery, leading to contralateral leg weakness.</li><li><b>Uncal Herniation:</b> The uncus (medial temporal lobe) herniates across the tentorium cerebelli. Classically compresses CN III, causing a fixed, dilated pupil ('blown pupil') and a 'down and out' eye.</li><li><b>Central/Downward Transtentorial Herniation:</b> Caudal displacement of the diencephalon and brainstem. Can cause Duret hemorrhages (brainstem hemorrhages) and is often fatal.</li><li><b>Tonsillar Herniation:</b> The cerebellar tonsils herniate through the foramen magnum, compressing the medulla. This leads to cardiorespiratory arrest and death.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A unilaterally 'blown pupil' in a comatose patient with head trauma is a classic sign of uncal herniation compressing the ipsilateral oculomotor nerve.</li></ul>",
