    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Hippocampus</b> is a complex brain structure embedded deep in the medial temporal lobe. It is a major component of the [[73ace357|limbic system]] and plays a critical role in the consolidation of information from short-term memory to long-term memory, and in spatial navigation.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Essential for the formation of new <mark>declarative (explicit) memories</mark> (facts and events).</li><li><b>Lesion Effects:</b> Bilateral damage to the hippocampus results in profound <mark>anterograde amnesia</mark>, the inability to form new long-term memories. Remote memories and procedural memory (skills) are typically preserved.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> The hippocampus is one of the first regions of the brain to be affected in [[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]], which explains why memory loss is an early symptom. It is also highly vulnerable to hypoxic-ischemic injury.</li><li><b>Limbic System:</b> It is a key part of the Papez circuit, connecting to the [[f02cfaa1|mammillary bodies]] via the fornix.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The classic case of H.M., who had his hippocampi surgically removed to treat epilepsy, demonstrated the hippocampus's crucial role in forming new memories.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Hippocampus</b> acts as the brain's memory 'save button,' crucial for converting the experiences of the present moment into lasting declarative memories; its destruction leads to a state of being permanently stuck in the past, unable to form new personal or factual knowledge.</p>",
