    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>HIV-Associated Dementia (HAD)</b>, also known as AIDS dementia complex, is a subcortical dementia that occurs in the late stages of HIV infection, characterized by cognitive, motor, and behavioral abnormalities.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Caused by the HIV virus infecting CNS cells, primarily <mark>microglia and macrophages</mark>. Neurons are not directly infected but are damaged by inflammatory cytokines and viral proteins (e.g., gp120, Tat) released by infected glial cells.</li><li><b>Risk Factors:</b> Occurs in patients with advanced immunosuppression, typically with a <mark>CD4 count < 200 cells/mm¬≥</mark>.</li><li><b>Histopathology:</b> The pathognomonic finding is the presence of <mark>multinucleated giant cells</mark> (formed by the fusion of infected microglia) and microglial nodules in the white matter and deep gray matter structures.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> A subcortical dementia, it presents with cognitive slowing (bradyphrenia), memory problems, apathy, and social withdrawal. Motor symptoms include ataxia, poor balance, and tremors.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> The incidence and severity of HAD have dramatically decreased with the advent of effective antiretroviral therapy (ART).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The presence of multinucleated giant cells in the brain of an AIDS patient with dementia is the classic histological finding for HAD.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>HIV-Associated Dementia</b> is not caused by direct neuronal infection but rather by an inflammatory 'bystander effect,' where HIV-infected microglia release neurotoxic substances that damage neurons, leading to a characteristic subcortical dementia.</p>",
