    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Holoprosencephaly</b> is a severe congenital brain malformation resulting from the failure of the embryonic forebrain (prosencephalon) to divide into two distinct cerebral hemispheres during early gestation (weeks 3-4).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> A developmental field defect involving incomplete cleavage of the prosencephalon. It is associated with mutations in genes involved in the <mark>Sonic hedgehog (SHH)</mark> signaling pathway.</li><li><b>Spectrum of Severity:</b> Ranges from alobar (most severe, single ventricle and no hemispheric separation) to semilobar and lobar (less severe).</li><li><b>Associated Midline Facial Defects:</b> The severity of the brain malformation often correlates with the severity of midline facial defects. These can range from a single maxillary incisor or cleft lip/palate to severe anomalies like cyclopia (a single eye).</li><li><b>Associated Conditions:</b> Can be seen in genetic syndromes like <mark>Patau syndrome (Trisomy 13)</mark> and as a feature of fetal alcohol syndrome.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of a severe midline facial defect (like cyclopia or a single nostril) and a major brain malformation is characteristic of holoprosencephaly. Think of SHH pathway mutations and Trisomy 13.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Holoprosencephaly</b> is a fundamental failure of the brain to divide into left and right hemispheres, a process intimately linked to the development of the midline face, such that the 'face predicts the brain'‚Äîsevere facial anomalies often signal an underlying undivided brain.</p>",
