    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Homer-Wright rosettes</b> are a characteristic histological finding in several small round blue cell tumors, where tumor cells arrange themselves in a circular pattern around a central space filled with fibrillary material (neuropil).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Appearance:</b> A ring of small, dark tumor cell nuclei surrounding a central, eosinophilic, fibrillary core that is devoid of a blood vessel or lumen.</li><li><b>Associated Tumors:</b> They are a classic feature of several neuroblastic tumors, including:<br> - <mark>Medulloblastoma</mark>: The most common malignant pediatric brain tumor.<br> - <mark>Neuroblastoma</mark>: A common extracranial solid tumor of childhood, arising from neural crest cells.<br> - Pineoblastoma and Ewing sarcoma (less commonly).</li><li><b>Distinction from Other Rosettes:</b><br> - <b>Flexner-Wintersteiner rosettes:</b> Have a true central lumen; seen in retinoblastoma.<br> - <b>Perivascular pseudorosettes:</b> Tumor cells are arranged around a central blood vessel; seen in ependymomas.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The presence of Homer-Wright rosettes in a cerebellar tumor from a child is pathognomonic for [[16d613bb|medulloblastoma]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Homer-Wright rosettes</b> are a histological sign of primitive neuroblastic differentiation, where undifferentiated tumor cells attempt to form a rudimentary synapse-like structure, creating a distinctive circular pattern that is a key diagnostic feature of tumors like medulloblastoma and neuroblastoma.</p>",
