    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Homunculus</b> (Latin for \"little man\") is a distorted, topographic representation of the human body located in the primary motor cortex and the primary somatosensory cortex. The disproportionate size of body parts in the homunculus reflects the density of innervation and functional importance of those areas.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Motor Homunculus:</b> Located in the precentral gyrus (frontal lobe). Represents the origin of the corticospinal tracts. Areas with fine motor control, like the <mark>hands and face</mark>, have a very large representation.</li><li><b>Sensory Homunculus:</b> Located in the postcentral gyrus (parietal lobe). Represents the termination of sensory pathways. Areas with high tactile sensitivity, like the <mark>lips and fingertips</mark>, have a very large representation.</li><li><b>Somatotopic Arrangement:</b> The body is represented in an upside-down and inverted fashion. The feet and legs are located on the medial surface of the hemisphere, while the trunk, arm, hand, and face are located along the lateral convexity.</li><li><b>Vascular Supply and Clinical Correlation:</b> This arrangement is clinically significant for localizing strokes:<br> - <mark>Anterior Cerebral Artery (ACA) stroke:</mark> Affects the medial cortex, causing contralateral leg and foot deficits.<br> - <mark>Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA) stroke:</mark> Affects the lateral cortex, causing contralateral face and arm deficits.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The vascular supply of the homunculus is a very high-yield concept for stroke localization questions.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Homunculus</b> is a neural map that illustrates the brain's prioritization of function over physical size, with the vast cortical real estate devoted to the hands and face underscoring their critical roles in motor dexterity and sensory perception.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
