      "definition": "<p>A <b>hordeolum</b>, commonly known as a stye, is an acute, painful, purulent inflammation of an eyelid gland, typically caused by a bacterial infection.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Types:</b><br> - <b>External Hordeolum:</b> An infection of a sebaceous gland of Zeis or an apocrine gland of Moll, located at the eyelid margin. This is the more common type.<br> - <b>Internal Hordeolum:</b> An infection of a meibomian gland, located within the tarsal plate of the eyelid.</li><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly caused by an infection with <mark>Staphylococcus aureus</mark>.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> A localized, <mark>painful</mark>, red, swollen lump on or within the eyelid. It may have a central point of pus (pustule).</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> The mainstay of treatment is warm compresses to promote drainage. Topical antibiotics may be used. Incision and drainage may be required if it does not resolve.</li><li><b>Distinction from Chalazion:</b> A [[chalazion]] is a granulomatous inflammation of a meibomian gland, not an acute infection. It is typically <mark>painless</mark>, harder, and located further from the eyelid margin than an external hordeolum.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The key differentiating feature between a hordeolum and a chalazion is pain. Hordeolum = <b>H</b>urts. Chalazion = <b>C</b>hronic and non-tender.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>hordeolum</b> is essentially a small abscess of an eyelid gland, presenting as a tender, red bump, which distinguishes it from the painless, chronic granulomatous nodule of a chalazion.</p>",
