    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Horner syndrome</b> is a clinical triad of symptoms resulting from the disruption of the oculosympathetic pathway, which provides sympathetic innervation to the eye and face.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Classic Triad:</b><br>1. <b>Ptosis:</b> Mild drooping of the upper eyelid due to paralysis of the superior tarsal muscle.<br>2. <b>Miosis:</b> A constricted pupil due to unopposed parasympathetic tone to the sphincter pupillae muscle.<br>3. <b>Anhidrosis:</b> Decreased sweating on the ipsilateral side of the face.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Caused by a lesion anywhere along the three-neuron [[84b5e4f6|oculosympathetic pathway]]:<br> - <b>First-order (Central):</b> Brainstem stroke (e.g., [[07656b4a|lateral medullary syndrome]]), spinal cord lesion above T1 (e.g., [[4792bc68|Brown-S√©quard syndrome]], syringomyelia).<br> - <b>Second-order (Preganglionic):</b> A <mark>Pancoast tumor</mark> (apical lung tumor) compressing the sympathetic chain.<br> - <b>Third-order (Postganglionic):</b> Carotid artery dissection (painful Horner's), [[9a089fd7|cavernous sinus syndrome]].</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> Can be confirmed with pharmacological eye drop tests (e.g., apraclonidine, cocaine).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A smoker presenting with shoulder pain, arm weakness, and the triad of ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis likely has a Pancoast tumor causing Horner syndrome.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Horner syndrome</b> is the clinical manifestation of a sympathetic blackout to one side of the face, and its presence should trigger a search for an underlying lesion along the long and vulnerable oculosympathetic pathway, from the hypothalamus down to the chest and back up to the eye.</p>",
