    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Hunger and satiety regulation</b> is a complex homeostatic process controlled primarily by the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]], which integrates peripheral hormonal signals from the gut and adipose tissue with central neuronal circuits to control food intake and energy expenditure.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Hypothalamic Centers:</b><br> - <b>Lateral Nucleus:</b> The <mark>hunger center</mark>. Stimulation induces hunger. It is inhibited by leptin and stimulated by ghrelin. Lesion ‚Üí anorexia. <br> - <b>Ventromedial Nucleus:</b> The <mark>satiety center</mark>. Stimulation induces satiety. It is stimulated by leptin. Lesion ‚Üí hyperphagia and obesity.</li><li><b>Key Hormones (Peripheral):</b><br> - <b>[[c8515469|Leptin]]:</b> Secreted by adipose tissue; signals satiety (long-term).<br> - <b>Ghrelin:</b> Secreted by the stomach; stimulates hunger (short-term).<br> - <b>Insulin:</b> Secreted by the pancreas; signals satiety.<br> - <b>CCK:</b> Secreted by the duodenum; signals satiety.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the opposing roles of the hypothalamic nuclei: <b>L</b>ateral nucleus makes you <b>L</b>ean (lesion). <b>V</b>entro<b>m</b>edial nucleus makes you <b>V</b>ery <b>M</b>assive (lesion).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The regulation of <b>hunger and satiety</b> is a delicate balance orchestrated by the hypothalamus, which acts as a central processor for a host of peripheral signals like leptin and ghrelin to ensure energy homeostasis.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Lateral Hypothalamus] --Stimulates--> B(Hunger); C[Ventromedial Hypothalamus] --Stimulates--> D(Satiety); E(Ghrelin) --> A; F(Leptin) --Inhibits--> A; F --> C;"
