      "Pathology",
      "Neurodegenerative Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Huntington Disease</b> is an autosomal dominant neurodegenerative disorder characterized by a triad of motor, cognitive, and psychiatric symptoms, caused by an expansion of a CAG trinucleotide repeat in the huntingtin (<i>HTT</i>) gene.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Genetics:</b> Autosomal dominant inheritance with <mark>anticipation</mark> (disease becomes more severe and appears at an earlier age in successive generations). Caused by a CAG trinucleotide repeat expansion on chromosome 4. Mnemonic: <b>C</b>audate loses <b>A</b>Ch and <b>G</b>ABA.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Degeneration of GABAergic neurons in the <mark>caudate and putamen</mark> (striatum). This leads to atrophy of the striatum, visible on imaging as enlargement of the lateral ventricles.</li><li><b>Neurotransmitter Changes:</b> Marked decrease in [[5aa5cb91|GABA]] and [[6a005559|acetylcholine]], with a relative excess of [[90adc821|dopamine]].</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Onset typically between ages 30-50. Presents with <mark>chorea</mark> (involuntary, dance-like movements), progressing to dementia and psychiatric disturbances (depression, aggression).</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> There is no cure. Symptomatic treatment for chorea includes dopamine antagonists (e.g., haloperidol) or VMAT inhibitors (e.g., tetrabenazine).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient in their 40s with new-onset chorea and personality changes should make you think of Huntington disease. The key pathology is atrophy of the caudate nucleus.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Huntington Disease</b> is a fatal genetic disorder where an expanded CAG repeat leads to the progressive destruction of GABAergic neurons in the striatum, resulting in a devastating clinical triad of uncontrollable movements (chorea), cognitive decline (dementia), and psychiatric illness.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[CAG Repeat Expansion in HTT Gene] --> B(Gain-of-Function Huntingtin Protein); B --> C(Degeneration of Striatal Neurons); C --> D(Decreased GABA & ACh); D --> E(Chorea, Dementia, Psychiatric Symptoms);"
    },
